<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fringe Sports Shine at Pan Am Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Water skiing, racquetball, roller  
skating. Sounds like a day at Club Med, but it's actually the Pan 
American Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Looking for some exposure as well as some legitimacy, six  
non-Olympic sports joined such stalwarts as basketball, boxing and 
track in the sports lineup at Winnipeg. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Asian Games can have kabaddi (full-contact tag) and sepak  
takraw (foot volleyball), the Pan Ams can have bowling and squash. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a perception amongst the public of a weekend  
cottager, have a few beers, go out on weekends and have some fun,'' 
said Ross Outerbridge, who chairs the High Performance Committee of 
Water Ski Canada. ``One thing that is difficult is to convince 
people of the perception of how difficult it is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Each Olympics usually reserves some place for a local sport or  
activity. But these competitors are more than weekend warriors. In 
nearly every sport, a pro circuit exists in which the top 
performers can earn more than $100,000 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Nor are these sports free of drug controversies. Canadian roller  
hockey goaltender Steve Vezina tested positive for three banned 
substances, including an anabolic steroid, and cost his country the 
gold medal at these Pan Ams. 
</P>
<P>
	The six non-Olympic sports contested at Winnipeg are: water  
skiing, racketball, roller sports, bowling, squash and karate. 
</P>
<P>
	In many cases, these sports struggle with their image. Take  
bowling, which conjures visions of middle-aged men in loud, loose 
shirts, smoking and drinking beer, 
</P>
<P>
	``I always tell our guys: `The best thing about your sport is  
everybody can do it. The worst thing about your sport is, everybody 
can do it,''' said Marc Whitney, press officer for the U.S. bowling 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	Roller skating is stuck with an image of bikini-clad women  
gliding along Venice Beach in California. 
</P>
<P>
	``True, but how many times to do you see a highly trained  
athlete going backward down the street with a boom box on his 
shoulder?'' asked Maxine McKenzie, Canada's roller sports team 
leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly all thse competitors realize this is their chance to  
shine. 
</P>
<P>
	``Walking around the (athletes) village I haven't seen anybody  
who isn't excited,'' Canada racquetball coach Ron Brown said. ``But 
we're doubly excited.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If nothing else, the Pan Ams offer a rare chance for officials  
of the fringe sports to lobby IOC members. 
</P>
<P>
	International Bowling Federation president Jerry Koenig has been  
working for years to get his sport recognized by the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	He went so far as to hold a bowling party at the 1998 Winter  
Olympics in Nagano, Japan, where he challenged IOC president Juan 
Antonio Samaranch. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last time we bowled, he won one, and I won one,'' Koenig said.  
``We have handicapping in our sport, so I'm obligated to give him a 
few pins.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And if a sport wants to convince the IOC of its merits, this is  
the time and place. In 1995, in the Pan Am Games in Argentina, 
water skiing was held some 500 miles from the main sites. 
</P>
<P>
	``Having the sport within the city limits, within access of the  
fans, the media, the officials is tremendous for us,'' said 
Outerbridge of Water Ski Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	The Athens Olympic Organizing Committee has proposed adding  
water skiing for the 2004 Games. Of course, it's also asked the IOC 
to consider fin swimming, in which racers don a mermaidlike tail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
