<DOCNO> APW19990804.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 18:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan May Leave Republican Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pat Buchanan, the pugnacious conservative  
whose insurgent presidential campaigns hobbled Republican 
front-runners in 1992 and 1996, is considering bolting to the 
Reform Party, officials said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	A major factor in his decision, which is not expected until the  
fall, will be the results of an Aug. 14 contest in Iowa testing the 
political strength of nine Republican presidential candidates, said 
officials close to Buchanan and in the Reform Party. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials, all of whom spoke on condition of anonymity, said  
Buchanan is worried that the Republican nomination process is 
geared in favor of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, and that he has 
little chance of winning or even pushing his social and economic 
issues to the forefront of the debate. 
</P>
<P>
	They say the candidate's sister, Bay Buchanan, has talked  
informally to a Reform Party official in recent weeks about a 
possible move. Such a step would be personally difficult for the 
former Nixon White House aide because of his long ties to the 
Republican Party, the officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders worry that a Buchanan defection would drain  
support of the GOP's most conservative voters from the party's 
eventual nominee. Already, conservative Sen. Bob Smith of New 
Hampshire has abandoned the Republican Party for a third-party run 
at the White House. Buchanan defended him against criticism from 
GOP leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the party that stands for the conservative principles  
that Pat Buchanan has articulated so well throughout his life,'' 
Republican National Committee spokesman Mike Collins said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rumors have circulated for weeks that Buchanan may switch  
parties, and his campaign has refused to rule out the option. 
Interviews Wednesday with a half dozen officials familiar with the 
discussions produced the strongest evidence yet that Buchanan is 
seriously considering the move. 
</P>
<P>
	In a little-noticed television interview last month, Buchanan  
complained that the GOP establishment had decided that he was not a 
viable candidate. ``If they slam those doors shut,'' he warned, 
``we'll just have to look for another way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Associates said the interview was a warning that Buchanan was  
willing to abandon his party. 
</P>
<P>
	More recently, his sister talked with Pat Choate, a family  
friend and 1996 Reform Party vice presidential candidate, about the 
possibility of Buchanan leaving the GOP. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan declined to return telephone calls. His sister said the  
candidate was focused on the Iowa straw vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has been no further development whatsoever'' since the  
TV interview ``when Pat said quite clearly that he will follow his 
ideas,'' Bay Buchanan said in a telephone interview from Montana, 
where she is vacationing. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan would not be assured of the presidential nomination in  
the fractious Reform Party. Backers of Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura 
have wrested the party leadership from associates of party founder 
Ross Perot. 
</P>
<P>
	While Perot supporters such as Choate and past chairman Russell  
Verney would welcome Buchanan to the party, Ventura has been cool 
to the idea. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reform Party nominee will have access to more than $12  
million in federal funding, millions more than Buchanan is expected 
to raise as a GOP candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Bay Buchanan's discussion with Choate took place shortly after  
the July 23 Reform Party convention. She left no doubt that 
Buchanan may leave the GOP if he isn't satisfied with the 
nominating process, according to two people well versed on the 
conversation,. 
</P>
<P>
	They described the conversation as informal, part of a long  
series of discussions between friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan still hopes to do well in the GOP-sponsored Iowa straw  
poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Though non-binding, the contest could determine the fate of  
Buchanan and other second-tier candidates including former Vice 
President Dan Quayle and former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander. 
</P>
<P>
	A poor showing would weaken Buchanan's standing in the GOP  
field, raising questions about whether he continue the Republican 
race, close down the campaign or seek the Reform Party nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan, who left CNN to launch his third presidential campaign  
in March, is a fiery orator with a potent blend of politics: He is 
conservative on social issues yet appeals to populist instincts on 
economic matter such as trade. 
</P>
<P>
	He beat eventual nominee Bob Dole in the New Hampshire primary  
four years ago and put a scare into President Bush in 1992, 
finishing a close second. 
</P>
<P>
	Both times, Buchanan soon ran out of money and votes.  
</P>
<P>
	This year's campaign is a pale imitation of his past efforts. He  
is drawing smaller crowds, working with a staff that is smaller and 
less experienced and, at times, appears to be just going through 
the paces on the stump. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
