<DOCNO> APW19990804.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 16:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steelers Hope To Restore QB Stewart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LATROBE, Pa. (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Steelers are doing a lot of  
construction work these days, and not all of it is taking place at 
their new stadium site. 
</P>
<P>
	They're also trying to rebuild a quarterback.  
</P>
<P>
	The restoration of Kordell Stewart began last winter, deep in  
the midsection of Three Rivers Stadium's windowless coaching 
offices. They started with a series of get-acquainted meetings with 
new offensive coordinator Kevin Gilbride, then progressed into 
on-field sessions aimed not just at restoring Stewart's on-field 
ingenuity, but also his confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of all, his confidence.  
</P>
<P>
	Stewart wasn't the same quarterback in 1998 that he was in 1997,  
when he led the Steelers to within four points of the Super Bowl in 
his first season as a starter. Small wonder the Steelers weren't 
the same team, missing the playoffs for the first time since 1991 
with a 7-9 record and losing their final five games. 
</P>
<P>
	Exit former offensive coordinator Ray Sherman, who now finds  
himself running the NFL's most prolific offense in Minnesota. Enter 
Gilbride, a former NFL head coach and offensive coordinator whose 
success -- or failure -- will be determined largely by Kordell 
Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	The progress report one week into training camp: nothing  
dramatic yet, but everything seems on course. 
</P>
<P>
	``You start off pretty much with the basics and, at this point,  
you're running the plays everybody is familiar with,'' Stewart said 
Wednesday. ``As times progress, you start adding things here and 
there, and that's when the mind starts scrambling for some air.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That Stewart is scrambling at all is a sign the offense has  
changed. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Sherman restricted Stewart's propensity for rolling  
out of the pocket and creating on the fly, partly to cut down on 
interceptions. Stewart was restricted mostly to the pocket, a 
quarterback forced to rely more on his ability to read defenses and 
much less on his improvisational skills. 
</P>
<P>
	To say it was a dismal failure would be an understatement.  
</P>
<P>
	One season after producing 32 touchdowns, 21 on passes and 11 on  
runs, he threw for 11 touchdowns and ran for two, a nearly 
two-thirds dropoff in touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Gilbride is in the process of opening up the offense by  
allowing Stewart and his receivers to adjust and react as a play is 
developing. The system demands that a quarterback and his receivers 
always be on the same wavelength, but also creates the possibility 
of more big plays. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the Steelers had only one scoring pass play longer  
than 50 yards all season. With no fear the Steelers would strike 
for a big play, defenses stacked the line of scrimmage to contain 
the run, causing Jerome Bettis' yardage to drop from 1,665 yards in 
1997 to 1,185 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a scrimmage Tuesday against the Washington Redskins,  
Stewart found first-round draft choice Troy Edwards open several 
times for big yardage. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a long way from being perfect,'' Gilbride said. ``There  
were a lot of mistakes, but there were a lot of good plays. I 
thought Kordell threw the ball well and made some pretty good 
reads. Some receivers stepped up big and made some big catches for 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards' legs may not yet be in top condition -- he quickly ran  
out of gas during wind sprints last week -- but there is nothing 
wrong with his hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Bill Cowher quickly picked up on how Stewart and his  
receivers seem to be acclimating themselves to Gilbride's system. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a real comfort level that is taking place,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	That in itself is a major change, considering how uncomfortable  
Stewart seemed last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``The receivers are doing more reading, giving the quarterback  
more of an opportunity to make some plays,'' Stewart said. 
``Whatever coverage they get, they can do whatever they want. They 
can work inside, they can work outside, there is a lot going on 
right now. So you will see more of a flashier offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pretty soon, it will be an automatic thing and, once that time  
comes, that's when everything will be rolling real smooth.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
