<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 15:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knee Sidelines Jets' Eric Green </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. -- For Bill Parcells, finding a fourth receiver  
is a minor hurdle. Sifting through the roster for pass-rusher is a 
test of patience. But Eric Green's knee is a problem. 
</P>
<P>
	After five straight days of two-a-day workouts, the veteran  
tight end was excused from training-camp sessions Tuesday afternoon 
and Wednesday with a sore left knee. The development had New York 
Jets coach Parcells sounding an alarm bell. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Eric Green can't play, we're going to have big problems,''  
Parcells said. ``It would impact us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The former two-time Pro Bowler, who signed a four-year, $7.5  
million free-agent contract with the Jets during the offseason, is 
being counted on to fill the void created when Kyle Brady left for 
the Jacksonville Jaguars. Green, 32, underwent arthroscopic surgery 
on his knee following last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the Jets nor Green would reveal the exact nature of the  
problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just one of those knees that's been around a long time,''  
said Green, who played with Baltimore the past three seasons. In 
that span, he stressed, the Ravens never required him to take part 
in two-a-day workouts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm new, and this is something I wanted to gauge and see how  
(the knee) responds,'' Green said. ``It's not all bad, though. I 
got some great things down at camp. These guys need to learn what 
kind of player I really am.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parcells would like that, too, but is frustrated to find Green  
already sidelined in pain. Neither Fred Baxter nor Lawrence Hart, 
backups to Green, have wowed the Jets staff thus far in workouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Green, who made the Pro Bowl in 1993 and 1994 with the  
Pittsburgh Steelers, missed four games last season with injuries, 
most unrelated to the knee. He finished with 422 yards on 34 
catches, with one touchdown. Over the past two seasons, he has 99 
receptions for 1,023 yards and six scores. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets hope that the 6-5, 279-pound veteran becomes more of a  
downfield receiving threat than Brady, and provides a powerful 
blocking presence for running back Curtis Martin. Parcells admits 
to being worried, however. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no choice,'' Parcells said of keeping Green off the  
field. ``It's going to make him dysfunctional if I keep going. So, 
I'll give him a couple of days off. 
</P>
<P>
	Green, who continually downplayed his knee problems Wednesday,  
declined to reveal how many surgeries have been performed on the 
troublesome joint. 
</P>
<P>
	Parcells admitted that the team knew Green was battling a  
long-standing knee problem, but, ``I didn't know it was quite like 
this.'' If the tight end is unavailable, ``There's nobody out there 
to look for,'' the coach added. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're making a bit of a mountain here, though. If he's still  
not practicing two weeks from now, then we'll definitely have 
problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Green doesn't see that happening.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's getting better,'' he said. ``I'm going to have days like  
this. I don't see any long-term effects. I'm not worried at all.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
