<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Fall in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell early Thursday, pushed down by  
a decline on Wall Street and the dollar's slide against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 114.38 yen, down 0.72 yen from late Wednesday  
in Tokyo but above its late New York level of 114.29 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average 214.75 points, or  
1.21 percent, to 17,470.63 in the first 30 minutes of trading. On 
Wednesday, the average closed down 284.55 points, or 1.58 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Among early losers were high-technology issues and blue chips,  
including Sony, TDK, NEC and Toyota Motor. They were sold in line 
with falls in the technology-rich U.S. Nasdaq composite index, 
which dropped 47.99 points to 2,540.00 at Wednesday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average lost  
2.54 points to 10,674.77. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors in Tokyo were also discouraged by the yen's strength  
against the greenback. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen reduces the profits of Japanese exporters by  
making their products more expensive abroad and less competitive, 
while reducing their dollar-denominated revenues when translated 
into yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Comments from U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers gave the  
dollar an early boost to 114.57 yen earlier in the session, but 
U.S. funds stepped in to take profits, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with the BBC late Wednesday, Summers reiterated  
America's strong dollar policy, but there was no specific 
suggestion that U.S.-Japan joint dollar-buying intervention in 
currency markets was planned. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 14.97 points, or 1.03 percent, to 1,444.70. 
The TOPIX closed down 22.32 points, or 1.51 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 122.98 yen, down  
from 124.12 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.8500 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.8850 percent, 
driving its price up to 99.57 yen from 99.27 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
