<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Close Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices closed lower today mainly on  
selling of shares in large Japanese exporters. The dollar declined 
against the yen in late-afternoon trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 284.55 points,  
or 1.58 percent, to close at 17,685.38. On Tuesday, the average 
finished up 144.23 points, or 0.81 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 115.10 yen at late-afternoon, down 0.30 yen  
from late Tuesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level 
of 115.28 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices fell on continued investor concern  
that the yen's strength against the dollar will hurt Japanese 
exporters, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	A higher yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad and  
thus less competitive, and reduces the dollar-denominated earnings 
of Japanese exporters when translated into yen. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors are worried that the yen may continue to  
strengthen,'' said Hideyuki Okoshi, deputy manager at Chuo 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The overnight plunge in the Nasdaq Composite Index also weighed  
on Tokyo stocks today. The Index tumbled 35.64 points to 2,587.99 
Tuesday in the U.S. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section closed down 22.32 points, or 1.51 percent, to 
1,459.67. The TOPIX closed up 13.37 points, or 0.91 percent, the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the First Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was  
estimated at 472.32 million shares, down from 490.50 million shares 
on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Retreating issues outnumbered advancing stocks 839 to 361 while  
116 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, traders sold the dollar, ignoring hints  
from Japan's government that it may carry out dollar-buying 
intervention. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will think of appropriate measures at every turn of  
events,'' Zembei Mizoguchi, director-general of the international 
bureau at Japan's Ministry of Finance, told reporters today. 
</P>
<P>
	Expectations of intervention emerged after Finance Minister  
Kiichi Miyazawa and U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers agreed 
in phone talks Tuesday that they will maintain close ties on 
foreign exchange policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said, however, that there has been no indication of any  
joint intervention since the two officials spoke the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent months, the Bank of Japan has bought dollars to stop  
the yen's rise against the greenback, an action meant to help the 
country's nascent economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 124.12 yen, up from  
123.08 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.8900 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.8800 
percent, driving its price down to 99.23 yen from 99.32 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
