<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suns Close To Deal for Hardaway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The Phoenix Suns are closing in on a deal with  
would bring Penny Hardaway from the Orlando Magic in a 
sign-and-trade arrangement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Suns have intensified conversations with the Magic and  
Hardaway just as other NBA teams, including the Los Angeles Lakers 
and Toronto Raptors, have backed off. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida Today quoted Magic general manager John Gabriel as  
saying the Suns' deal is ``the only trade left out there.'' The 
remaining option for Orlando would be to try to keep Hardaway with 
the Magic to play for new coach Doc Rivers. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway was in Phoenix last Friday and Saturday, met with team  
officials, and played golf with coach Danny Ainge. 
</P>
<P>
	Phoenix radio station KMGE reported Tuesday night that the deal  
was completed, but Suns president Jerry Colangelo said nothing was 
final. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be premature to say anything about a deal that's  
done,'' Colangelo said late Tuesday night. ``We've had a lot of 
conversation with his agent and with Orlando, but I can't confirm 
to you that a deal is done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reports that the deal was imminent surfaced in Arizona and  
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orlando Sentinal and The Tribune of Mesa reported that the  
Suns would send Pat Garrity, Danny Manning and two draft picks to 
the Magic in exchange for Hardaway. The Arizona Republic quoted 
league sources and a source close to Hardaway as saying he has told 
the Suns he wants to play in Phoenix and has agreed to contract 
terms. 
</P>
<P>
	The Magic want a sign-and-trade deal, even one that might not  
bring the kind of value they think Hardaway is worth, in order to 
get some compensation for losing the four-time all-star guard. 
</P>
<P>
	A sign-and-trade deal is the only way the Suns could get  
Hardaway, because they have no room under the salary cap to sign 
him outright as a free agent, a situation similar to most other 
teams in the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	The 28-year-old guard has averaged 19 points in his six NBA  
seasons, but dropped to 15.8 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Orlando is in the midst of a roster overhaul under new coach Doc  
Rivers. The Magic traded Nick Anderson to Sacramento on Tuesday for 
Tariq Abdul-Wahad and a first-round draft pick. 
</P>
<P>
	According to The Tribune, while Hardaway was in Phoenix,  
Colangelo presented him with a set of golf clubs in a purple golf 
bag with Hardaway's name and the Phoenix Suns stitched into it. 
It's the kind of gesture Colangelo is known for in his successful 
attempts to attract athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers removed themselves from the Hardaway sweepstakes when  
they reached a seven-year, $30 million agreement with Derek Fisher. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
