<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Korean IOC Member Mum on Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A powerful South Korean Olympic  
official refused to comment today on a criminal case implicating 
his son in Salt Lake City's bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	A businessman pleaded guilty to tax fraud Tuesday, saying he  
helped the son of Kim Un-yong, an executive member of the 
International Olympic Committee, obtain lawful permanent resident 
status by setting up a sham job at his now-defunct communications 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Kim Un-yong cannot comment until he reviews all the  
details on the case,'' his chief secretary, Baek Sung-il, said. 
``But he is not too concerned about the latest development.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The secretary distributed copies of a statement Kim's American  
lawyer, Howard Graff, issued right after the guilty plea in the 
first criminal case stemming from the U.S. federal investigation 
into Salt Lake City's winning bid for the 2002 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is indeed unfortunate that by implication, Dr. Kim has once  
again been dragged into a story concerning the alleged misdeeds of 
others,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	David E. Simmons, the businessman, has admitted that he used  
fake contracts and phony invoices to conceal the fact that John 
Kim's salary was being paid by the Salt Lake City Olympic bid 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The goal, he said, was to win support for the city's quest for  
the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim, a member of the IOC's ruling executive board and president  
of an international confederation of Olympic sports, has denied any 
wrongdoing in the Salt Lake City scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	He has said that his son worked with Simmons on purely business  
terms and that he was unaware of any wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten IOC members either resigned or were expelled for receiving  
cash and other improper inducements from the Salt Lake City 
committee trying to win the right to hold the Olympics in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	An IOC probe ruled Kim's case as minor and closed the case with  
a ``severe warning'' to him. 
</P>
<P>
	Graff's statement said the arrangements for reimbursing Simmons  
by the bidders were kept secret from the family. Court documents 
released Tuesday offered no evidence that the elder Kim knew about 
the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	An IOC spokesman refused to comment, saying it would be  
``inappropriate'' because ``the proceedings are ongoing in the 
United States.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
