<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 13:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Korean IOC Member Reviewing Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A South Korean Olympic executive is  
not worried about tax fraud allegations that have touched on his 
son, arising out of the selection of Salt Lake City for the 2002 
Winter Olympics, a spokesman said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The case involving John Kim, the son of Kim Un-yong, is the  
first criminal prosecution by U.S. federal investigators over 
allegations that Salt Lake City officials illegally tried to 
influence Olympic delegates selecting the games' venue. 
</P>
<P>
	A businessman from Utah pleaded guilty to misdemeanor tax fraud  
Tuesday, admitting that he helped John Kim obtain permanent U.S. 
resident status by setting up a fake job at his now-defunct 
communications company. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Kim Un-yong cannot comment until he reviews all the  
details on the case,'' his chief secretary, Baek Sung-il, said in 
the South Korean capital, Seoul. ``But he is not too concerned 
about the latest development.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Kim, an IOC executive member, has denied any  
wrongdoing in the bidding scandal. He has previously said the money 
Simmons paid his son was for consulting and other services and had 
nothing to do with the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The businessman, David E. Simmons, has admitted that he used  
fake contracts and phony invoices to conceal the fact that John 
Kim's salary was being paid by the Salt Lake City Olympic Bid 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC official has said any deal between Simmons and the Salt  
Lake City bid committee was kept secret from his family. 
</P>
<P>
	The Salt Lake City scandal has never loomed large in South  
Korea, where senior government officials are routinely jailed on 
bribery charges. It has received little coverage in the news media. 
</P>
<P>
	President Kim Dae-jung's office said it was following Kim's case  
but there has been no probe or questioning by the South Korean 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC's own investigation in March gave Kim Un-yong a ``severe  
warning'' for his conduct, but stopped short of harsher sanctions 
in the inquiry that led to an unprecedented 10 expulsions or 
resignations. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim is an influential power broker in the IOC, and has been  
cited as a candidate to replace Juan Antonio Samaranch as IOC chief 
in 2001. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 10:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: No Excuse for Infidelity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today he makes no  
excuses for his marital infidelity, and neither does his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	It was his first public reaction to Hillary Rodham Clinton's  
much-discussed magazine interview, in which she drew an apparent 
link between the tumult of Clinton's childhood and what she 
described as his ``weakness'' and lack of self-control as an adult. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe that anybody could fairly read the article and  
think that she was making any excuses for me,'' Clinton said today. 
``I have not made any excuses for what was inexcusable, and neither 
has she, believe me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During a Senate campaign visit to Jamestown, N.Y., Mrs. Clinton  
said today that she did not mean to imply in the interview with 
Talk magazine that the president's childhood problems were to blame 
for his infidelity. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody is responsible for their behavior and I am a very  
strong proponent and believer in personal responsibility, so I hope 
that people will take that message away from this,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she believes that the country has put the issue behind  
it. ``I have as well,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``My husband and I love each other very much,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said today that thoughtful readers of the article will  
conclude ``that my wife is an extraordinary person,'' with an 
impressive record of public service, ``and that we love each other 
very much. 
</P>
<P>
	His comments came at the close of a Rose Garden appearance on  
economic themes, including the GOP-passed tax cut bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Looking pensive, Clinton spoke carefully about his childhood in  
Arkansas, which was marked by family discord. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't have a bed of roses as a kid,'' Clinton said. But he  
said he had what's most important for any youngster. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important thing is that every child needs to know  
growing up that he or she is the most important person in the world 
to someone,'' he said. ``And I knew that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I always knew that I was well-loved and I think that's  
important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Mrs. Clinton's spokeswoman, Marsha Barry, weighed in  
with a similar refrain. 
</P>
<P>
	``She did not say the president's childhood in any way caused  
his behavior, nor does she believe that,'' spokeswoman Marsha Barry 
said, seeking to clarify what Mrs. Clinton meant when she said in 
the magazine interview that her husband was ``scarred by abuse'' as 
a child. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, he has his weaknesses,'' Mrs. Clinton told the magazine.  
``Yes, he needs to be more responsible, more disciplined, but it is 
remarkable given his background that he turned out to be the kind 
of person he is, capable of such leadership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Expanding on her husband's background, Mrs. Clinton said what  
scarred him at age 4 was a struggle between his mother and 
grandmother. 
</P>
<P>
	``A psychologist once told me that for a boy being in the middle  
of a conflict between two women is the worst possible situation,'' 
she said. ``There is always a desire to please each one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's quotations were misinterpreted, Berry said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think that she was basically stating some feelings about his  
childhood, but that they do not excuse his behavior,'' Berry said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
