<HEADLINE> Tyson Visits Phoenix Inmates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Mike Tyson was back among the incarcerated -- but  
this time, he was just visiting. 
</P>
<P>
	The ex-inmate and former heavyweight champion was supposed to  
promote Maricopa County Sheriff Joe Arpaio's tent city, where 
approximately 1,000 nonviolent inmates serve their sentences in 
tents. 
</P>
<P>
	But the parolee was less than complimentary when he saw it.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's too much like slavery,'' Tyson said Tuesday when he saw  
a dozen inmates with their ankles chained together. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson then joked that he was ``proud to see an all-white chain  
gang'' for once. He later apologized. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson was recently released from a Maryland jail after serving a  
sentence for assaulting two motorists, and has served prison time 
in Indiana for rape. On Tuesday, he handed out doughnuts in 
100-degree weather to the inmates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most people come in here because they can't manage their  
lives,'' Tyson said. ``They need skills to cope with society.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the inmates asked Tyson to sign autographs on pieces of  
the doughnut boxes they ripped apart. 
</P>
