<HEADLINE> Briggs, Botha Talk a Good Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- Shannon Briggs sizes up Francois  
Botha as nothing more than a washed-up fighter. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're too slow, you have no power,'' he said Wednesday. ``You  
can't move your head. You fought all bums your whole career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two heavyweights, doing their best to pump pay-per-view and  
ticket sales with trash talk, meet in a 10-round nontitle fight 
Saturday at Trump Taj Mahal. 
</P>
<P>
	Botha, the former IBF heavyweight titleholder, didn't want to  
hear any of Briggs' opinions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't matter whether you bring all these guys (Briggs'  
corner men) in here to scare me. The baddest man on the planet 
couldn't do it. What makes you think you can?'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Botha, a 30-year-old South African living in Newport Beach,  
Calif., once fought three matches in one day. In 1992, he defeated 
Art Hooks, Russell Pierson and Mike Jones -- knocking each one out 
in the first round -- in Oklahoma City. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, he won the IBF title with a unanimous decision over  
Axel Schulz, but a month later the bout was ruled a no contest 
after Botha's drug test showed steroids. 
</P>
<P>
	More recently, he led Mike Tyson on all three judges' cards in  
the fifth round of their Jan. 26 bout. Tyson knocked him out with 
one punch to win it. His other loss was to Michael Moorer. 
</P>
<P>
	Botha (39-2), fighting for the first time since the Tyson bout,  
says Briggs has no endurance. 
</P>
<P>
	``He starts early and he burns out in the later rounds,'' Botha  
said. ``I want to get him tired, work the body and take him out 
later.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Briggs, a 27-year-old New Yorker, and Botha both want a shot at  
Tyson. Briggs also hopes for an eventual rematch with WBC champion 
Lennox Lewis, who stopped him in five rounds last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Briggs (31-2) hasn't fought since last December, when he scored  
a first-round TKO over Marcus Rhode. But he says he's in prime 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	This bout could be crossroads for both fighters.  
</P>
<P>
	``These two guys, neither one of them can afford to lose,'' said  
Emanuel Steward, Briggs' trainer. 
</P>
<P>
	``The winner has a great future in front of him,'' co-promoter  
Frank Warren said. ``And the loser has nowhere to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Each fighter will get $400,000. The bout will be carried on a 9  
p.m. pay-per-view telecast by Showtime Event Television. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
