<HEADLINE> Canucks Sign Free Agent Doug Bodger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- The Vancouver Canucks  
bolstered their young blueline, signing veteran Doug Bodger to a 
reported one-year contract on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	An unrestricted free agent, Bodger had three goals and 11  
assists in 65 games with the Los Angeles Kings last season. The 
33-year-old defenseman, who grew up on nearby Vancouver Island, 
reportedly signed a deal that will pay him $700,000 plus bonuses, 
almost half of the $1.3 million he made last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Doug is a solid player at the NHL level and he will add  
veteran leadership and depth to our defense,'' said Brian Burke, 
Canucks president and general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Bodger, who played his 1,000th career game last season, is  
entering his 16th NHL campaign and joining his sixth club after 
breaking into the league with Pittsburgh in 1984. An all-around 
player, Bodger's best offensive season came in 1992-'93 when he had 
nine goals and a career-high 45 assists in 81 games. 
</P>
<P>
	He is expected to help nurture the Canucks' young but promising  
defensive corps, which includes Ed Jovanovski, Mattias Ohlund and 
top prospect Bryan Allen. Murray Baron, 32, is the only other 
Canuck defenseman over 26 years of age. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate move Wednesday, the Canucks also signed free-agent  
right winger Martin Gendron. A journeyman with only 30 NHL games 
under his belt over five pro seasons, Gendron led the Montreal 
Canadiens' American Hockey League farm club in Fredericton, New 
Brunswick with 33 goals and 67 points in 65 games last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Gendron, 25, was Washington's fourth-round pick in the 1992  
draft, and played 20 games with the Capitals in 1995-'96. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
