<HEADLINE> Dixon Edwards Leaves Dolphins Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAVIE, Fla. (AP) -- Veteran linebacker Dixon Edwards left the  
Miami Dolphins today and may sit out the season because of an 
irregular heartbeat. 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards, a starter the past six years for the Dallas Cowboys and  
Minnesota Vikings, signed with Miami as a free agent in June. He 
participated in the first three training camp workouts last week 
before the heart ailment sidelined him. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has seen four different doctors and cardiologists, one in  
Dallas in February and three other doctors in South Florida,'' 
coach Jimmy Johnson said. ``All four have cleared him to practice 
and to play. All four have said he's got a healthy heart. For that 
reason, we're leaving the door open for him to return to the squad 
at a later date.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards, 31, met with Johnson today before leaving camp. He  
agreed to return his signing bonus, so there will be no salary-cap 
implications for the Dolphins. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has concerns,'' Johnson said. ``He will be working with a  
nutritionist to try to alleviate his concerns, and so he could have 
a change of mind here at a later date.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards has played for a playoff team in each of his eight NFL  
seasons. He was expected to challenge Derrick Rodgers for a 
starting job at outside linebacker. 
  	   	
</P>
