<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 07:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kellogg Co. To Introduce New Cereal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Coming soon to a breakfast bowl near you: a cereal that promises  
to deliver a super-dose of calcium. 
</P>
<P>
	Kellogg Co. was to introduce Wednesday its Special K Plus, a  
multi-grain, fruited cereal that, without milk, provides 600 
milligrams of calcium with every one-cup serving. 
</P>
<P>
	That's 60 percent of the daily calcium recommended by the  
federal government and many public health groups. The 
recommendations are higher for adolescents and people over age 50. 
</P>
<P>
	``It contains two times the calcium of any national cereal,''  
said Kellogg spokeswoman Meghan Parkhurst. ``With milk, the calcium 
goes up to 75 percent'' or 750 milligrams. 
</P>
<P>
	The cereal, the latest in an arsenal of products designed to  
revive the Battle Creek, Mich., manufacturer's stale cereal sales, 
will be sold in a milk carton to emphasize the high calcium 
content. 
</P>
<P>
	Kellogg Co.'s second-quarter earnings, released July 29, jumped  
7.7 percent, but the company's first-quarter earnings were down 30 
percent after a disappointing 1998. While overall sales were up 4 
percent to $1.8 billion for the quarter, cereal sales were 
relatively flat. 
</P>
<P>
	Kellogg hopes the new cereal will appeal to the three out of  
four Americans who are thought to not get enough calcium -- 
particularly women concerned about preventing osteoporosis, a 
degenerative bone disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacquelynn O'Palka, a clinical professor at the Indiana  
University School of Allied Health Sciences said it's difficult for 
the body to absorb calcium in large doses and that she prefers milk 
and other dairy products as sources for calcium. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not ideal,'' she said ``But you think about the day and  
how rushed people are. This may their only shot at getting 
calcium.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Special K Plus will cost the same as regular Special K and  
should be on store shelves by month's end. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
