<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Liberians in US Lose Special Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Torli Krua was hunted down in the middle of the  
night by machete-wielding warlords in Liberia nearly 10 years ago, 
but he managed to escape from the marauders targeting him because 
he was from a rival tribe. 
</P>
<P>
	He may soon be forced to return to his country.  
</P>
<P>
	After war erupted in the West African nation of Liberia in 1989,  
Liberians were granted temporary permission to live and work in the 
United States until their homeland settled down. 
</P>
<P>
	The special immigration status was extended year after year, and  
many Liberians were able to begin new lives here. But the State 
Department now says Liberia is stable and has recommended that the 
1,000 to 1,500 Liberians granted the special status return home by 
Sept. 28. 
</P>
<P>
	Krua and others are pleading for permission to remain, saying  
Liberia is still too dangerous. 
</P>
<P>
	``The (Liberian) government has not shown it will tolerate  
dissent,'' said Krua, 48, who has been living in Boston. ``Here, I 
go to bed freely. I speak freely. If I go back, I don't know if I 
will be able to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department and the State Department say that while  
Liberia continues to struggle from the effects of the civil war, 
Liberians here should be safe. 
</P>
<P>
	The Temporary Protected Status allows foreigners to stay in the  
United States if their home countries suffer political violence or 
natural disasters. Liberians whose temporary protected status 
expires have the right to apply for political asylum. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberia's civil war ravaged the country between 1989 and 1996,  
leaving an estimated 200,000 people dead. While the country is 
largely at peace, much of it is still without electricity, passable 
roads, and supplies remain short. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberia's political system is riddled by tribal division. A  
person's tribe often makes or breaks their position in society. 
</P>
<P>
	Some critics of Liberia's president, Charles Taylor, say the  
former warlord has rewarded supporters and punishes those who are 
not obedient. 
</P>
<P>
	``People who had homes, property and skills fled because they  
had to,'' said Rev. Henry James, a Liberian who lives permanently 
in Stoughton. ``If some of these Liberians go back, they will be 
hunted because of who they are and their tribal backgrounds.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
