<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Subpoenaed for Alien Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Angry about the release of a Mexican drifter  
suspected in nine killings, a House subcommittee has voted to 
subpoena the nation's top law enforcement officer to get 
information on immigrants with criminal records who commit more 
crimes after they're freed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Immigration and Naturalization Service recently came under  
fire for allowing Angel Maturino Resendez, the suspected ``railroad 
killer,'' to slip repeatedly through its fingers. He is charged in 
connection with murders in Texas, Illinois and Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, the House Judiciary Committee's immigration  
subcommittee voted 6-1 on Wednesday to issue a subpoena for 
Attorney General Janet Reno. Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said he 
never received data he requested from Reno in mid-July. 
</P>
<P>
	``The attorney general failed to respond in a timely or  
responsive manner,'' Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, the subcommittee's chairman, said he was not satisfied  
with a two-page letter the Justice Department sent in response to 
his request. 
</P>
<P>
	In the letter sent Monday, Acting Assistant Attorney General Jon  
P. Jennings said 26,870 criminal immigrants had been released from 
custody for various reasons in the five-year period ending May 31. 
But the department had no information on those who committed 
additional crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	``However, many of the aliens who commit crimes are encountered  
by the INS following their release and are dealt with appropriately 
as a result of referrals received from state and local law 
enforcement channels,'' Jennings said in his letter. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said he didn't believe that the department had no other  
information. 
</P>
<P>
	The subpoena gives Reno three weeks to turn over ``all records  
relating to inadmissible or deportable criminal aliens who, during 
the past five years, were released from Immigration and 
Naturalization Service detention and subsequently convicted of 
additional crimes committed in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The subpoena was signed by House Judiciary Committee Chairman  
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., Smith spokesman Alan Kay said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
