<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Cites Y2K Weak Spots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House worries that local  
governments, small hospitals, school districts and small businesses 
are not doing enough to prepare for any Year 2000 technology 
problems, according to an administration report. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, the nation's banks, utilities, travel industry and  
the federal government will be ready to confront potential computer 
troubles in the new year, said the report being released today by 
the President's Council on Year 2000 Conversion. 
</P>
<P>
	With fewer than 150 days left before Jan. 1, 2000, the latest  
snapshot of America's readiness said ``more and more organizations 
are reporting that they have met the Y2K challenge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States is in a much better position to make the  
transition into the Year 2000 than was the case just a few short 
months ago,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Of greatest concern to the administration is inadequate  
preparation by small businesses and hospitals, local governments 
and school districts -- organizations taking a ``wait-and-see'' 
approach to computer failures after the new year. 
</P>
<P>
	The council urged the nation to shift its focus to areas where  
the highest chance for failures exist and to make sure that 
organizations have contingency plans for unexpected failures. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, which called Y2K preparations ``one of the most  
extraordinary management challenges of our time,'' said 25 percent 
of counties have no formal plans, and only a little more than 
one-third the nation's 911 emergency call centers were compliant in 
June. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has been concern about the slow progress in the area of  
remediating 911 dispatch systems, especially in municipalities with 
large populations that often operate complex systems,'' the report 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	A spring survey of health care providers found only 40 percent  
were prepared, while 15 percent have not done anything to get 
ready. 
</P>
<P>
	Only 28 percent of more than 3,500 school systems reported they  
were ready, and the same percentage of small businesses admitted in 
a recent survey they plan to take no preparations. 
</P>
<P>
	But the report predicted no problems with the nation's grocery  
stores, banks, electrical and water utilities and phone companies -- 
except for international calls -- and said consumer appliances 
probably would not be affected, either. 
</P>
<P>
	``Older model VCRs may have programming problems but will still  
play and record off the air,'' the report said. ``Fax machines and 
camcorders will operate but may show incorrect information in date 
headers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House was less optimistic about problems overseas. It  
noted that while foreign preparations have improved, there still is 
a general lack of information about industries in other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is likely some countries will not escape Y2K-related  
disruptions in key infrastructure systems,'' the report said, 
finding that ``efforts to prepare electric power systems are of 
particular concern.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
