<HEADLINE> Broncos' Davis an `Invisible Man' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Terrell Davis has one of the most  
recognizable faces in the United States, so it's no wonder he feels 
like the invisible man Down Under. 
</P>
<P>
	While the 16-hour flight from Denver to Sydney, Australia, upset  
some of the Broncos' players, there has been an upside for 
superstars like Davis, last season's NFL MVP. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one really knows who I am, so that's kind of cool to walk  
around and be a normal person,'' Davis said after Broncos practiced 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis has to endure a bewildering level of fame in his hometown.  
He spoke Wednesday of being approached by fans wanting to talk 
football midway through a show at a movie theater. 
</P>
<P>
	A random poll of 20 downtown office workers Monday came up with  
20 blanks on Davis' name. In a walk around the same downtown area 
Tuesday night, Davis said he had just one person, a bartender, say 
he recognized him. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's so different from what I'm used to, living my life at  
home,'' Davis said. ``You get used to it and try to adjust and do 
things to make it easier. You know when to go out and when not to 
go out. How to handle different situations, and as you get older 
and more experienced, it gets a little bit easier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis is smart enough to know that his massive salary is  
directly linked to his fame. So he's not about to dump on Denver's 
loyal fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't dislike fame, but sometimes you're just not in the  
mood to deal with fans,'' Davis said. ``I love the fans but you 
know fans are harsh sometimes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last season Davis became just the fourth player in NFL history  
to rush for 2,000 yards in a single season. This year he must 
adjust to life after John Elway, the legendary quarterback who 
retired after back-to-back Super Bowl victories. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis says he has every confidence that Bubby Brister's  
elevation to the starting quarterback position will provide a 
smooth transition for the Broncos' offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're running the same system we ran last year and  
we're trying to do things the same way, so we don't change too much 
from last year,'' Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I worked with Bubby last year when he started four games so  
I'm comfortable with him. I'm glad I had the opportunity to play 
with him last year because it kind of gave me a preview to this 
season. I think we're going to work well together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the Broncos regular-season finale against Seattle last year,  
Davis, suffering sore ribs and finding it hard to breathe, needed 
170 yards to reach the 2000. With coach Mike Shanahan's help, and 
with his usual focus and toughness, Davis rushed for 178. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing I'm concerned about is the team goals, and if I  
achieve that then I've succeeded,'' Davis insists. ``It's nothing 
about Terrell and his personal goals. Maybe this team won't be the 
running team it was the last couple of seasons, I don't know that, 
but hopefully we'll have the same type of success we've been 
having.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
