<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Watts Threatened To Resign As Chair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A turf battle that erupted on Capitol Hill  
among senior Republican leaders prompted GOP Conference Chairman 
J.C. Watts of Oklahoma to threaten to resign his post. 
</P>
<P>
	The source of Watts' ire, according to his allies, was Rep. Tom  
DeLay of Texas, the powerful GOP whip charged with marshaling votes 
for Republican legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials close to both men said Watts took offense when DeLay  
handed out a communications strategy and questionnaire last 
Thursday during a meeting of House Republicans -- a job 
traditionally handled by someone wearing Watts' leadership hat. 
</P>
<P>
	After the meeting, Watts, the first black man in a top GOP  
leadership post since the party won congressional control five 
years ago, confronted House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and 
threatened to resign as conference chairman, according to 
leadership officials familiar with the event. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert stepped in to stop the squabble, they said.  
</P>
<P>
	``J.C. was not pleased on Thursday,'' said Rep. Pete Hoekstra,  
R-Mich. ``His view was that if J.C. Watts and Tom DeLay are not 
working together, neither of them will be successful at their 
leadership jobs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Watts, who has expressed frustration before about being usurped  
by other GOP leaders, issued a statement calling the brouhaha a 
``family'' matter. 
</P>
<P>
	DeLay insists he was only trying to help.  
</P>
<P>
	``Had we foreseen this (action) would have caused this much  
tension, we would have never done it in the first place,'' said 
DeLay spokesman Mike Scanlon. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials close to DeLay said the communications strategy was  
only a response to Watts' own call for more coordination during a 
meeting the two men had two days earlier at Watts' request. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers close to DeLay say one of his aides called Watts'  
office the night before DeLay was to present his communications 
strategy to House Republicans. They say the aide left a message, 
asking Watts' office to call back if there was any problem with 
presenting the plan, but no one did. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials close to Watts said his office responded by asking for  
a copy of the strategy before it was presented, but never received 
it. DeLay's camp said it never received such a request. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
