<DOCNO> APW19990804.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 09:20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Seek Farm Aid Compromise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eager to placate farmers hurt by drought and  
depressed crop prices, senators struggled today to work out a 
compromise between Republican and Democratic aid plans that are 
billions apart. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers are telling their senators: ``They want action, they  
want votes, some indication that something will happen,'' said 
Idaho Sen. Larry Craig, one of several Republicans negotiating with 
Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats united with fiscally conservative Republicans today to  
reject a $7.5 billion proposal offered by farm-state GOP senators. 
On Tuesday, the Senate defeated an $11 billion Democratic plan. 
With losses mounting from an East Coast drought, the GOP proposal 
wouldn't go far enough, Democrats said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm still hopeful we can reach a decent compromise,'' said  
Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	The money would be added to an annual spending bill for the  
Agriculture Department. 
</P>
<P>
	The House has yet to consider farm aid, although Speaker Dennis  
Hastert has said he's committed to passing something. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately today, the Senate voted to require the president to  
get approval from Congress before including food or medicine in a 
trade embargo. The measure is aimed at increasing exports of farm 
products. 
</P>
<P>
	``Food embargoes typically have no effect on the actions of  
foreign leaders, serving only to damage American agriculture while 
denying much-needed food and medicine to innocent people with whom 
we have no quarrel,'' said Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	A worldwide glut of grain has depressed commodity prices for the  
second year in a row, and Agriculture Department estimates that net 
farm income will dip to $43.8 billion this year, about 4 percent 
below the inflation-adjusted average for the decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, drought has parched crops from New York to Virginia.  
Although the drought isn't likely to push commodity prices up, it 
has galvanized support for farm assistance among East Coast 
lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've seen this before and it shouldn't surprise us. Whenever  
commodity prices fall and there's a certain amount of dislocation 
among some producers, then there's going to be a political 
response,'' said Kevin Kliesen, an economist with the Federal 
Reserve Bank of St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers themselves have mixed opinions about what Congress  
should do. 
</P>
<P>
	While there's widespread support for some kind of assistance,  
there's disagreement about the best way to deliver the aid or how 
much growers need. And there is concern that some growers will use 
the cash to bid up farm rents to expand their operations. 
</P>
<P>
	And some farmers ``don't want any payment at all for fear of  
what it may do. Others need it right now,'' said Edward 
Wiederstein, a grain and hog producer who is president of the Iowa 
Farm Bureau. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, some Republicans are worried that they're getting  
into a bidding war with Democrats. During last fall's congressional 
campaigns, Republicans proposed $4 billion in farm aid only to have 
the president veto the package and force them to add $2 billion 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're competing to show compassion with other people's  
money,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
