<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mozart Won't Make Kids Smarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Playing classical music for your baby might  
produce a more cultured toddler, but a smarter one? Not 
necessarily. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers are debunking a popularly theory that listening to  
the music of 18th century composer Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart spurs 
brain development in children under 3 years of age. 
</P>
<P>
	The theory was widely publicized after 1993 and 1995 studies  
conducted on college students at the University of 
California-Irvine showed an increase in spatial-reasoning 
immediately after exposure to a Mozart piano sonata. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kenneth Steele, a psychology professor at Appalachian State  
University in Boone, N.C., and John Bruer, who heads the McDonnell 
Foundation in St. Louis, say there's no real benefit, and that one 
would see the same results listening to any kind of music or none 
at all. 
</P>
<P>
	``People have tried to produce the effect all kinds of ways,''  
Steele said. ``Not only haven't we found that it is a weak effect 
and we can't make it stronger, we can't find any kind of effect at 
all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the University of California studies were released, some  
parents began playing Mozart compositions in their homes in hopes 
of raising smarter children. It wasn't just parents who were swayed 
by the study. 
</P>
<P>
	In Georgia, former Gov. Zell Miller started a program to provide  
every young mother with a CD of the composer's music. And the 
National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences Foundation handed 
out free CDs of Grammy-winning classical music at hundreds of 
hospitals in May. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's how science spreads through our culture,'' said Steele.  
``There is one kind of study and everyone assumes that it's true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Follow-up studies have been unable to duplicate the original  
research, he said. Steele conducted a study that went so far as to 
follow the same procedures used to produce the effect in the 
original study. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we went back to that and still didn't get the effect,  
that cast grave doubts on the original effect and what the effect 
means,'' Steele said. ``It can't be investigated. It can't be 
researched.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steele's research is published in the July issue of the journal  
Psychological Science; Bruer's book, ``The Myth of the First Three 
Years,'' will be published next month. 
</P>
<P>
	Steele's test subjects showed an increase in reasoning when  
listening to contemporary composer Philip Glass -- or not listening 
to anything at all. The differences between silence, Mozart and 
Glass's music were so small, Steele said, they lacked any 
statistical significance. 
</P>
<P>
	Not all scientists feel there is no value in ``extra''  
stimulation for young children. 
</P>
<P>
	John Flohr, a professor of music education at Texas' Woman's  
University in Denton, Texas, was a consultant on the project to 
hand out Grammy-winning music to new parents. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stimulus in the environment has a significant effect in early  
childhood,'' Flohr said. ``We don't know what will do what yet. But 
music could be a part of that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
