<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Promises To Veto Tax Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today promised to veto the  
$792 billion Republican tax cut plan, calling it ``risky and 
plainly wrong for America.'' The GOP plan would gradually cut 1 
percentage point off each personal income tax rate. It also would 
provide relief from the so-called marriage penalty, cut the 
individual capital-gains tax rate and eventually eliminate the 
estate tax. Clinton said the package ``signs away our commitment to 
America's future, Social Security, Medicare, paying down the 
debt.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Boy Scouts To Appeal Gays' Ruling  
</P>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The Boy Scouts of America says it will  
appeal today's ruling by the New Jersey Supreme Court that said the 
group's ban on homosexuals is illegal. The court unanimously 
decided in favor of a James Dale, an assistant scoutmaster who was 
kicked out nine years ago when Boy Scout leaders found out he is 
gay. The court said the Boy Scouts organization constitutes a 
``place of public accommodation'' because it has a broad-based 
membership. Thus, the court said, under the anti-discrimination 
law, the Boy Scouts cannot deny any person ``accommodations, 
advantages, facilities and privileges'' because of sexual 
orientation. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Kosovo Head Tours Mass Graves  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The top U.N. administrator in Kosovo  
toured a mass grave today where the remains of dozens of ethnic 
Albanians were found. The 72 graves were uncovered in and around an 
existing graveyard on a hill overlooking the northern village of 
Kosovska Mitrovica. Officials said they had so far retrieved 40 to 
50 bodies over the past 10 days. Some of the remains were in body 
bags and appeared to have been brought to the site over a period 
from April to June, when Serb forces were waging a campaign of 
expulsions and massacres in Kosovo, a spokesman for the 
international war crimes tribunal said. He also said some of the 
bodies had signs of torture. 

</P>
<P>
	US, Israel Investing in Laser Weapon  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and Israel have agreed to  
spend an additional $46.6 million to continue development of a 
one-of-a-kind laser weapon for use against short-range projectiles 
like the Katyusha rockets that Hezbollah forces fire into northern 
Israel from southern Lebanon. The program has cost the United 
States $130.8 million since it started in 1996. 

</P>
<P>
	Survey: Age Doesn't Deter Sex Drive  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new survey finds that many Americans  
continue to have active sex lives and find their partners 
attractive as they age -- although as health declines and partners 
are lost to death or divorce, sex becomes less frequent for most. 
The survey was conducted by the AARP, the nation's largest 
organization of older adults, for the September-October issue of 
its ``Modern Maturity'' magazine. The survey found that more than 
six in 10 men between the ages of 45 and 59 and a similar 
percentage of women in middle age report having sex at least once a 
week. 

</P>
<P>
	More Than 500M Guns Said on Planet  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- More than 500 million guns and other small  
arms are circulating around the world, widely used because they are 
lethal, inexpensive, easy to care for and easy to hide, a U.N. 
panel says. Assault rifles, machine guns, pistols and 
grenade-launchers are increasingly ``the weapon of choice'' in 
contemporary conflicts, the U.N. Department for Disarmament said in 
a report yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft To Help Navajo Schools  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft is giving a $1.2 million grant to fund  
technology training for teachers in 12 Navajo school districts in 
Arizona, New Mexico and Utah, the company announced today. The 
grant to the Navajo Education Technology Consortium will help match 
a five-year, $7.6 million national Technology Innovation Challenge 
Grant awarded earlier this year to the consortium by the U.S 
Department of Education. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 97  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 97.20 to 10,774.51. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,767-1,114. The Nasdaq was down 23.78 to 
2,564.21. 

</P>
<P>
	Small Fire Damages Fenway Park  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A worker's blowtorch was blamed for a small fire  
at Fenway Park this morning that damaged a restroom wall and forced 
the Red Sox to close one entrance to the park for 30 minutes. The 
fire broke out shortly after 11:30 a.m. EDT in a wall outside a 
rooftop bathroom along the third base line. No injuries were 
reported and the 1:05 p.m. game against the Cleveland Indians 
started on time. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  



  	   	
</P>
