<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> British Olympic Champion Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Linford Christie, the retired former Olympic  
sprint champion who has repeatedly denied taking drugs and claims 
he now competes for fun, is furious that he's being forced to stop 
racing because of a drug test. 
</P>
<P>
	After a decade at the top, he's been banned on suspicion of  
steroid use. 
</P>
<P>
	The glittering career of the 1992 Olympic titlist who reveled in  
beating the American stars could be overshadowed by a test at an 
indoor meet at Dortmund, Germany, in February. The test showed 
traces of the banned steroid nandrolone. 
</P>
<P>
	Christie only ran in the meet because of challenges thrown down  
by the sprinters he was coaching. He won a heat and then finished 
fourth in the final. 
</P>
<P>
	But a urine test gave an adverse reading for metabolites of  
nandrolone, and if the test eventually proves positive, Christie 
could be banned for two years, even though he has retired. 
</P>
<P>
	``I vigorously deny ever taking any form of banned substance.  
What would be the point of me doing it?'' Christie said on 
Wednesday after news of the ban came from UK Athletics and the 
world governing body, the International Amateur Athletic 
Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	The 39-year-old British athlete, who now coaches leading  
sprinters in Europe, also gave his support to a campaign for a more 
reliable testing procedure for nandrolone, which can be produced 
naturally. 
</P>
<P>
	``I agree that there should be a full investigation into the  
numerous cases where metabolites of nandrolone have been found in 
urine samples to establish how this could happen without the 
knowledge of the athletes,'' Christie said. 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF says the suspension is technical and that the test  
isn't positive. But the athlete who has often spoken out against 
the use of performance enhancing substances faces a two-year ban if 
he's proved wrong this time, and his 23-title career would be in 
ruins. 
</P>
<P>
	``The unfortunate thing is that this puts a cloud over  
everything Linford has done, whether he is innocent or guilty,'' 
said Derek Redmond, a former 400-meter runner who was one of 
Christie's teammates at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Christie has consistently spoken out against drugs. But he has  
had to fight accusations that his success might be tied to 
performance-enhancing substances. 
</P>
<P>
	At the 1998 Seoul Olympics, Christie finished third behind Ben  
Johnson and Carl Lewis, but wound up with the silver after Johnson 
was stripped of the title for taking steroids. 
</P>
<P>
	Christie survived a scare when a banned substance showed in his  
urine sample. However, the substance derived from ginseng in a 
health drink and was cleared as acceptable. 
</P>
<P>
	Last summer, Christie won $64,000 in libel damages from a  
magazine writer who said his track performances were the result of 
taking drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspension comes a day after sprinter Dennis Mitchell  
received a two-year drug ban. The IAAF said Mitchell's drug test 
showed a high level of testosterone. 
</P>
<P>
	The American runner, who won the bronze medal behind Christie in  
Barcelona, is barred from the world championships, but because the 
ban is retroactive, Mitchell will be eligible for the 2000 Sydney 
Olympics. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
