<DOCNO> APW19990804.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 02:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pediatricians Suggest Limits on TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Children under 2 shouldn't watch television at  
all and older kids shouldn't have TVs in their rooms, the American 
Academy of Pediatrics recommends in a new report. 
</P>
<P>
	The report in this month's issue of Pediatrics magazine is the  
first from the 55,000-member academy on how to better manage 
children's use of television. Details were outlined in today's New 
York Times. 
</P>
<P>
	The group said TV viewing can affect the mental, social and  
physical health of young people. Its recommendations were based in 
part on the thinking that babies need close interaction with people 
for proper brain development -- and that TV time can take away from 
people time. 
</P>
<P>
	Pediatricians should also ask for a child's ``media history''  
along with a medical history, the report recommends. The academy is 
supplying members with a sample checklist for young patients, 
including questions about movies, video and computer games, music 
videos and the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Other recommendations include critical discussion of what  
children watch and keeping TVs and computers in common spaces where 
use can be monitored. 
</P>
<P>
	The academy, which spent two years developing the policy,  
suggested in 1990 that children be limited to one to two hours of 
``quality'' programming a day. In 1997 it launched a campaign to 
educate pediatricians on the influences television can have on 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	Aggressiveness in older children has been linked to violence in  
movies and television in several studies by groups including the 
American Medical Association, the American Psychological 
Association and the National Institute of Mental Health. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 12:00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> College Edits Portion of Sex Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The University of Minnesota is rejecting  
efforts by a state agency, a newspaper and two alleged victims of 
sexual misconduct to see sections edited out of a report on the 
conduct of athletes and administrators. 
</P>
<P>
	About half of the 233-page report by outside investigators on  
the university's handling of sexual assault and misconduct 
allegations was blanked out before the university released it in 
early July. 
</P>
<P>
	The report is one of two covering men's athletics. The second  
inquiry, into allegations of academic fraud in the university's 
basketball program, isn't expected to be done until the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The report reviewed about 40 accusations made against athletes  
of various types of sexual misconduct, including assault and 
harassment. It concluded that in some cases, school officials 
improperly intervened in the cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The Star Tribune reported in May that athletics officials  
sometimes had the cooperation of campus police as they helped 
players negotiate agreements in cases that were never submitted to 
prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Star Tribune sought access to the censored information in  
the report, and asked the state Department of Administration to 
review whether information was wrongly withheld. 
</P>
<P>
	But the university has refused to provide the edited portions.  
</P>
<P>
	The university also has denied requests by two women for  
information regarding their specific allegations that athletes who 
abused and harassed them were protected by school officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Rotenberg, university general counsel, wrote to the women's  
attorney that the information remains confidential because it is 
part of an active investigation. Rotenberg said federal and state 
laws allow the university to withhold information to protect the 
privacy of employees, students and victims. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
