<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 07:56:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Nears Senate Confirmation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Diplomatic troubleshooter Richard Holbrooke's  
longest mission, winning Senate confirmation to be U.N. ambassador, 
appeared near an end today. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., who earlier had been  
among four senators holding up a final vote, suggested a final 
floor vote could come as early as today. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Holbrooke has always appeared to have overwhelming  
support in the Senate, it has been 14 months since President 
Clinton announced his selection for the top diplomatic post. 
</P>
<P>
	A series of delays has plagued the nomination, most recently a  
wave of parliamentary maneuvers by individual senators to delay a 
final vote, mostly over unrelated disputes. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke, now an investment banker, is a former ambassador to  
Germany and was architect of the 1995 accord that ended the war in 
Bosnia. He has also served at Clinton's special envoy to the 
Balkans during the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott predicted Holbrooke's confirmation if Sen. Charles Grassley  
withdraws his opposition ``and there are no other issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley, R-Iowa, is the only remaining senator with a ``hold''  
on the Holbrooke nomination. Grassley has objected to the State 
Department's treatment of a whistle-blower Linda Shenwick. 
</P>
<P>
	A Grassley spokeswoman, Jill Kozeny, said that while talks  
between the senator and State Department on Shenwick's plight are 
continuing, ``Generally, Senator Grassley's concerns have been met. 
</P>
<P>
	``But he's going to take additional steps to make sure fairness  
returns,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley contends that Shenwick, who worked at the U.N. mission  
in New York, was demoted and transferred to a lesser job in 
Washington in retaliation for her telling members of Congress about 
waste and inefficiency at the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department has said Shenwick was reassigned because of  
unsatisfactory job performance, not because she was a 
whistle-blower. 
</P>
<P>
	John Czwartacki, a spokesman for Lott, said a floor vote could  
come at any time on the nomination as Congress prepares to leave 
for its August vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott had detected ``some movement'' in recent days in support of  
ending Holbrooke's long odyssey, Czwartacki said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
