<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 07:52:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Isiah Thomas New Owner of CBA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Isiah Thomas has big plans for his little league.  
</P>
<P>
	At first interested in acquiring an expansion franchise for  
Detroit, Thomas instead wound up paying $10 million to purchase the 
entire Continental Basketball Association and its nine franchises. 
</P>
<P>
	And he believes it's a great deal.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is a great business opportunity if we can put the right  
operational structure in place,'' Thomas said. ``The most important 
thing is to concentrate on being the best minor league system 
around. The CBA has been here since 1946 and plans to be around 
until 2046.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas' CBA involvement began innocently enough when he inquired  
about putting a team in Detroit, where he led the Pistons to 
consecutive NBA championships in 1989 and 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	The next thing he knew, he owned the whole league, with Detroit  
on the back burner as a possible future expansion team. Also 
mentioned as areas the CBA might look to in the future were 
southern California and suburban Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas plans to reorganize the CBA from an association with 40  
owners into a single entity league. 
</P>
<P>
	``The franchises will be owned by the league,'' Thomas said.  
``This new single entity model will eliminate the inefficiencies of 
current franchise ownership. Under the single entity model, the 
nine teams will report to the league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And the league will control all aspects of team operations from  
player negotiations to marketing to revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	From a personal standpoint, Thomas sees his CBA connection as a  
natural progression. 
</P>
<P>
	``This completes the cycle of basketball for me, touching all  
the aspects of basketball,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	After a 13-year playing career with the Pistons, he became part  
owner and general manager of the expansion Toronto Raptors. Then he 
moved into broadcasting as an analyst on NBC's coverage of the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``My interest is purely in basketball remaining healthy and the  
game continuing to grow, and protecting the sanctity of the game we 
all love,'' Thomas said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas wants the CBA to continue its role as a developmental  
league, a training ground for future NBA players and officials. He 
would also like to see the league's teams become directly 
affiliated with NBA clubs, moving players up and down with single 
contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on his agenda are possible exhibition games for CBA teams  
against NCAA teams, much like preseason games currently played 
against teams like Athletes In Action and touring European clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	But that's for the future.  
</P>
<P>
	For now Thomas wants to build what he has.  
</P>
<P>
	``We have one goal -- to be the second best league in the  
world,'' he said. ``As a minor league, a developmental league, 
we're not in the driver's seat. We're passengers. We bring to the 
table the ability to enhance the property in each city.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All this developed out of Thomas' dream to own an NBA team. He  
was forced to back off because he could not compete with corporate 
bankrolls. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have not given up on the NBA dream,'' he said. ``I learned a  
long time ago if your pocketbook can't support your dreams, you 
need to look elsewhere.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 15:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. May Buy Back $3.6 Trillion Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Talk about a head-spinning turnaround. The  
United States, which for most of the century has struggled to 
borrow money for the burgeoning national debt, is now faced with an 
altogether different dilemma. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time since 1972, the government is figuring out  
ways to buy back debt held by the public. The country, born in debt 
from the Revolutionary War, has been out of the red only once, when 
Andrew Jackson fulfilled a campaign promise and wiped out the 
national debt, for a brief period, in 1835. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury Department on Wednesday issued proposed rules for  
the debt buyback operation and plans to finalize details by Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, President Clinton said his plans for the budget surplus  
were smart and sound compared with the Republicans' $792 billion 
tax cut. The president has promised to veto the package once it 
clears Congress this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wants to use two-thirds of the projected surpluses over  
the next 15 years to eliminate the $3.6 trillion in debt held by 
the public. He said that approach would help the economy by 
lowering the government's borrowing demands and reducing interest 
rates paid by consumers and businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	He likened the buyback plan to a family's decision to refinance  
a home mortgage at lower, more favorable interest rates in hopes of 
eventually paying off the entire mortgage and eliminating all 
interest payments. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's refinance our nation's mortgage and then wipe the ledger  
clean,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said any government purchases of debt would be  
voluntary and conducted through a type of reverse auction. The 
government would announce the type of securities it was interested 
in buying and accept the most competitive bids from holders of 
those securities. 
</P>
<P>
	If bond holders wanted too much money to sell their securities  
back to the government, Treasury could decline to purchase that 
option. 
</P>
<P>
	Private economists generally gave the administration's proposal  
high marks. They said it would not disrupt the government's 
procedures for offering new Treasury bills, notes and bonds to 
investors, or upset the massive secondary market, where close to 
$200 billion in U.S. securities changes hands daily. 
</P>
<P>
	``This plan looks like sound fiscal management. It makes sense  
to pay down the debt and it makes sense to pay down higher-interest 
debt that was issued years ago first,'' said Mark Zandi, senior 
economist at Regional Financial Associates in West Chester, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury has not bought back securities since 1972, when a  
few existing bonds and notes held by the public were swapped for 
new debt issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Huge budget deficits in the 1980s and early 1990s caused the  
national debt to climb from less than $1 trillion, before Ronald 
Reagan became president, to $5.5 trillion now. Of that amount, $3.6 
trillion is in public hands; the rest is held by government trust 
funds, the largest of which is Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	The government last year had its first budget surplus since  
1969, a record $69.2 billion. Those surpluses are projected to 
total $2.9 trillion over the next decade, providing the money the 
administration proposes to use to reduce the national debt. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration projects that by the end of the current  
budget year on Sept. 30, it will have lowered the national debt by 
$142 billion over the past two years by reducing the amount of new 
T-bills, notes and bonds that were issued and by not buying back 
securities already in private hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said taxpayers would save if  
the government buys back older, higher-interest-rate securities in 
private hands rather than continuing to issue new securities. 
</P>
<P>
	If the buyback does not go ahead, Treasury estimated the average  
maturity for government securities would rise from the current 5.4 
years to 7 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers said a reduction of three basis points, or  
three-hundredths of a percentage point, on the government's debt 
holdings would translate into annual savings of $1 billion in 
interest payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Buying back existing debt rather than reducing new debt sales  
would maintain a sizable market for new securities, making them 
more attractive to investors because they will be able to count on 
an available supply. 
</P>
<P>
	That is important not just to the government but to businesses  
and homeowners because Treasury securities often are used as a 
pricing benchmark for private debt. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 08:32:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Spent $500,000 on Kennedy Search </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When John F. Kennedy Jr.'s plane was first  
reported missing, the government sent sailors and pilots, aviation 
experts and two ships. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks later, federal costs are still being calculated.  
Estimates surpass $500,000 -- not including Air Force and Navy 
involvement -- but much of that would have been spent anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	Some factors:  
</P>
<P>
	--The U.S. Coast Guard's total cost was close to $492,000.  
</P>
<P>
	--The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration spent about  
$55,000 to operate the Rude and Whiting -- ships that usually survey 
the ocean for updating nautical charts -- in the search for 
wreckage. 
</P>
<P>
	--Forces from the Navy and Air Force were sent, including one  
ship that otherwise wouldn't have been at sea. The Defense 
Department would not release figures until it completes its review. 
</P>
<P>
	--The National Transportation Safety Board has embarked on an  
investigation that's expected to take six to nine months and 
involve numerous experts. But neither the NTSB or Federal Aviation 
Administration break down costs on a case-by-case basis, spokesmen 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the federal government's role was extensive, it didn't  
come at the Kennedy family's request -- with one exception. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only request the family made was for the burial-at-sea,''  
said a family spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Otherwise, President Clinton took responsibility for authorizing  
the extraordinary effort to recover the private plane. He based it 
on the Kennedy family's role ``in our national lives, and because 
of the enormous losses that they have sustained in our lifetimes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The costs are hard to calculate, at least in terms of  
determining what was spent for the Kennedy crash that wouldn't have 
been spent otherwise. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, the USS Briscoe, a Navy guided missile destroyer on  
which the Kennedys gathered privately to release the ashes of JFK 
Jr., his wife Carolyn Bessette Kennedy and her sister, Lauren 
Bessette, costs roughly $100,000 a day to run, says the Federation 
of American Scientists, a nonprofit research group. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Briscoe, with a crew of about 380, was on a training  
mission off Virginia when it was diverted to the Kennedy mission, 
so some costs probably would have been incurred anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even on its way up there, it was able to do some of the  
training,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Lydia Robertson, a Navy spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, the USS Grasp, a Navy salvage ship that retrieved  
about 75 percent of the plane, was sent from port. A ship like that 
typically has a crew of 100 and probably costs about $25,000 a day 
to operate, said John Pike, an analyst with the Federation of 
American Scientists. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force contributed to the search as well.  
</P>
<P>
	``I would be puzzled if they came up with a number that was only  
tens of thousands for the air component,'' Pike said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard, meanwhile, would have incurred much of its  
$492,000 in costs even if it didn't help with the search because 
its personnel get the same pay whether they are on a mission or 
not, said Jack O'Dell, a Coast Guard spokesman. The only extra cost 
for the Kennedy mission would have been fuel, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Likewise for NOAA, which would have had to spend about $30,000  
of its $55,000 expense regardless of the Kennedy crash, said Jeanne 
Kouhestani, a spokeswoman for the Commerce Department, which 
includes NOAA. That means the Kennedy mission cost the agency an 
additional $25,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
