<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pacers' Bender Admits He's Behind </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Jonathan Bender, nearly two weeks late for  
the Indiana Pacers' rookie camp, admits he has some catching up to 
do but isn't too worried about lost time. 
</P>
<P>
	Due to league restrictions, the 18-year-old Bender couldn't join  
the Pacers in the rookie camp which started July 23 because he was 
officially a Toronto Raptor until Aug. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Bender, the Raptors' first-round pick in the June 30 NBA draft,  
was traded to the Pacers for veteran forward Antonio Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I'm going to be behind, but I adapt to situations  
pretty quickly and I think I'll be able to handle it,'' Bender 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, Bender has been working with a personal  
trainer, lifting weights for an hour and a half each day to try to 
bulk up for the regular season. Since the draft, Bender has gained 
10 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-11, 200-pound forward is expected to sign a contract  
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bender joins 19-year old Al Harrington as one of two teenagers  
on a largely veteran Pacer team. If Bender's rookie season in the 
NBA is anything like Harrington's, he can expect little playing 
time. That suits him just fine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm considering learning a lot this year, just asking a lot of  
questions and learning from sight, learning from the veterans,'' 
Bender said. ``If I do well, I'll play but it's the coach's 
decision. I'm not going to sit on the bench and pout about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're all aware that at his age he's got an awful lot of work  
to do in the NBA but he really has a legitimate chance of being a 
terrific NBA player,'' club president Donnie Walsh said. 
</P>
<P>
	Just last year, Bender was a high school All-American out of  
Picayune, Miss. He said a lifelong dream to join the NBA convinced 
him to declare for the draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just dreamed all my life that I would make it here and I  
just played hard, worked at it, shot balls in the middle of the 
night, thought about it, and finally made it here,'' Bender said. 
``Thank God for all that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But now that he's realized his dream, Bender said he wants to  
use the money to give back to his family. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to make sure my mom and my grandma don't work anymore.  
I'm not really worried about me right now, I'm worried about 
them,'' Bender said. ``They worked every day of their life. They've 
taken care of me so it's my turn to take care of them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
