<DOCNO> APW19990804.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 15:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seifert Laments Panthers' Poor Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPARTANBURG, S.C. (AP) -- It was bad enough that the Carolina  
Panthers were stricken by an outbreak of the training-camp blahs 
Wednesday. Making matters worse was that the boss was on hand for a 
rare view of his troops. 
</P>
<P>
	For the better part of two hours, the Panthers spent their  
morning workout at Wofford College putting on a clinic in 
inefficiency. Snap counts were forgotten, handoffs were missed, 
passes were dropped, blocking assignments were blown and players 
seemed to be moving in slow motion. 
</P>
<P>
	Watching all of this while alternately sitting in a golf cart or  
standing along the sidelines, his arms folded across his chest, was 
owner Jerry Richardson. It was Richardson's first appearance at 
training camp this year, and it couldn't have come at a worse time, 
at least as far as new coach George Seifert was concerned. 
</P>
<P>
	Seifert, signed in January to a five-year, $12 million contract  
by Richardson, had envisioned marking the owner's visit to 
Spartanburg with a nice, crisp workout. The coach even joked with 
the Panthers before practice about how they would celebrate showing 
the owner how far they had come in such a short time under Seifert 
in their bid to rebound from last year's 4-12 record. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the end of practice, we had a certain group lined up that  
was going to carry me off the field,'' Seifert said, managing a 
weak chuckle. ``Believe me, I squelched that. It's kind of one of 
those things that when I see Jerry now, I kind of wave and walk in 
the other direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seifert made several attempts to snap his players out of the  
doldrums. He repeatedly gathered the Panthers for a team huddle and 
spoke to them about the virtues of hard work, concentration and the 
like. 
</P>
<P>
	But shortly after one such huddle, the practice hit a low point  
when reserve quarterback Jeff Lewis took a center snap, wheeled to 
turn back into the pocket -- and fell flat on his face. As the ball 
squirted loose and rolled away, some coaches threw up their arms. 
Others blew whistles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not flicking in the towel by any means,'' said Seifert,  
who has the highest winning percentage of any coach in NFL history. 
``And to say that you might not expect this from time to time -- you 
do. But the players, they've got to accept the responsibility that 
they've got to at least take the snap from center, they've got to 
at least make a catch, they've got to at least tenaciously go block 
people. And until we do that, we'll just kind of show up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson declined to speak with reporters about the practice,  
but Seifert was more than willing to talk passionately on the 
subject. The coach was particularly pointed when he was reminded 
that the defensive line was thinned by the absence of starters 
Jason Peter and Tim Morabito, who sat out the practice to rest what 
were described as minor leg muscle pulls. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the scary part,'' Seifert said. ``What we did have kind  
of knocked our offense's butts off. We weren't able to run any 
plays.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seifert said part of the execution problems likely could be tied  
to the fact that he is instituting a new system at Carolina. While 
Seifert has been using parts or all of the system throughout his 
17-year NFL career, almost all of the Panthers are just seeing it 
for the first time, and they're still trying to get comfortable 
with it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got so many things going in right now, so many plays,  
and there's no specific execution,'' he said. ``So we're working at 
about -- I think I can optimistically say -- 10 percent efficiency as 
far as where we're going to have to be.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
