<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Raiders' Ware retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAPA, Calif. (AP) -- Andre Ware, who won the Heisman Trophy in  
1989 as a record-setting quarterback at Houston, has retired from 
the NFL, the Oakland Raiders said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ware, a first-round draft choice by Detroit in 1990, played in  
the Canadian Football League last season, then signed with Oakland 
this spring and was assigned to NFL Europe for development. He 
fractured his left shoulder midway through the schedule and fell 
hopelessly behind in camp with the Raiders. 
</P>
<P>
	Ware, who runs a computer business, hasn't played in the NFL  
since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Raiders coach Jon Gruden said Ware informed him of the decision  
Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Andre was in a tough situation, and wasn't getting may  
opportunities to show what he could do. It's unfortunate,'' Gruden 
said. ``He was hurt and we really liked some of the things that 
(rookie quarterback) Scott Dreisback was doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, the Raiders signed Ray Zellars, who started  
seven games for New Orleans last year, and Tyrone Wheatley, who was 
cut by Miami on Tuesday and played only sporadically for the New 
York Giants in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Zellars rushed for 162 yards and one touchdown on 56 carries for  
New Orleans before being picked up on waivers by Cincinnati. The 
Bengals didn't invite him to camp this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheatley had 14 carries for 52 yards with the Giants last year.  
</P>
<P>
	Zellars, a 1995 second-round draft pick out of Notre Dame, was  
brought in as a replacement for fullback and short-yardage 
specialist Zack Crockett, a free-agent acquisition from 
Jacksonville who fractured his right foot on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheatley was a first-round pick by the Giants in 1995.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
