<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FBI Holds Turkish Man in Custody  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- A Turkish man removed from a Delta Air Lines  
flight before it left for Istanbul was held today for an expired 
visa as the FBI investigated what it would refer to only as the 
man's suspicious behavior. Hakan Caglar, 35, attracted the 
suspicion of law enforcement officials when he retrieved his 
luggage from a U-Haul truck yesterday and paid cash for a one-way 
ticket to Turkey at a Valdosta airport. Caglar, who had been in the 
United States since March 7, is being held by the Immigration and 
Naturalization Service because his visa expired June 6, an INS 
official said. 

</P>
<P>
	Buchanan May Leave Republican Party  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pat Buchanan may bolt to the Reform Party  
because of concerns that the Republican nomination process is 
geared in favor of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, and that he has 
little chance of winning or even pushing his social and economic 
issues. The decision, which is not expected until the fall, may 
depend on an Aug. 14 contest in Iowa testing the political strength 
of nine Republican presidential candidates, said officials close to 
Buchanan and in the Reform Party. Republican leaders worry that a 
Buchanan defection would drain support of the GOP's most 
conservative voters from the party's eventual nominee. 

</P>
<P>
	Group Says Patent Bill Harms Poor  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The sick, poor and elderly who need  
prescriptions would suffer from a bill that would extend patents on 
seven drugs, a former senator who represents consumer groups said 
today. Howard Metzenbaum of the Consumer Federation of America said 
the legislation would block manufacturers of generic drugs from 
making cheaper versions of brand-name medicines. ``The bill is 
essentially a tax on the uninsured, the poor, the sick and the 
elderly,'' Metzenbaum, a former Democratic senator from Ohio, told 
the Senate Judiciary Committee. 

</P>
<P>
	Fen-Phen Suit Seeks Medical Care  
</P>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Thousands of healthy New Jersey residents  
who took the fen-phen diet drugs want one of the drug makers to pay 
for years of medical checkups to detect any signs of heart and lung 
problems. Complaints forced the drugs off the market in 1997. 
American Home Products -- which made fenfluramine -- could be forced 
to pay more than $1 billion over the next decade if it loses the 
trial. Jury selection in the case began earlier this week. An 
economist estimated that American Home Products would have to pay 
$1.5 billion for a decade of regular checkups for the 94,000 
residents who took the drug combination for at least three months. 

</P>
<P>
	Removing Predators Has Consequences  
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- House cats and other small animals are becoming  
the dominant predators in many of San Diego's rugged canyons, 
replacing wild coyotes that were driven away by urban development, 
according to a new study. Because cats, opossums, skunks and 
raccoons are no longer preyed on, they are free to eat more rodents 
and birds, threatening their populations, said biologist Kevin 
Crooks, co-author of the study in tomorrow's journal Nature. ``It 
shows if you destroy habitat and remove components of an ecosystem, 
effects are seen throughout,'' said Lee McClenaghan, professor of 
biology at San Diego State University. 

</P>
<P>
	Stanford Buys Steinbeck Stories  
</P>
<P>
	STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- Stanford University has bought an array  
of papers by the late author John Steinbeck, including previously 
unknown short stories and poems from his teens and twenties. The 
university bought the collection from his sister, Esther Steinbeck 
Rodgers. The collection includes a draft of Steinbeck's speech 
accepting the 1962 Nobel prize in literature. Also included are 
hundreds of family photos and nearly 400 of Steinbeck's letters to 
his parents, sisters and other relatives. Steinbeck studied English 
at Stanford but dropped out. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Stocks Fall in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell Thursday, pushed down by a  
decline on Wall Street. The Nikkei Stock Average fell 214.75 points 
to 17,470.63 in early trading. On Wall Street on Wednesday, the Dow 
Jones industrial average closed down 2.54 at 10,674.77. The Dow, 
following what is becoming a familiar pattern, gave up nearly all 
its gains late in the day and wiped out what had been a 152-point 
gain. 

</P>
<P>
	McGwire Says He Hasn't Taken Andro  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Mark McGwire, adamant in spring training that  
he would keep taking androstenedione, disclosed today that he has 
not used the supplement for four months. McGwire, who has hit 42 
homers this year and is one short of No. 500, made the revelation 
before his St. Louis Cardinals played the San Diego Padres. McGwire 
said the fact his record 70-homer season was linked to andro, a 
testosterone booster, likely encouraged youngsters to try it. That 
was perhaps the biggest reason for his decision. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  



  	   	
