<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 88.02; Nasdaq Down 25.40 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks surged higher today on news of  
a $9.3 billion merger of Dow Chemical and Union Carbide, but the 
broader market lagged well behind. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 88.02 at 10,765.33. On Tuesday, the index rose 31.35 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Following Tuesday's pattern, other market indexes struggled with  
modest losses while the Dow marched higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 
500 index was off 4.49 at 1,317.69, and the Nasdaq composite index 
was down 25.40 at 2,562.59. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow's gains came largely from the announcement that Dow  
Chemical is buying Union Carbide, building its position as the No. 
2 chemical company behind DuPont. The two companies said they 
expect the combination to save $500 million a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Union Carbide, a Dow Jones component stock, soared 10 5/8 to 59  
7/16, while Dow Chemical fell 7 5/16 to 117 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Other companies that make basic materials like chemicals and  
paper rose as well. International Paper, another stock in the Dow 
average, rose 3 1/4 to 55 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, traders remained unconvinced of the market's underlying  
strength. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is lacking any conviction,'' said Richard Cripps,  
chief market strategist for Legg Mason in Baltimore. ``The market 
lacks any real incentives for buyers to come in, and some selling 
pressure definitely remains.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks continued to languish. Amazon.com fell 4 3/4 to  
90 1/8, and online auctioneer eBay fell 6 1/16 to 78 5/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices, which have tumbled amid the growing belief that the  
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates, recovered today as the 
Treasury Department said it would reduce bond sales and proposed a 
buyback of the $3.6 trillion national debt. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell to 6.11  
percent from 6.16 percent late Tuesday. But analysts say the yield 
remains high enough to lure some investors away from stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks were expected to stay in a fairly narrow range through  
Friday, when the Labor Department releases its monthly unemployment 
report. The report is expected to offer the latest indication of 
whether wage pressures are escalating enough to persuade the Fed to 
raise rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by nearly 2-to-1 on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 617.71 million 
shares, slightly ahead of Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 3.57 at 618.83, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 2.04 at 778.43. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies slipped 6.04 to  
430.24. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
