<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Enough Talk, Mrs. Clinton Listens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAMESTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- Slamming the door on further talk of her  
husband's infidelities, Hillary Rodham Clinton returned to the 
Senate campaign trail Wednesday, calling for a big-state coalition 
to fight for more federal aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, the former first lady of Arkansas, said the larger  
states such as New York, California and Illinois, where she was 
raised, were being shortchanged on federal aid. 
</P>
<P>
	``Were I in the Senate, I would try to create a coalition of the  
big states to stand up for our interests,'' she told more than 60 
Jamestown-area residents at a ``listening event'' at Crawford's 
Furniture factory. ``It may be that we'll never get a 
dollar-for-dollar exchange, but we sure ought to get more than 
we're getting now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's pitch for more federal aid for larger states  
picks up on a theme espoused for years by fellow Democrat Daniel 
Patrick Moynihan, who next year is vacating the Senate seat the 
first lady is eyeing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I get more interested in running every day,'' she said  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Republican side, a race is being considered by New York  
City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and two House members from Long Island, 
Peter King and Rick Lazio. 
</P>
<P>
	Moynihan has long argued that New York and other large states  
send more to Washington than they get back in federal aid, to the 
tune of $14 billion annually for New York. Smaller states often get 
more money than they send to Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton said the situation stems from federal policies that  
began more than 50 years ago when ``a state like New York was so 
much better off than a state like Alabama'' and ``there was a 
conscious effort to redistribute money to the poorer states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady said that trend continued, even as the economic  
disparity lessened, because ``you've got a lot of political 
influence in the Congress that represents those (smaller) states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Mrs. Clinton, it was the first appearance on the campaign  
trail in New York since the Talk magazine interview appeared in 
which she discussed her marital problems more openly than ever 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	But she said Wednesday that enough had been said on the subject.  
</P>
<P>
	``I really believe strongly that the country has put that issue  
behind it. I have as well,'' Mrs. Clinton said, adding, ``I've said 
all I'm going to say on that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before she clamped the lid down again, Mrs. Clinton said she did  
not mean to imply in the interview that the president's childhood 
problems were to blame for his infidelities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody is responsible for their behavior and I am a very  
strong proponent and believer in personal responsibility, so I hope 
that people will take that message away from this,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady also said, ``My husband and I love each other  
very much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the Talk magazine interview, Mrs. Clinton called her  
husband's infidelities ``a sin of weakness'' and appeared to 
suggest it might have been linked to battles between his mother and 
grandmother over custody of him when he was young. 
</P>
<P>
	Following the Jamestown event, Mrs. Clinton stopped for lunch in  
Dunkirk on the edge of Lake Erie on her way to Buffalo. She planned 
to spend Thursday in the Buffalo area before ending her latest New 
York foray with stops Friday in Rochester. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
