<DOCNO> APW19990804.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 15:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Cut Debate Previews Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the veto clash now taking shape,  
Republicans intend to trumpet the benefits of tax cuts for 
individuals, families, students and others. President Clinton and 
Democrats will talk darkly of a GOP plan that shortchanges 
Medicare, Social Security and other programs Americans hold dear. 
</P>
<P>
	The outcome of their struggle will determine not only the fate  
of tax cuts and other major legislation over the next two months, 
but also help shape the 2000 election campaign that will decide 
control of the White House and Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope the president will not veto this,'' Texas GOP Rep. Bill  
Archer, the chief House tax-writer, said of the $792 billion 
measure. ``Every income taxpayer in America will get relief in this 
bill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton has repeatedly said he will cast a veto, and  
Republicans crafted a final House-Senate compromise designed to 
maximize the political price that he and his Democratic supporters 
will pay for it. 
</P>
<P>
	Tax rates would come down by 1 percentage point, a reduction  
that means higher proportional cuts for the lowest bracket than the 
highest. The marriage penalty would be eliminated. The 
self-employed would be allowed to deduct the full cost of health 
insurance premiums from their taxes. The cost of education would be 
cut to students who borrow money. Individuals would be permitted to 
contribute more money to tax-deductible retirement accounts. 
Farmers would benefit. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle previewed the  
case Wednesday in opposition. ``I will refuse to sign any plan that 
signs away our commitment to America's future, Social Security, 
Medicare, paying down the debt,'' the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	And Daschle said the measure offered ``the sun and the moon and  
the stars ... for special interests all over the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``But if I were a student in school, if I were a senior citizen  
on Medicare looking for prescription drugs, if I were a farmer, if 
I were just about anybody but those few thousand people who are 
going to be beneficiaries of this major rip-off, I would wonder 
whether or not the sun and the moon and the stars will be available 
for them,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders hope to secure final passage for the measure by  
Thursday or Friday. It won't be sent to the White House until after 
Labor Day, though. 
</P>
<P>
	That way, rank-and-file Republicans can spend the August  
congressional recess describing the benefits of the measure to 
their constituents. And Clinton would be deprived of a 
headline-grabbing veto ceremony with GOP lawmakers dispersed and 
unable to respond effectively. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very good for us to take this tax message home,'' said  
Rep. Roy Blunt, R-Mo., the chief deputy whip of House Republicans. 
``If we want to give money back (in tax cuts) as the first priority 
and they want to spend it, that's a good issue for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is a theme that Republicans stress. ``We want to cut taxes  
and the president wants to spend (the surplus),'' Senate Majority 
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said recently. ``That's what the 
fighting is all about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rank and file lawmakers will be supplied with material for their  
appearances back home, while Speaker Dennis Hastert and Lott are 
both expected to make appearances in scattered locations around the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP message will be that Republicans passed tax cuts only  
after proposing ``lock box'' legislation that sets aside $2 
trillion in projected surpluses to be available for Social Security 
reform. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, sometime this fall, after the veto has faded from the  
headlines, Republicans in Congress on the one hand and Clinton on 
the other will have to decide whether to reach across party lines 
and attempt to fashion a compromise that would cover tax cuts, 
Medicare and domestic spending as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Divisions are likely in both camps on that issue.  
</P>
<P>
	Some Democrats favor passage of a middle-ground tax cut. Others  
can be expected to oppose compromise, believing it would only help 
the image of House Republicans. But they are already nervous that 
Clinton will decide to work with the GOP, as he did on welfare 
reform in 1996 and the balanced budget agreement of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Republicans, some prefer to let the issue ride through  
the 2000 elections, confident it will give their presidential 
nominee and congressional candidates a winning hand. Others, 
principally in the House, prefer accomplishment over gridlock to 
show they can govern effectively. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a judgment question,'' says Rep. Tom Davis, the Virginia  
Republican who chairs the GOP campaign committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The fate of the GOP majority may turn on the answer.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- David Espo is chief congressional correspondent  
for The Associated Press. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
