<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> One Million Fire Sprinklers Recalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As many as a million fire sprinklers were  
recalled today by the Consumer Product Safety Commission because 
they may fail to work. 
</P>
<P>
	The sprinklers were installed in nursing homes, hospitals,  
schools and other buildings nationwide from 1961 to 1976. Mealane 
Corp., formerly Star Sprinkler Co. of Philadelphia, has agreed to 
replace the sprinkler heads, the piece responsible for the 
malfunction. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission discovered the defect in an ongoing  
fire-sprinkler investigation. During tests, 67 percent of those 
sampled failed to activate properly, said commission spokesman Ken 
Giles. 
</P>
<P>
	No injuries have been reported, but the sprinklers allegedly  
failed during a 1991 fire at a Warsaw, Ind., nursing home, Giles 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of its investigation, the commission in October recalled  
more than 8 million sprinklers made by Omega, the second-largest 
manufacturer of the devices. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know if there is a problem, but we are checking and  
investigating other brands,'' Giles said. 
</P>
<P>
	The recalled Star sprinklers are dry-type model numbers D-1,  
RD-1, RE-1, E-1 and ME-1. Owners should call (800) 866-7807 for 
more information on the recall. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
