<DOCNO> APW19990804.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 20:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stottlemyre Throws Well in Tuscon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Todd Stottlemyre had a strong outing in his first  
rehabilitation appearance in a game Wednesday and remains on target 
for a return to the Arizona Diamondbacks rotation on Aug. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	``My arm feels great,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Stottlemyre, attempting to come back from a partial tear of his  
rotator cuff, threw four shutout innings in Tucson for the 
Diamondbacks' team in the Arizona Rookie League. He allowed three 
hits, struck out five and walked one. Of his 58 pitches, 40 were 
strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	``His stuff is as good or better than it was before he was  
hurt,'' said pitching coach Mark Connor, who marveled at how 
quickly Stottlemyre has been able to come back from the injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Stottlemyre said he had a restless night and was up at 5 a.m. to  
prepare for the 10 a.m. appearance against the Mexican All-Stars. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his biggest jolt came a half-hour before the first pitch  
when players from the opposing team approached him with cameras and 
baseballs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The opposing team wanted to take pictures with me and have me  
sign baseballs,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stottlemyre, injured while pitching against the San Francisco  
Giants on May 17, refused to undergo surgery because he wanted to 
try to come back this season. He has worked extensively on weights 
and exercises under the supervision of the team's trainers to 
improve the strength around the tear. In the process, he said, 
``I'm stronger than I've ever been in my career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stottlemyre said his competitive juices were flowing after he  
had a runner on first and second with one out. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like, `Jeez, I don't want to go back to Phoenix giving  
up a couple of runs,''' he said. ``So the last couple of hitters, I 
geared it up a little bit. Especially that last hitter, I really 
went maximum effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``To be able to do that, to reach back and get a little extra  
and make the pitches and do it pain-free, was nice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stottlemyre is to make two more starts in the minor leagues,  
next Monday again in the Arizona Rookie League, then five days 
later for a team yet to be determined. He plans to be up to 90 to 
95 pitches by his last rehabilitation start. 
</P>
<P>
	He said there was a time in the first weeks after the injury  
that he wondered if he'd ever pitch again. 
</P>
<P>
	``Really for the first time in my career, it was almost like I  
had one foot out of the game,'' Stottlemyre said. ``I was scared 
that maybe it would be over. But for some reason, I feel good 
again.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
