<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Titans' Lyons Likely Out for Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The odds of defensive end Pratt Lyons  
playing this season are ``very, very slim'' following a car 
accident that broke a bone in his neck, Tennessee Titans coach Jeff 
Fisher said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons was speeding on a curvy road Tuesday night when he lost  
control of his car and crashed down the embankment and into trees. 
Fisher said the collision threw the 6-foot-5, 295-pound Lyons 
through the windshield. 
</P>
<P>
	``The good Lord was kind to us,'' Dr. Burton Elrod said. ``Pratt  
was very fortunate. Anything in the neck is a game of millimeters. 
But there was no neurological injury. No signs of swelling in the 
spinal cord.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elrod said Lyons experienced no paralysis and could be released  
from the hospital within days. Tests continued Wednesday night, and 
he was listed in stable condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons apparently was knocked unconscious by the collision but  
later walked back up to the road and flagged down a passing 
motorist. He felt well enough that he used a flashlight to retrieve 
his cell phone and playbook from his car before being taken to 
Baptist Hospital by ambulance, Fisher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police reports listed excessive speed as the cause of the crash,  
but no citations will be issued, the department said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons started 12 games at left end in 1998 and was competing  
with top draft pick Jevon Kearse for playing time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have to go on and pick up the slack,'' Fisher  
said. ``He will be missed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Teammates declined to comment on Lyons' condition after  
practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons had been staying with most of the team in a hotel across  
the road from the practice facility. But he took a drive after team 
meetings, and Fisher said the accident happened about an hour 
before the 11:30 p.m. curfew. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors originally thought the injury was limited to cuts and  
bruises. But the broken bone was found after the 24-year-old end 
reported stiffness in his neck. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether Lyons needs surgery will depend on how the bone heals.  
Elrod said fusing the bone to another vertebra is always an option 
but that Lyons should be able to return to football. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons reported to training camp 15 pounds lighter, and Fisher  
said he had been playing ``head and shoulders'' above last season 
when he had two sacks and 47 tackles, including 13 quarterback 
pressures. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
