<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Asian Stock Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed lower  
Wednesday, led by a fall in Tokyo, the region's largest market. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, stock prices fell on continued investor concern that  
the Japanese yen's strength against the U.S. dollar will hurt 
Japanese exporters, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 284.55 points,  
or 1.58 percent, to close at 17,685.38. On Tuesday, the average 
finished up 144.23 points, or 0.81 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad and  
thus less competitive, and reduces the dollar-denominated earnings 
of Japanese exporters when translated into yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 115.10 yen at late-afternoon, down 0.30 yen  
from late Tuesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level 
of 115.28 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Malaysian shares plunged 3.8 percent on programmed selling by  
foreign investors, traders said. The Composite Index, which tracks 
100 blue-chip stocks, lost 28.82 points to end at 719.52. 
</P>
<P>
	News that the prominent head of stock broker firm TA Securities  
was arrested and charged earlier in the day in Malaysia's session 
court under the country's Securities Industries Act poured more 
cold water on trading sentiment 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, gains in top banking stocks pushed Hong Kong  
stocks higher for their fourth straight day of gains. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index ended up 117.18 points, 0.9  
percent, at 13,591.02. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan shares ended lower as concerns over tensions with  
mainland China continued to weigh heavily on investor sentiment. 
The market's key Weighted Price Index closed 64.39 points or 0.9 
percent lower at 7,110.80. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed virtually unchanged. The Straits  
Times Index gained a marginal 0.63 point to end at 2,144.00. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine stocks rose as a slew of corporate rumors  
whetted the appetites of local investors for a number of issues. 
The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index closed 15.92 points, 
or 0.7 percent, higher at 2,372.05. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed higher on expectations Daewoo Group's  
restructuring will hasten. The Korea Composite Stock Price Index 
gained 2.12 points, or 0.2 percent, to end at 975.45. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian shares closed lower with many potential  
investors sitting on the sidelines amid concerns that U.S. interest 
rates will rise later this month. The All Ordinaries Index closed 
down 26.5 points, or 0.9 percent, at 3,005.7. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed virtually unchanged.  
The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index shed 1.68 points to 2,178.43. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stock prices closed lower as investors sold  
banking and finance shares. The Stock Exchange of Thailand index 
shed 4.64 points, or 1.0 percent, to close at 451.43. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares fell on a technical correction after  
a sharp rise Tuesday. The Jakarta Stock Exchange's Composite Index 
ended 4.591 points, or 0.7 percent, lower at 614.395. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
