<HEADLINE> Buccaneers, Punter Royals Reunite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Punter Mark Royals signed with the Tampa Bay  
Buccaneers on Wednesday, rejoining the team he left seven years ago 
as a free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	Royals, 34, led the NFC with a 45.6-yard average on 88 punts for  
New Orleans last season. He played two seasons with the Bucs from 
1990-91 before spending the next seven with the Saints, Pittsburgh 
Steelers and Detroit Lions. 
</P>
<P>
	The 11th-year pro has a 42.5-yard career average and will  
compete in training camp with rookie Aron Langley and Eddie Howard, 
who punted in two games for the San Francisco 49ers last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Royals, who makes his offseason home in Tampa, joined the team  
before the second practice of the day. The job he's trying to win 
was held last year by Tommy Barnhardt, the player who replaced 
Royals in New Orleans after last season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bucs, in the market for an experienced punter, worked out  
Royals, John Kidd, Tommy Hutton, Tommy Thompson and Greg Montgomery 
on July 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, first-round draft pick Anthony McFarland practiced  
for the first time since signing a five-year contract worth up to 
$8.5 million. He agreed to terms Tuesday, ending a three-day 
holdout. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can think you're in great shape, but you put the pads on  
and they tell you something else,'' McFarland said. ``It was good 
to get out there, run around a little bit and get some contact. It 
lets you know where you stand.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
