<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House To Vote on Inventors' Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House is nearing a vote on legislation  
aimed at protecting the rights of inventors while bringing patent 
procedures more in line with international practices. Opponents say 
it could make small-scale inventors vulnerable to big corporations 
and foreign countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation guarantees 17 years of patent protection after  
the Patent and Trademark Office has granted a patent. It requires 
publication of a patent application after 18 months, conforming to 
practices in Europe and Japan, but allows an inventor to stop 
publication if applying only in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, its chief sponsor, Rep. Howard Coble, R-N.C., said in  
debate Tuesday night, would ``bring our patent and trademark system 
into the 21st century to the benefit of American inventors and 
American consumers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coble's bill was modified considerably from legislation that  
narrowly passed the House two years ago but was stalled in the 
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., the most vocal opponent two  
years ago, said he strongly supports the new bill because it would 
better protect inventors from those who would take advantage of 
early publication to steal their secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	He called the compromise plan ``a major victory for the  
independent inventor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Phyllis Schlafly of the conservative Eagle Forum, long an  
opponent of the legislation, said that even with the changes the 
bill would result in big corporations and foreign companies 
stealing the inventions of individual inventors. 
</P>
<P>
	Publication of applications, she said, was sought by  
multinational corporations ``that want to control all innovation 
and therefore look upon independent inventors as their natural 
enemies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would protect inventors from disreputable invention  
promoters who overcharge to help get patents processed and 
guarantee 17 years of protection after a patent is granted. The 
previous bill called for 20 years after application, which could 
have shortened protection time because the Patent and Trademark 
Office sometimes takes more than three years to process an 
application. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would provide a limited defense to a charge of  
patent infringement for an earlier inventor who has made good-faith 
commercial use of an invention patented by another. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also aims, through early publication, to counter the  
practice of ``submarining,'' in which people delay action on their 
patent applications and then file huge lawsuits against 
competitors, who, not knowing a patent is on file, come out with 
similar products. 
</P>
<P>
	Coble and others argued that the 18-month provision would help  
small-scale inventors by letting investors know what is being 
developed and encouraging them to bring the new products to market. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate has yet to consider the legislation.  
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1907.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
