<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Newspaper Carrier Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAULT STE. MARIE, Mich. (AP) -- A former newspaper carrier who  
gunned down an executive at his old paper apologized to his 
victim's family before a judge sentenced him to life in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Nathan Hanna, 40, was convicted of killing Anthony Gillespie at  
The Evening News of Sault Ste. Marie with two shotgun blasts on 
July 23, 1998. Hanna's attorney said he was insane and believed 
Gillespie, 48, was the Antichrist. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury rejected Hanna's plea of innocent by reason of insanity  
in June. It found him guilty of murder but mentally ill, which 
amounts to a recommendation that he get treatment in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to say I'm sorry to the Gillespie family. I regret  
there is nothing that can be changed,'' Hanna said Tuesday before 
the sentence was read. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Nicholas Lambros denied a defense motion to set aside the  
jury verdict. Lambros also tacked on two years for a firearms 
violation. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Elizabeth Church said the case would be  
appealed. 
</P>
<P>
	Lauren Rubin, who is engaged to Gillespie's son, sobbed as she  
read a statement on behalf of the family. She recalled Gillespie's 
joy at learning of the planned marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dad was looking forward to so much -- our wedding, being a  
grandfather, growing old with the love of his life, his wife,'' Ms. 
Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nathan Hanna murdered our dad. He murdered our family. He  
murdered our faith in humanity. He murdered our future. He murdered 
our happiness. One evil man has taken away so much,'' she said. 
``This murderer must not be given the opportunity to strike 
again.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
