<HEADLINE> Dollar Down Against Yen, Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen and the euro in  
New York Wednesday as a shaky stock market and strong economic data 
weighed heavily on the currency. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0771, up  
from $1.0676 late Tuesday. The dollar also was quoted at 114.29 
Japanese yen, down from 115.28. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks ended lower Wednesday despite an early rally, and data on  
U.S. factory orders came in stronger than many expected, prompting 
new worries that the Fed may raise interest rates to cool off the 
economy. Higher rates could hurt stock and bond markets, which in 
turn could put downward pressure on the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4844 Swiss francs, down from  
1.4968, and 1.4902 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4936. The British 
pound rose to $1.6223 from $1.6205. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Wednesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8159 German 
marks, down from 1.8318; 6.0901 French francs, down from 6.1425. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
