<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Accused Starbucks Slayer Indicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A man accused of murdering three workers at a  
Starbucks coffee shop in the trendy Georgetown section of the 
nation's capital was charged Wednesday with a host of other crimes, 
including racketeering. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the District of Columbia has no death penalty,  
prosecutors indicated they could seek it against Carl Derick Cooper 
under the federal racketeering charges. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal grand jury returned a 48-count indictment against  
Cooper charging him with six armed robberies, the attempted murder 
of an off-duty police officer in Maryland, a bank robbery and a 
total of four murders. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today's indictment charges Mr. Cooper with leading a small but  
violent racketeering enterprise,'' said U.S. Attorney Wilma Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooper, 30, was to be arraigned Thursday before a federal  
magistrate. 
</P>
<P>
	He was arrested last March and charged with the July 6, 1997  
murders of Emory Allen Evans, 25, Aaron David Goodrich, 18, and 
Mary Caitrin Mahoney, 24. The three employees of the Starbucks 
coffee shop were killed during a pre-dawn robbery attempt after the 
shop had just closed. 
</P>
<P>
	According to investigators, more than $10,000 was in the shop's  
safe at the time but Cooper left without taking anything, 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis said convictions on any of the racketeering charges  
related to the Starbucks slayings could make Cooper eligible for 
the death penalty under federal law. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to speculate as to what the result is going to  
be, but we will make that determination and recommendation to the 
attorney general as soon as we can,'' Lewis said. 
</P>
<P>
	District Councilman Harold Brazil said he would defer to the  
prosecutor on determining whether the death penalty under federal 
charges should be sought. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bringing this person to justice and seeking very harsh  
punishment if he's found guilty would be appropriate,'' said 
Brazil, who chairs the city council's Judiciary and Criminal 
Justice Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment alleges that Cooper was responsible for several  
crimes between 1993 and 1997, including the murder of a private 
security guard in 1993 in the lobby of an apartment building. 
</P>
<P>
	It also charges him with 1996 robberies of a pizza restaurant  
and a bank in Maryland and a massage parlor in Harrisburg, Pa., and 
the wounding of a Prince George's County, Md., police officer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
