<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston Chicken Claims Buyout Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Boston Chicken Inc. has asked a federal Bankruptcy  
Court in Phoenix to change the process for bidding on its assets 
after receiving a buyout offer. 
</P>
<P>
	An investment group calling itself the Boston Market Acquisition  
Co., led by Jack Baum of Dallas-based Sagebrook Investments, has 
offered to buy Boston Chicken's assets for $140 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston Chicken's board of directors approved the financial terms  
of the sale on July 30, according to court documents. 
</P>
<P>
	In a motion filed Tuesday, the company asked the court to amend  
portions of orders issued in June and July which require two 
creditors, GE Capital Corp. and Bank of America, to approve any 
purchase proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston Chicken, the parent company of the Boston Market  
restaurant chain, sought U.S. Bankruptcy Court protection from its 
creditors in October 1998 as it attempted to reorganize its 
finances while continuing to operate. 
</P>
<P>
	Baum told the Associated Press on Wednesday that his group  
believes the company's management team has the potential to take 
the brand forward once the company emerges from the 
court-supervised reorganization. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is very rare for a company to go through bankruptcy and  
maintain such high brand recognition,'' he said. ``Market research 
shows people like the company's product and trust the name.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baum said he has no plans to change the company's management  
structure. He also said the company will continue its licensing 
agreement with H.J Heinz Co., begun in June, to sell packaged food 
products in supermarkets nationwide under the Boston Market name. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to focus on three things: we are going to  
leverage the brand and work with Heinz to continue selling it in 
supermarkets; we are going to revitalize our 866 stores; and we are 
going to begin to develop our foreign markets,'' he said. ``We are 
going to move the company forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Wednesday, Boston Chicken stock slipped 3 1/4 cents to  
37 3/4 cents a share. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
