<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A's Prospect Goes On Power Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Maybe it's the cereal that Adam Piatt  
munches on in the clubhouse prior to batting practice. 
</P>
<P>
	That would be as good an explanation as any to the power surge  
Piatt has had in professional baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	In 172 games at Mississippi State from 1995-97, and while using  
aluminum bats, Piatt had just 22 home runs. 
</P>
<P>
	This season, the 23-year-old Piatt is leading all minor leaguers  
with 34 homers and 110 RBIs through 110 games for Double-A Midland 
in the Texas League. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't know ... I think just growing up a little bit,  
getting more physically mature and certainly a better understanding 
of the pitchers and how they are going to work me,'' Piatt said. 
</P>
<P>
	Piatt says he's as surprised as anyone at the numbers, which  
also include a .340 batting average, a league-leading 103 runs 
scored and a .720 slugging percentage for Oakland's farm club. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't set goals as far as numbers go, but I thought  
if I hit 25 homers, it would be a great year,'' Piatt said before 
Midland wrapped up a six-game series at Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	Piatt is already well past what he would have considered a great  
year in his second full professional season. And the RockHounds, 
after having Wednesday off, still have 30 games left. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just had to reassess, and I have to keep working and going  
out and trying to improve the last month of the season,'' he said. 
``It just comes down to mental toughness. You certainly get tired, 
but at the same time, you're playing a game and you have to have 
fun doing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Piatt was taken in the eighth round of the 1997 draft by the  
Oakland A's, which selected the third baseman while Mississippi 
State was playing in the College World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	During a short season at Medford, Ore., in the summer of 1997,  
Piatt made the transition to wood bats by hitting .292 with 13 home 
runs in 216 at-bats. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Piatt led the Class A California League with 107  
extra-base hits. That included 20 homers, 16 of them coming in the 
last two months of his only season at Modesto. 
</P>
<P>
	After the quick progress Piatt has made, and the success he is  
having this season, expect the A's to put the third 
baseman-designated hitter on their 40-man protected roster after 
this season. If not, he becomes a free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are happy with my progress right now,'' Piatt said.  
``They are not going to divulge too much in where I'm headed, but 
they certainly have let me know they are happy with my progress and 
they're happy with me as a prospect. So that's very positive.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
