<HEADLINE> Chase Buys Mellon's Mortgage Outfit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chase Manhattan Corp.'s mortgage subsidiary has  
agreed to purchase the residential mortgage business of Mellon 
Bank, N.A. 
</P>
<P>
	Chase was the nation's third-largest residential mortgage  
originator last year, writing $85 billion in new loans, while 
Mellon originated $8 billion. Chase moved to first place in the 
first two quarters of this year, passing Countrywide and Norwest 
Mortgage. 
</P>
<P>
	``This acquisition expands our customer base significantly, by  
25 percent,'' said Thomas Jacob, Chase Manhattan Mortgage Corp.'s 
chairman and chief executive, on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	With the acquisition, Chase would rise to first place from third  
in servicing residential loans, surpassing Bank of America and 
Norwest, said Steve Kim, research director at Inside Mortgage 
Finance, an industry newsletter. 
</P>
<P>
	Chase Manhattan Mortgage, based in Edison, N.J., serviced a  
portfolio of $327 billion in residential loans last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchase, the terms of which were not disclosed, includes  
Mellon's $55 billion servicing portfolio and 630 customers. The 
Pittsburgh-based Mellon currently ranks fourteenth in mortgage 
servicing, Kim said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
