<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants' Jones Getting His Chance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- If Cedric Jones is going to make something  
of his NFL career, this is his chance with the New York Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	Heading into training camp, Jones is the Giants' starting  
defensive right end. The job opened when Chad Bratzke left to sign 
a $30 million contract with the Indianapolis Colts. 
</P>
<P>
	All Jones has to do is produce, something he hasn't done much  
since being taken with the fifth pick overall in the 1996 draft. 
His stats for three years show 39 tackles and four sacks in 41 
games, including three starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year alone, Bratzke had 80 tackles and 11 sacks.  
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody worries about Cedric,'' defensive line coach Denny  
Marcin said. ``I don't worry about Cedric. He'll be fine, if he 
stays healthy. He's 0-for-3 years there, you know. He has to 
overcome that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones' first year was somewhat of a writeoff because he came to  
camp late and then was slowed by hamstring and eye injuries. A 
sprained knee and a leg injury limited him to nine games in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	But just when it seemed like Jones was becoming another  
first-round bust like so many of the Giants' other draft picks in 
the '90s, things turned around last year. Jones stayed healthy, got 
his weight down to around 270 -- his college playing weight -- and 
started producing. Eighteen of his tackles and all four of his 
sacks came last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I have more of a sense of urgency,'' Jones said after  
practice at the University at Albany. ``I know from day one that I 
am going to be out there, but I want to make sure I stay out 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones is cutting no corners. He's become a workaholic on and off  
the field, which is one of the ways he cut his weight. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-4 career sack leader at Oklahoma weighed in at 268  
pounds for training camp -- more than 30 pounds lighter than most 
offensive tackles. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you try to battle a 300-pounder and fight with them toe to  
toe all day, you are not going to win,'' Jones said. ``You have to 
keep them off balance and then try to knock them out and 
sneak-punch them. That's where speed and quickness help you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two-time Pro Bowl defensive end Michael Strahan also is helping.  
He's taken Jones under his wing. The two seem to show up every day 
for lunch together, making sure there are no misunderstandings. 
</P>
<P>
	Strahan and Bratzke were much like that.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not even comparing myself to Chad and what he did and what  
I do,'' Jones said. ``I'm trying to go out and do the things I do 
best to make this team succeed. First and foremost I have to worry 
about myself and make sure I take care of my responsibility.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 18:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Linebackers Aplenty for Packers Now </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Green Bay linebackers coach Johnny  
Holland has reason to smile these days. 
</P>
<P>
	With the addition of proven veterans Anthony Davis and Lamont  
Hollinquest, the Packers could be building their deepest 
linebacking corps in recent memory. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis was signed last week as a free agent from Kansas City,  
where he led the Chiefs in tackles over the last four seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the Packers re-signed Lamont Hollinquest, who was  
waived by the Chiefs in July after leaving Green Bay as a free 
agent following last season. He was Green Bay's top backup last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Immediately, the Packers' linebacker depth went from a concern  
to a strength. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we have taken an upgrade,'' starting outside  
linebacker Brian Williams said. ``Anthony Davis has a lot of 
experience and led his team in tackles the last couple of years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then we added Lamont. He knows all the positions.''  
</P>
<P>
	Holland said the additions should mean improvement for all the  
linebackers. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you bring in competition, it always makes you better,''  
he said. ``We have some solid guys there. I'm pleased with all the 
guys right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Williams, George Koonce and Bernardo Harris starting, the  
Packers feel their linebacking corps can compete with any other 
unit in the Packers' recent past. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would think so,'' Williams said. ``I don't think we've had  
this much depth, this much experience. Besides Jude (Waddy), Davis 
and Lamont have been in the league longer than I have. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're going to be one of the better linebacking  
corps,'' Waddy said. ``We're a strong part of the defense. I can't 
wait to get started.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis had 117 tackles last season for the Chiefs, 10 more than  
Green Bay's leading tackler, Williams, had last season, and is 
obviously hoping for a starting spot. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any time you have a guy breathing down your back it makes you  
play better,'' Holland said. ``If you go down, you got a guy 
filling your spot who can play. Then he may shine, and it may be 
hard to take him off the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``You want competition. Our three starters want competition. We  
have a good group of guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Packers linebackers had no pass interceptions and the  
starters had just five sacks. 
</P>
<P>
	New coach Ray Rhodes wants more from this unit, which is why it  
was important to add Davis and Hollinquest. They add flexibility to 
a unit that lacked it last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel good about our linebacker depth now, but coming into  
camp we were a little nervous about it,'' Rhodes said. ``We didn't 
have enough depth. With Davis and Hollinquest coming in, that gives 
us a lot of depth.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
