<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jim Brown, Wife Discuss 911 Call </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The wife of Hall of Fame football star Jim  
Brown said in a 911 call that he beat her car with a shovel and 
threatened to kill her. On Wednesday, she denied ever feeling 
threatened and claimed police overreacted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I dialed 911 and I used it because I was angry. I was trying  
to get leverage,'' Monique Brown said Wednesday at the couple's 
Hollywood Hills home, where the media was summoned to hear the 911 
audio tape. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no reason to call. There was no emergency,'' she  
said, her husband at her side. ``I did not feel threatened at any 
time -- never felt I was in any danger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the 911 emergency call transcript provided by the couple,  
Mrs. Brown identifies herself only as Monique Brown and she doesn't 
mention her ex-football player husband is Jim Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Brown, who was making the call from a neighbor's home, told  
the operator: ``He's inside the house, he just beat my car with a 
shovel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later she said: ``He has a gun in the house but he doesn't use  
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The operator asked at one point: ``He didn't hit you today?''  
</P>
<P>
	``Not today,'' Mrs. Brown answered.  
</P>
<P>
	``OK. But if there's a history of domestic violence, right?''  
the operator said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes,'' Mrs. Brown said.  
</P>
<P>
	``And he threatened to kill you today?''  
</P>
<P>
	``Yes.''  
</P>
<P>
	The Browns wouldn't comment about the reference to a history of  
domestic violence, but lawyer William Graysen said the former 
football star has no recent criminal record for domestic violence. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Brown has a long history of arrests. In 1986, his  
then-fiancee declined to press charges after he allegedly beat her. 
In 1985, charges that he struck and raped a woman were dropped. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1978, he was fined and served a day in jail for beating up a  
golf partner. In 1971, charges that he battered two women were 
dropped after they failed to testify at his trial. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1968, he was accused of assault with intent to murder when  
his then-girlfriend was found semi-conscious under the balcony of 
his apartment. The charge was dropped when the woman said she had 
fallen. And in 1965, a jury found Brown innocent of assaulting an 
18-year-old girl in Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, 63, denied threatening his wife and alleged that police  
harassed and coerced her into making abuse statements. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't threaten people. In fact, I've never threatened  
people. ... I have no idea what's going to happen. I know that I 
should be exonerated,'' Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, who was arrested June 15, pleaded innocent July 9 to one  
count of making terrorist threats and one count of vandalism, both 
misdemeanors. Trial was set for Aug. 17. 
</P>
<P>
	Lara Bloomquist, who supervises the City Attorney's domestic  
violence unit, said Mrs. Brown, 25, was on the trial witness list, 
but ``whether she'll be for the prosecution remains to be seen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bloomquist said Mrs. Brown's contention that the case wasn't  
serious was not unusual in domestic violence cases. About 
two-thirds of domestic violence victims seen by her office recant 
their stories, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This wasn't an issue of recantation,'' Mrs. Brown said  
Wednesday. ``From the moment they got there, I was telling them 
there was no threat. I just wanted to come home. I wanted to come 
home, back to my husband.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, Brown could be sentenced to 18 months in jail,  
three years' probation and ordered to complete domestic violence 
counseling. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said it angered him that 15 to 20 police cars showed up at  
his home and officers armed with shotguns arrested him. He said 
Wednesday the show of force was a police overreaction because he's 
a black celebrity who works with ex-gang members and ex-convicts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm considered one of those individuals that are not  
controlled,'' Brown said. ``They have a record of not being able to 
get me. I think they have a policy that they would like to get me 
... what you want to do is nullify all voices in the community that 
are strong and have influence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The number of officers sent to Brown's home wasn't immediately  
known. 
</P>
<P>
	``The call came from his wife and we were responding to a  
domestic violence call. There were indications she was in fear,'' 
Officer Guillermo Compos said Wednesday. ``We have responded to his 
home before because there were problems that were there before.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
