<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Honda Vows To Stay Independent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) -- Honda Motor Co. is committed to  
remaining independent despite the trend toward consolidation of the 
auto industry, president Hiroyuki Yoshino said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at an industry conference, Yoshino disputed the  
conventional wisdom of industry executives that only large, global 
automakers with great economies of scale will survive in the 21st 
century. 
</P>
<P>
	``They argue that the challenge of global customer satisfaction  
is a job description for which only large companies need apply,'' 
Yoshino said. ``We believe that success in the future has little to 
do with size.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the past year, No. 3 U.S. automaker Chrysler Corp. merged  
with Germany's Daimler-Benz AG, No. 2 Ford Motor Co. bought Volvo 
Cars of Sweden, and France's Renault SA bought a stake in Japan's 
Nissan Motor Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoshino said Honda does not need to merge with another automaker  
to expand its global presence. It already has 100 plants in 34 
countries, part of its longstanding policy of developing and 
building cars, motorcycles and other motorized products in the 
markets where they're sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese automaker's goal is to combine the speed,  
flexibility and efficiency of a small company with the global reach 
and technological strength of a large company. Honda is the world's 
eighth-largest automaker by production. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda has proven that a car plant doesn't need high volumes --  
more than 200,000 vehicles -- to be profitable, he said. In China, 
Brazil and Thailand, Honda has built plants with capacities of 
10,000 to 30,000 vehicles that make money. 
</P>
<P>
	``In each case, we first entered the market with motorcycle  
production that requires only one-tenth the investment of an auto 
plant,'' Yoshino said. ``This serves as an effective stepping stone 
to auto production.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Honda is embarking on a new manufacturing system at its two  
largest Japanese plants that will allow them to produce more models 
on fewer assembly lines. Equipment will be designed to produce 
multiple products at the push of a button, allowing Honda to shift 
production to models in the greatest demand, Yoshino said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
