<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Up on Weather / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures advanced strongly a  
third day Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid expectations 
recent hot, dry weather will reduce expected bumper harvests. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures prices have rallied sharply in the past week on the  
unexpected turn in fortunes for a crop that many originally thought 
would exceed all estimates for production. 
</P>
<P>
	Hot, dry weather has taken its toll on crops in Illinois, one of  
the two largest growing states, and eastward. 
</P>
<P>
	While corn and soybean harvests likely will remain quite large,  
the reductions could come at a fortuitous time. Demand to Asia, a 
key exporting region for U.S. producers, is on the rise as 
countries there shake off economic problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 5 cents to $3.06 1/4 a bushel;  
December corn rose 5 3/4 cents to $2.36 1/2 a bushel; December oats rose 
1 1/4 cents to $1.18 1/4 a bushel; November soybeans rose 15 3/4 cents to 
$4.94 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and lean hog futures were mixed on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, while feeder cattle and pork bellies 
retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose .08 cent to 64.35 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .25 cent to 76.07 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs rose .75 cent to 50.45 cents a pound; August pork bellies fell 
2.90 cents to 56.72 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
