<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 00:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Than 500M Guns Said on Planet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- More than 500 million guns and other small  
arms are circulating around the world, widely used because they are 
lethal, inexpensive, easy to care for and easy to hide, a U.N. 
panel says. 
</P>
<P>
	Assault rifles, machine guns, pistols and grenade-launchers are  
increasingly ``the weapon of choice'' in contemporary conflicts, 
the U.N. Department for Disarmament said in a report Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The excessive and destabilizing accumulation and transfer of  
small arms and light weapons is closely related to the increased 
incidence of internal conflicts and high levels of crime and 
violence,'' the panel said. 
</P>
<P>
	Millions of innocent people, particularly children, have been  
killed by small arms, which are manufactured and sold legally and 
illegally, the report said. About 40 percent of the worldwide flow 
of small arms comes from illicit trafficking that serves warlords, 
drug traffickers, terrorists and other criminals. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also outlined progress being made on implementing  
recommendations in a 1997 U.N. report, including ways to prevent 
and reduce the excessive accumulation and transfer of small arms. 
</P>
<P>
	It also proposed that an international conference on the illicit  
arms trade, which the General Assembly has decided to hold no later 
than 2001, focus on international efforts to prevent, combat and 
eradicate illegal transfers. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, sent to the General Assembly by Secretary-General  
Kofi Annan, urged all states to exercise ``utmost restraint'' in 
transfers of small arms and ammunition to conflict areas. 
</P>
<P>
	In view of the theft of large numbers of weapons from storage  
facilities in many countries, the panel also recommended that all 
nations take measures to prevent loss of weapons through theft, 
corruption or neglect. 
</P>
<P>
	The group said it also wants a study on the feasibility of  
restricting the manufacture and trade in small arms to authorized 
manufacturers and dealers to be completed before the U.N. 
conference. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
