<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 11:10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Don Garber Named MLS Commissioner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Major League Soccer has a new commissioner, and he comes from a  
branch of the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	Don Garber, who had been senior vice president of the NFL's  
international division, was introduced today in New York as the 
successor to Doug Logan, who was removed after serving as the 
league's only commissioner since it started in 1996. Logan's 
contract ran through next season, but the league's financial 
backers were unhappy with the way the MLS has been drawing at the 
gate and its flat TV ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's clear I've lost confidence of the board of governors and  
it's time to move on,'' Logan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Board of Governors chairman Stuart Subotnick of the New York-New  
Jersey MetroStars, who announced the change, said the league needed 
to better connect with the fan. 
</P>
<P>
	``One area we have not moved as positive as we would like starts  
with fan,'' said Subotnick. ``If you want a successful business, 
you need to get the loyalty of the customer, in this case the fan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We started with a bang, it leveled off and we're creeping up  
again. That's OK if you want a middling business. We don't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Logan had predicted a 15 percent increase in average attendance  
from the league's first year to the second. But attendance actually 
fell from 17,406 to 14,619, a 16 percent drop. 
</P>
<P>
	It further fell to 14,312 last season, but has rebounded to  
15,174 through this past weekend's games. 
</P>
<P>
	The 41-year-old Garber will oversee all business operations of  
the 12-team MLS. 
</P>
<P>
	He worked for the NFL for 15 years. During the last three, he  
was in charge of the league's business ventures outside the United 
States, including television production and right distribution and 
various marketing and fan development activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Before taking over as head of NFL International, Garber was vice  
president of business development and special events for NFL 
properties, the league's marketing arm. 
</P>
<P>
	MLS operates under a ``single-entity'' concept in which  
companies invest in the league and receive the rights to operate a 
club. The league contracts with all the players, assigns the major 
stars to clubs in the name of competitive balance and gate 
attraction, and pays them from a central fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the salaries the league negotiates with the players,  
each team must stay under a $1.7 million salary cap. 
</P>
<P>
	Logan said he may be down, but not out.  
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday I was an 'is'. Today I'm a 'was'. Tomorrow, I assure  
you, I'm going to be an 'is' again,'' Logan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no elegant way to say I was fired. You in the media  
have more elegant ways: sacked, axed, ousted. Stuart Subotnick 
allowed me the prerogative to resign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No team has folded or been moved since the MLS began play in  
1996, and Logan oversaw its expansion to Chicago and Miami, 
bringing the league to 12 teams. 
</P>
<P>
	However, flat television ratings have plagued the league since  
the beginning of its second year, and it is still well below the 
average crowd of 17,406 it achieved in its first season. Some team 
officials had grumbled privately about Logan, particularly 
following his dismissal of deputy commissioner Sunil Gulati in 
February. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
