<DOCNO> APW19990804.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 10:26:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nashville Sound: Brad Paisley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Brad Paisley, dark and handsome, was on  
stage singing about lost love to the adoring women of the Wildhorse 
Saloon. 
</P>
<P>
	A guy standing on the dance floor with his enraptured girl  
friend was a little drunk and a lot jealous as he pointed to the 
electrifying singer who had snared the young woman's attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he's so miserable, why doesn't he go kill himself?'' said  
the drunk, spilling beer as he motioned to Paisley. 
</P>
<P>
	But Paisley, basking in the approval of his female fans, didn't  
seem to notice the guy. Nor did the drunk's companion or the rest 
of the audience at the spacious, faux honky-tonk in downtown 
Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	The women especially were loving Paisley, who alternated  
lovelorn ballads with witty, fast-paced tunes about -- well, being 
lovelorn. And when he stormed the edges of the stage during 
fleet-fingered guitar solos, the men cheered, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you think I'll just forget you and decide that I don't love  
you/Do you realize what you're tellin' me to do?'' he sang. ``It's 
like saying don't breathe or don't blink/ ... See I just can't turn 
this off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The drunk shuffled off to the bar to console himself with  
another beer, as his companion shoved through the dance floor to 
get closer to the stage and to Paisley, who has emerged this summer 
as THE breakout country music star of 1999. Only neo-Outlaw duo 
Montgomery-Gentry, ``Ordinary Life'' singer Chad Brock and the band 
Lonestar rival him. 
</P>
<P>
	Paisley is a clever songwriter, effective singer and  
accomplished guitarist in the league of Ricky Skaggs or Steve 
Wariner. He's wholesome without being preachy -- the first song on 
his debut album, ``Who Needs Pictures,'' is about cooling your 
heels in church during a long sermon while itching to go fishing. 
</P>
<P>
	The single, also called ``Who Needs Pictures,'' is selling about  
2,500 copies a week, putting it at No. 9 on the country charts, 
just ahead of Montgomery-Gentry's ``Hillbilly Shoes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Remember, you heard it here first,'' said Naomi Judd when  
Paisley was a recent guest on ``Heart to Heart With Naomi Judd,'' 
her syndicated radio show. ``What we have here is a star. And all 
you girls, he's 26 and real easy on the eyes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moments earlier, Paisley had moved Judd to tears performing his  
song, ``He Didn't Have to Be,'' about a grateful stepson thanking 
the man who married his mother. The song was inspired by the 
relationship his co-writer Kelly Loveless has with his stepson. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do a great song and people notice it,'' Paisley said,  
explaining how the Wildhorse crowd knew the words to ``He Didn't 
Have to Be'' well enough to sing along, even though it hasn't been 
issued as a single yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Paisley, who is from Glen Dale, W.Va., learned the basics of  
country music at the knee of his grandfather, Warren Jarvis, an 
amateur guitar picker. As a child, Jarvis looked after Paisley each 
morning before school when Paisley's parents -- his mother is a 
teacher and father works for the West Virginia Department of 
Highways -- went to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarvis bought Paisley his first guitar, a Sears Dancelctro  
Silvertone, when he was 8. Paisley learned to play standards like 
``Wildwood Flower'' from Jarvis, and first sang in church at 10. 
Jarvis died of cancer a few years ago, but not before seeing his 
protege open for The Judds. The ``Who Needs Pictures'' CD is 
dedicated to him. 
</P>
<P>
	In West Virginia, the most prominent country music radio show is  
Jamboree USA on WWVA in Wheeling. The 66-year-old program is the 
second-oldest radio show to the Grand Ole Opry on Nashville's WSM. 
Paisley played it at 12, and was a regular for eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Doing the Jamboree ... is THE thing that made me who I am,''  
said Paisley, who recently opened for Loretta Lynn in New York City 
and will do the same for Merle Haggard in Nashville. ``That whole 
experience of every Saturday night, getting to open for people as 
legendary as George Jones and Roy Clark. ... 
</P>
<P>
	``You learn real quick what's dying on stage when you say it,''  
he said. ``It gave me a sense of entertainment value for a show as 
opposed to just wanting to sing and trying to imitate people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After two years at West Liberty State College, Paisley had done  
everything he could as a performer in his hometown. A college 
adviser urged him to transfer to Belmont University, which is 
within walking distance of Nashville's Music Row, the center of the 
country music industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had classes called Record Company Operations, and  
Recording Industry 101 and things like that -- Publishing, copyright 
law, stuff I had always wondered about,'' said Paisley, who majored 
in business. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got college credit to learn all that, and they were going to  
let me go and walk into Atlantic Records every day and work there 
for free.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paisley was an intern at Atlantic Records, as well as a music  
management firm and ASCAP, where contacts helped him get a contract 
to write songs for a music publishing company and then a record 
deal with Arista. 
</P>
<P>
	Paisley's experience has made him a confident performer.  
</P>
<P>
	``Are there any single people out there?'' Paisley said to  
whoops from the audience at the Wildhorse. ``Well, I'm single, too 
-- and I HATE it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That set up ``Me Neither,'' Paisley's sly take on approaching  
women in bars, then trying to save face when they turn him town. 
Then he ripped through a guitar solo worthy of his greatest 
inspiration on the instrument -- Skaggs. 
</P>
<P>
	Paisley quieted the crowd by making his last encore a gospel  
song, ``In the Garden.'' It is also the last song on his CD. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time he finished, the drunk was a lot happier, swaying  
arm-in-arm with his girlfriend. ``At first I hated him,'' the man 
said his companion about Paisley. ``But he's all right.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
