<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TV Star in Real-Life Rescue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WRIGHTSVILLE BEACH, N.C. (AP) -- Reality provided a little more  
excitement than his usual TV fiction for ``Dawson's Creek'' actor 
Joshua Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	The actor, who plays Pacey Witter on the series on the WB  
network, and a friend saw two young women who had gotten into 
distress while swimming along the shore near Wrightsville Beach on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, 21, and his unidentified friend dove into the ocean and  
swam out to help the young women, who were floating near the rock 
jetty that separates Masonboro Inlet from the Atlantic Ocean, said 
Coast Guard Petty Officer Jody Howey. 
</P>
<P>
	But when they reached the pair, waves swept them all over the  
jetty and into the inlet, and then the current of the falling tide 
prevented them from getting back to shore, Howey said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Coast Guard boat rescued all four about 7 p.m. and no one was  
injured, Howey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson ``kept them safe and floating until the Coast Guard got  
there. He just helped out somebody who needed it,'' said David 
Hartley, producer of the show filmed in nearby Wilmington 
</P>
<P>
	The young women, who were not identified, were not involved with  
the television show, Hartley said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 10:49:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Warns U.S. on Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China warned the U.S. Congress today against  
backing any move by Taiwan toward independence, saying Beijing was 
ready to pay ``any price'' to defend China's claim to the island. 
</P>
<P>
	The warning came amid renewed tensions between China and Taiwan  
sparked by Taiwan President Lee-Teng-hui's insistence that the two 
sides should deal with each other as one state to another. 
</P>
<P>
	China regarded Lee's July 9 remarks as a move toward  
independence for Taiwan, which has ruled itself separately from 
Beijing since the two sides split in 1949 in a civil war. China 
views the island as a renegade province and has threatened to use 
force to stop it from formally declaring independence. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will defend the state sovereignty and territorial integrity  
of our motherland at any price,'' the official Xinhua News Agency 
quoted a senior legislator as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	The report did not identify him, other than saying he was a  
senior member of the Foreign Affairs Committee of the Chinese 
legislature, the National People's Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The official also accused Rep. Sherrod Brown, D-Ohio, and other  
House members of inflaming tensions between China and Taiwan by 
introducing a bill that ``bluntly advocated'' independence for 
Taiwan, Xinhua said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, introduced July 29 to the House Committee on  
International Relations, will ``gravely damage peace and stability 
in the Asia-Pacific region, as well as the relations between China 
and the United States,'' the legislator was quoted as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	He appealed to Congress to shelve the bill.  
</P>
<P>
	In Taiwan today, Defense Minister Tang Fei said the island's  
armed forces will be tough but restrained amid increased military 
activity over the Taiwan Strait. 
</P>
<P>
	Tang did not comment directly on reports of stepped up sorties  
by planes and ships from both sides. But he said the strait is in 
international waters and Taiwan's key interest is ensuring safe 
usage for civilian aviation and shipping. 
</P>
<P>
	``We follow international law and are extremely self-disciplined  
in the spirit and in the means we use to handle these matters,'' 
Tang said. ``We don't wish to see any provocation but will do what 
is necessary'' to ensure national security. 
</P>
<P>
	Ministry spokesman Kung Fan-ding told the TVBS cable news  
network that military activity in the strait has been ``more than 
normal,'' but added that July and August have traditionally been 
the high season for Chinese training due to optimum weather 
conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Military observers say Taiwan's air force has increased patrols  
in the strait and navy sailors say they have been placed on a 
greater state of readiness. 
</P>
<P>
	Kung denied reports that Chinese military planes and ships have  
crossed the strait's center line, a hazy boundary that the two 
sides generally respect as the limit of their military activity. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. government said Tuesday it was concerned increased  
sorties by China and Taiwan over the waterway could lead to 
accidents and advised both sides against anything that would 
heighten tensions. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has been a pick up of activity by both sides,'' said  
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon. ``We urge both sides to show 
restraint.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 11:00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Promises To Veto Tax Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today promised to veto a  
Republican plan that would lower the tax rate of every American who 
pays income tax. He called the bill ``risky and plainly wrong for 
America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 10-year, $792 billion tax cut package put together by House  
and Senate Republicans would gradually cut 1 percentage point off 
each personal income tax rate. It also would provide relief from 
the so-called marriage penalty, cut the individual capital-gains 
tax rate and eventually eliminate the estate tax. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they conclude this plan and send it to me,'' Clinton said,  
``I will have to veto it. I will refuse to sign any plan that signs 
away our commitment to America's future, Social Security, Medicare, 
paying down the debt.'' Speaking with reporters in the Rose Garden, 
Clinton said the GOP formula would jeopardize the economic success 
the nation has enjoyed under his administration and ``revert to one 
that is a proven failure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with the start of the August vacation at the end of the  
week, negotiators moved with unusual speed over two days of talks 
to resolve differences in the House and Senate bills, each of which 
totaled $792 billion in cuts but differed substantially in details. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and House Speaker  
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., were actively involved in the negotiations, 
while Democrats, who overwhelmingly opposed the GOP plans, were 
shut out of the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Republicans have sequestered themselves in a room in order  
to piece together a political bill they know is going nowhere,'' 
said Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., ranking Democrat on the Ways and 
Means panel. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House brushed off warnings by Lott and House Majority  
Leader Dick Armey that prospects are dimming that Congress and 
Clinton can agree on a tax bill this year. ``The remarks sound like 
two leaders in a sandbox,'' presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart 
said. ``If they don't get their way, they don't want to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the GOP tax numbers ``just don't add up. It's pretty  
clear the Republican leadership is interested in making a political 
statement.'' And he countered a question about the political 
consequences of vetoing a tax cut with assurances that voters are 
cognizant of the administration's economic record. 
</P>
<P>
	``Others will handicap the risks of what the president is going  
to do, but he's going to do it because it's the right thing for the 
public,'' Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has said repeatedly that he will veto the GOP bill  
because he says the tax cut would use up almost all of the 
projected non-Social Security surplus over the next decade, leaving 
almost nothing for needed government programs and paying down the 
national debt. Clinton and most Democrats have said that any cut 
over $300 billion would be unacceptably risky to the nation's 
economic future. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans insist they can return the money to the taxpayers  
that rightfully belongs to them and still have enough to save 
Social Security and Medicare and pay down part of the national 
debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the GOP plan, each of the five tax brackets would go down  
by 1 percentage point. The lowest 15 percent tax bracket would fall 
to 14 percent in 2001, and the highest 39.6 percent bracket would 
become 38.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The House-passed bill included a 10 percent across-the-board tax  
cut, which was strongly criticized by the White House and Democrats 
as disproportionately favoring wealthy taxpayers. The 1 percentage 
point cut would give taxpayers in the 15 percent bracket a 7 
percent cut, better than that in the higher brackets. 
</P>
<P>
	To alleviate the marriage penalty, under which some married  
couples pay more in taxes than if they were single because their 
combined income moves them into a higher bracket, the Republican 
bill would gradually raise the standard deduction for couples until 
it is double the level permitted for individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, it would widen the current 15 percent bracket for  
couples so it would apply to some income that currently is taxed at 
28 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	There would be no cuts in the corporate capital gains tax, but  
personal capital gains taxes would be reduced from 20 percent to 18 
percent on some gains and 10 percent to 8 percent on others -- and 
adjusted annually for inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. William Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Senate Finance  
Committee, said contribution limits to individual retirement 
accounts would rise gradually from $2,000 to $5,000 annually. He 
said the self-employed would be permitted to deduct the entire cost 
of their health insurance premiums. Other officials said medical 
savings accounts, tax-deductible accounts set aside for 
health-related costs, would be more readily available. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP leadership planned to bring the bill before the House on  
Thursday and the Senate on Friday, securing passage before the 
August recess begins. 
</P>
<P>
	However, it would not be sent to the president until after  
Congress returned to work in September, giving supporters the 
chance to return home and tout the bill's benefits to their 
constituents. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans ``would like to take our message to the American  
people,'' Lott said. ``Maybe the president will conclude at some 
point that he needs to work with us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
