<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow, Union Carbide To Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT, Mich. (AP) -- The Dow Chemical Co. and Union Carbide  
Corp. announced today they would merge in a $11.6 billion deal, 
creating the world's second-largest chemical company with an 
estimated $24 billion in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, Union Carbide shareholders will receive 0.537  
shares of Dow Chemical for each of their Union Carbide shares -- or 
$66.96 based on Tuesday's closing price of Dow Chemical's stock. 
</P>
<P>
	The merged company expects to have $3 billion in profits per  
year and about 49,000 employees. The two companies expect to cut 
costs by $500 million with the merger. 
</P>
<P>
	``This transaction is a giant step in our strategy to transform  
Dow into the world's most productive, best 'value-growth' company 
in the chemical industry,'' said William S. Stavropoulos, president 
and chief executive officer of Dow Chemical. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
