<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hatchet Wielder Dies After Jump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAKERSFIELD, Calif. (AP) -- A hatchet-wielding man was pursued by  
police through downtown and later died, apparently from wounds 
suffered when he cut himself on a broken window during the chase. 
</P>
<P>
	David Pollack, 46, died at a hospital Tuesday, the day after he  
was injured in a confrontation that began when he was spotted 
waving a small hatchet near a downtown bus depot, police Sgt. Glen 
Grundeis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Trying to get away Pollack used the hatchet to break into a  
closed business, Grundeis said. When officers followed him inside, 
Pollack threw a piece of computer equipment at them, then crashed 
through a second-story window and landed on an adjacent rooftop, 
breaking and severely lacerating his arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollack stayed on the roof for a time, pacing back and forth and  
waved the hatchet as blood poured from his wounds. He yelled at 
officers, police Lt. Bryan Lynn said, describing his behavior as 
``crazed, deranged.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two officers wrestled with Pollack, but he broke free and slid  
down the roof, falling to the ground. Police then shot him with 
non-lethal bean bags, but ``they didn't have much effect on him,'' 
Grundeis said. ``He didn't really slow down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, the man led police on a brief chase before collapsing.  
</P>
<P>
	An autopsy had not been performed as of early today, and the  
exact cause of death was not available. 
</P>
<P>
	``He probably just went into shock from loss of blood,''  
Grundeis said. ``He was unconscious when he was arrested.'' Police 
estimated the whole confrontation lasted about 15 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	The man's motives were under investigation.  
</P>
<P>
	Grundeis said Pollack suffered no injuries at the hands of  
officers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
