<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American Alters Frequent Flier Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Frequent flier miles with American  
Airlines will last indefinitely as long as passengers use their 
accounts every three years, the air carrier announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	That means the 35 million people enrolled in American's  
AAdvantage program may not ever see mileage expire as long as they 
continue to accrue or use points. 
</P>
<P>
	``All you really have to do is have some activity within 36  
months,'' said Henry Joyner, vice president of marketing for AMR 
Corp., the parent company of American. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, frequent flier miles had a shelf life of about three  
years, depending on the program. 
</P>
<P>
	American's easily has double the number of participants in its  
frequent flier program than other airlines. The Fort Worth, 
Texas-based airline had $695 million worth of flights outstanding 
at the end of 1998. Only an average of about 10 percent of seats 
per flight are available for redemption through frequent flier 
miles. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point it's not clear we need to increase seats,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Joyner said the airline's partnerships with about 20 other  
airlines will give fliers more choices. 
</P>
<P>
	``The real change will be the attractiveness of international  
flights,'' said Joyner. 
</P>
<P>
	American's decision follows Northwest Airlines similar  
announcement in January. Delta Air Lines had dropped most of its 
expiration requirements three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	United Airlines remains the only major carrier that has  
expiration dates. 
</P>
<P>
	``United does have non-expiring rules with their elite  
programs,'' said Randy Peterson, editor of InsideFlyer magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	Telephone messages left with United were not immediately  
returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Frequent flier programs have been a powerful tool for creating  
customer loyalty for the airlines. The miles are used as a virtual 
currency with the airlines redeemable for such things as plane 
tickets, travel packages and hotel stays. Over the last several 
years, program participants have been able to earn miles on the 
ground in almost endless ways. Phone companies, grocers, car rental 
agencies and credit cards offer miles. 
</P>
<P>
	The way mileage is now accrued is partially why airlines are  
dropping their expiration dates. 
</P>
<P>
	Back in 1988 when frequent flier programs were introduced  
literally all mile accrual came from flying. Today, companies buy 
miles from the airlines to give to customers, making the programs 
lucrative for carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Close to half of miles today comes from other program  
activity,'' said Peterson. ``Essentially the airline is being 
prepaid for each seat.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
