<DOCNO> APW19990804.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 23:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Corn Growers Grinning Ear-to-Ear / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FARGO, N.D. (AP) -- Worries that a common petroleum-based  
gasoline additive is polluting the environment have ignited 
optimism among corn growers and ethanol producers in the Upper 
Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's any doubt this could be very positive  
for everyone in our business,'' said Trevor Guthmiller, executive 
director of the Sioux Falls, S.D.-based American Coalition for 
Ethanol. ``And anything we can do to help create demand for the raw 
product is going to be good for the bottom line of the farmer, 
too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A panel of the Environmental Protection Agency has recommended  
the agency immediately begin ``substantial reductions'' of the 
gasoline additive MTBE because of evidence it contaminates 
groundwater. 
</P>
<P>
	The recommendations, some of which would require congressional  
approval, have not been acted on yet by the EPA. 
</P>
<P>
	MTBE -- short for methyl tertiary butyl ether -- is the most  
widely used additive. It is blended with gasoline to produce 
cleaner-burning, oxygenated fuel as required by the federal 
government in more than a dozen of the nation's most polluted 
cities. 
</P>
<P>
	But a study released last month indicated that MTBE is seeping  
into drinking water supplies across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	MTBE producers already are fighting the panel's recommendation  
to phase out use of the product over four years in favor of ethanol 
and other alternatives. 
</P>
<P>
	But few in the ethanol industry believe the arguments will be  
successful. And they already are beginning to prepare for what many 
believe will be a huge increase in the demand for ethanol. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everyone in the industry is excited about this,'' said  
Dwight Enockson, a Washburn-area farmer and member of the North 
Dakota Corn Utilization Council. ``If California alone had to 
switch from MTBE to ethanol, that alone would literally take nearly 
all the ethanol production in the U.S. right now to meet the 
demand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The potential effect for corn producers and ethanol producers  
is tremendous right now,'' added Mark Dillon, executive vice 
president of Golden Growers Cooperative, a North Dakota-based corn 
growers co-op. ``And the industry is working hard at the state and 
federal level to convince leaders that ethanol really is the 
leading alternative to MTBE.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guthmiller said early projections are that if ethanol were to  
replace MTBE, the new demand would use up an additional 240 million 
bushels to 300 million bushels of corn. 
</P>
<P>
	Ethanol adds about 30 cents to each bushel of corn, but ethanol  
supporters said that probably would double if ethanol replaces 
MTBE. Corn prices currently are at about $1.50 per bushel, their 
lowest in a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``The immediate benefit would be much better corn prices for  
farmers,'' added David Kolsrud, vice chairman of Agri-Energy, a 
company that began operating an ethanol plant near the small town 
of Luverne, Minn., about a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it would also provide an economic boon to rural areas like  
ours that build ethanol plants and that haven't really enjoyed the 
economic benefits the rest of the country seems to be enjoying,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ethanol supporters know they still face hurdles. Ethanol costs  
considerably more to make than MTBE, and its production is almost 
completely restricted to the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	To be economically feasible and to meet the demand on the West  
Coast and in the Northeast, some production would need to shift to 
those areas, experts say. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 15:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Education of QB McNown Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PLATTEVILLE, Wis. (AP) -- The contract's been signed, Cade McNown  
is settled into his dorm room and the rounds of introductions are 
over. 
</P>
<P>
	Now it's time to get the rookie quarterback caught up on  
everything he missed in the first 11 days of training camp. And the 
Chicago Bears have, oh, about zero time to get it done. Welcome to 
a crash course, NFL style. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since he missed those 16 practices, he's got to really work  
hard to catch up because you don't want to slow down for everybody 
else,'' offensive coordinator Gary Crowton said Wednesday. ``The 
object is to win. So it's not, `Let's slow down for Cade and not do 
anything offensively.' We can't be like that. He's just got to 
catch up, and he wants to and he's trying to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Getting a new player, especially a rookie, up to speed is never  
easy, but McNown's case is especially challenging. The Bears are 
using a new, wide-open offense that demands a lot from the 
quarterback, and all but two plays of the scheme have already been 
installed. 
</P>
<P>
	There's no apprentice year on the bench, either, like some other  
rookie quarterbacks get. Veteran Erik Kramer was released two days 
before camp began and Shane Matthews, who had been the No. 1, is 
already taking over holding duties for extra points, usually the 
domain of the No. 2 quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	So McNown spends his days either on the practice field or in  
meetings. On Tuesday, his first day at training camp, he spent 
about six hours in one-on-ones with quarterbacks coach John Shoop 
as well as meetings with the other three quarterbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I go up and ask them questions all the time, and nobody's ever  
stiffed me,'' McNown said. 
</P>
<P>
	If he does have any spare time, it's off to the film room or a  
quiet corner so he can study his playbook. There's a little time 
left over to eat and sleep, but not much. 
</P>
<P>
	McNown did learn the basics of the offense during three  
offseason minicamps, but that's no comparison to training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's coming, it's just going to take time,'' Crowton said.  
``I'm just going to take it one practice at a time and try to push 
him as hard as we can without blowing a fuse. But I think people 
who are pushed hard can do very good things, and we're going to 
push him hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Take Wednesday. In just his second practice, McNown was thrown  
into blitz drills, in which the defense comes flying at him as soon 
as he gets the ball, hoping to sack him. He didn't pick up the 
blitz as fast as Matthews, but Crowton said that was to be 
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made some good plays on that, but I also made a couple of  
mistakes,'' McNown said. ``I'm glad I finally got to face some of 
that stuff. It's starting to feel more like football than it was 
before, when I wasn't getting any pressure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNown has always been one of those overachievers who throws 15  
passes if he's asked to throw five, and his competitiveness is 
showing already. On Tuesday, coach Dick Jauron said he doubted if 
McNown would play in Saturday's exhibition opener against the 
Indianapolis Colts. 
</P>
<P>
	A few hours later, Jauron had changed his mind.  
</P>
<P>
	He wasn't making any promises Wednesday, but if McNown shows in  
the next couple of days that he can pick up blitzes better and 
handle defenses, he'll be on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he doesn't handle the blitz and he doesn't have it down, he  
could just get a clean shot on him and get hurt,'' Crowton said. 
``At the same token, we're discussing that we don't want him to get 
further behind by not playing. We want to make sure we give him 
every opportunity to get reps. This is an opportunity, but we've 
got to be smart about it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 19:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sandeno Only U.S. Swim Winner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Freestyler Kaitlin Sandeno broke  
Canada's stranglehold on women's swimming at the Pan American Games 
Wednesday night, while the U.S. team set two ignominious records. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandeno, 16, from Lake Forest, Calif., one of the promising  
young members of the American team, won the women's 400-meter 
freestyle in a career-best 4 minutes, 10.74 seconds. Her time was 
just off the Pan Am record of 4:10.56 by Cynthia Woodhead in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first U.S. women's victory after five consecutive  
losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandeno, nicknamed ``Energizer,'' showed her energy and strength  
in beating Janelle Atkinson of Jamaica, the runner-up at 4:10.83, 
and 400 individual medley champion Joanne Malar of Canada, third at 
4:12.64. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the last 25 meters, I was thinking about our team the whole 	
time,'' Sandeno said. ``Everyone was saying we had to get the first 
</P>
<P>
                         girls' gold medal. 	
</P>
<P>
	``And I was thinking, `C'mon guys, I am going to do it for you.'  
</P>
<P>
	``It was awesome.''  
</P>
<P>
	Sandeno had displayed her ability, durability and versatility at  
this year's spring nationals, winning the 400 individual medley, 
finishing second in the 800 and 1,500 freestyles and placing third 
in the 400 freestyle. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandeno's victory was the only one for the Americans in five  
events -- the third consecutive night they had that result. 
</P>
<P>
	The total of only three gold medals in 15 events so far marks a  
low point for the U.S. team and seven losses for the women also 
constitutes a record. 
</P>
<P>
	Never in Pan Am history had U.S. swimmers lost more than 10  
events at one games. Now, they have lost 12 with 17 events 
remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Never in Pan Am history had the women lost more than six events.  
Now, they have lost seven with eight left. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada added to its domination in the women's competition,  
winning two more golds, and Brazil took over the gold medal lead 
among the men with two victories for a total of three. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly Stefanyshyn shattered her Canadian record in the women's  
100-meter backstroke, winning at 1:02.14, beating 1996 Olympic 
champion Beth Botsford. 
</P>
<P>
	Denali Knapp of Davis, Calif., finished second at 1:02.45, with  
Botsford, of Timonium, Md., third at 1:02.48. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada also won the 400 freestyle relay at 3:45.07, with 200  
freestyle champion Jessica Deglau swimming the leadoff leg. The 
U.S. finished second at 3:45.72. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's victories came in the men's 100 freestyle and 200  
backstroke, both in Pan Am record time. 
</P>
<P>
	Fernando Scherer broke teammate Gustavo Borges' record in the  
freestyle, clocking 49.19, with Borges, the two-time defending 
champion, taking third at 50.10. Splitting the two Brazilians was 
Argentina's Jose Meolans (49.94) as Americans failed to get a 
medal. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second event in which the Americans were blanked. In  
all the previous Pan Am Games, U.S. swimmers had failed to medal in 
individual events only twice -- once each in 1951 and 1955. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Tucker of Auburn, Ala., was fourth in the freestyle at  
50.15 and Dan Phillips of Colorado Spmrings, Colo., seventh at 
50.71. 
</P>
<P>
	Leonardo Costa won the backstroke at 1:59.33, .01 second under  
the previous record set by Rick Carey in 1983. Americans went 2-3, 
with Aaron Peirsol of Irvine, Calif., the runner-up at 1:59.77, 
followed by Dan Shevcik of Wilton, Conn., at 2:00.27. Both were 
personal bests. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, the U.S. leads the medals table with 17, but only three  
golds. Canada has 14 medals, but eight golds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 15:04:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Chile Seeks Pinochet Clemency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Having failed to convince British judges  
that Gen. Augusto Pinochet must be freed under international law, 
Chile is now mounting an effort to have him sent home because of 
failing health. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinochet, who is being held in London on a Spanish warrant for  
alleged human rights abuses, is said to dislike the idea of seeking 
clemency. ``He entered Britain through the front door, and he wants 
to leave the same way,'' said his oldest son, also named Augusto. 
</P>
<P>
	After a recent meeting, Pinochet's former press secretary,  
Alejandro de la Carrera, quoted the former dictator as saying he 
wants ``to fight until the end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, de la Carrera added, Pinochet also wants ``to return to  
Chile more than anything else'' and might accept an act of clemency 
in the end. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chilean government says it will attempt to win Pinochet's  
release for health reasons whether the 83-year-old general likes it 
or not. 
</P>
<P>
	``His opinion in this regard is irrelevant,'' said Defense  
Minister Edmundo Perez. ``It is not for the patient to write the 
prescription.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference last month in Rio de Janeiro, British  
Foreign Minister Robin Cook called on Chilean authorities to relay 
any evidence of Pinochet's health problems to Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	Late last week, Chile's Foreign Ministry received a report from  
a British and a Chilean doctor who had examined Pinochet and 
concluded he had ``serious medical problems that could be 
life-threatening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pinochet was arrested on Oct. 16 while in London for back  
surgery. A Spanish warrant charges him with human rights abuses 
allegedly committed by his security forces during his 17-year rule. 
An official Chilean report says 3,197 people disappeared or were 
killed after the coup he led in 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	A hearing on Spain's extradition request is set for Sept. 27.  
Britain and Spain have said that any decision on clemency would be 
made only after a ruling on extradition. 
</P>
<P>
	Chile's current government has little sympathy for Pinochet, but  
has argued that his arrest is a violation of sovereignty and that 
any trial for offenses that occurred in Chile should be carried out 
in Chile. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue of his arrest has threatened to polarize Chile. A  
center-left coalition has led the government since Pinochet gave up 
power in 1990. Chilean conservatives, who represent about a third 
of the population, credit Pinochet with saving the country from 
communism when he toppled an elected Marxist president. 
</P>
<P>
	In their medical report, the Chilean and British doctors who  
examined Pinochet said the stress of prolonged detention was 
hampering the former dictator's recovery from back surgery and 
worsening his existing diabetes. It noted that Pinochet also 
suffers from arthritis in his left knee and uses a pacemaker. 
</P>
<P>
	The report concluded that Pinochet isn't ``capable of enduring  
the stress that his prolonged captivity or a long trial'' could 
pose. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 15:04:25 </DATE_TIME>
