<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 15:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Injured Steelers' Dawson Practices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LATROBE, Pa. (AP) -- Dermontti Dawson obviously felt three to  
four weeks was much too long for an All-Pro center to rest his 
injured knee, even when games aren't being played. 
</P>
<P>
	Three to four days was more like it.  
</P>
<P>
	Only a day after the Pittsburgh Steelers' top offensive lineman  
was hampered by a bulky cast and predictions that he wouldn't 
practice for weeks, he strapped on a knee brace and snapped during 
blocking drills Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The consensus among his teammates: Dawson is remarkably brave or  
incredibly bored. 
</P>
<P>
	``From everything I've heard and everything I've witnessed since  
I've been here, he is the essence of what a football player should 
be,'' offensive coordinator Kevin Gilbride said. ``He loves the 
game and he loves to play. Am I shocked? No, I'm not shocked by 
anything. He's physically tough and courageous and I know he wants 
to be out here. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope he's not doing anything foolish by being out here, but  
it's good to see him back. I'm not going to do anything to 
discourage him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Dawson cautiously lifted his injured knee onto a bus  
seat and rode 170 miles round trip just to watch the Steelers 
scrimmage the Washington Redskins, even though he couldn't play. 
</P>
<P>
	Usually, a star player such as Dawson would gladly welcome the  
opportunity to skip such a workout. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to be smart about it,'' said Dawson, who has never  
missed a game during an 11-year NFL career. ``I know it's only 
training camp, but my knee is important as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That made Dawson's decision to practice all the more surprising,  
if only because the Steelers still are a week away from their first 
exhibition game and five weeks away from their first regular season 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	But several days of inactivity clearly knocked Dawson off his  
routine, perhaps because he could never remember missing any 
significant practice time before. 
</P>
<P>
	Dawson sprained his left knee Saturday when a teammate rolled  
across it during a 9-on-7 blocking drill. Four days later, he was 
back on the practice field. 
</P>
<P>
	``Understand we're talking about Dermontti Dawson now,''  
quarterback Kordell Stewart said. ``He's pretty much a world class 
athlete, not just an All-Pro center. You can't find too many 
centers who can pull and do all those great things he does. For him 
to be giving me snaps, that feels pretty good.'' 
  	   	
</P>
