<HEADLINE> Flight Delayed Over Security Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The FBI, tipped to a ``potential threat to  
national security,'' has detained a man who paid cash for a one-way 
ticket to Turkey on a Delta Air Lines flight. 
</P>
<P>
	All 217 passengers on Flight 40 to Istanbul, Turkey, were asked  
to get off the plane Tuesday night for a security sweep that 
included luggage. Six passengers were questioned and the man was 
detained. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as the terrorism concern, all of that has been  
resolved,'' FBI agent Tom Bush said. ``We have not been able to 
connect him to any terroristic group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said the agency had received information about the man as  
``a potential threat to national security.'' He said the man was 
not under arrest, but not free to go until authorities addressed 
``other law enforcement issues that still need to be resolved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush would not elaborate on what caused authorities to consider  
the man a threat. The flight left Hartsfield Atlanta International 
Airport about four hours late. 
</P>
<P>
	The Valdosta Daily Times reported today that airport officials  
became suspicious when the man paid cash for his one-way ticket and 
then retrieved his luggage from a large U-Haul truck parked outside 
the terminal. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
