<HEADLINE> Drug Dealer's Car Linked to Martin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- An expensive luxury car sought in connection with a  
convicted drug dealer was located after Miami Dolphins wide 
receiver Tony Martin turned it back to the dealership, a federal 
agent testified Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency agent Daryn Johnson told jurors  
that authorities were seeking a black 1996 Mercedes 500 SL 
convertible they believed was in Rickey Brownlee's possession. The 
car surfaced when Martin returned it to a dealer, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents seized four other cars as part of Brownlee's January 1998  
arrest. A sixth vehicle, a pickup truck, hasn't been found. Also 
seized were 14 homes that DEA officials said were bought by 
Brownlee's drug ring. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson's testimony and cross-examination took all day to  
complete, and Martin's link to the Mercedes was the only time the 
player's name was mentioned. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin is being tried along with Brownlee in a case largely  
focusing on Brownlee's alleged drug activities from 1995-97. 
Brownlee, known on the streets as the ``Mayor of Opa-locka,'' spent 
seven years in prison for 1980s drug convictions. 
</P>
<P>
	The receiver sat silently through most of the day, although he  
and Brownlee did exchange conversation across the defense table 
during breaks. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin, 33, is charged with five counts of money laundering. The  
receiver allegedly leased three cars in his name on behalf of 
Brownlee, who paid him back with cash. The receiver also is accused 
of writing a check to Brownlee's lawyer in exchange for a cash 
reimbursement. 
</P>
<P>
	Brownlee, 42, faces five counts of possessing heroin or cocaine  
with the intent to distribute and one count of conspiracy to 
possess and distribute. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial, before U.S. District Judge K. Michael Moore, is  
expected to last four weeks. That could keep Martin in court until 
about two weeks before the NFL season opens. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin returned to court Wednesday after missing Tuesday's  
session to practice with the Dolphins. The wideout only has to be 
present on days in which testimony is connected to his case. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, though, Martin's link to testimony lasted all of  
10 seconds. Assistant U.S. attorney Ron DeWaard spent the day 
building the prosecution's case against Brownlee, as Johnson 
chronicled several drug transactions with Brownlee or his 
associates. 
</P>
<P>
	Mel Black, Brownlee's lawyer, poked a couple holes in Johnson's  
testimony. He noted the sequence of events Johnson related in one 
transaction did not match those in the agent's report. He also 
pointed out that Johnson misidentified a man on a surveillance 
videotape as Brownlee. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
