<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Workplace Deaths Decline in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans who died from injuries  
at work last year was the lowest since the Labor Department started 
keeping track in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Job-related deaths fell to 6,026 in 1998 -- about 17 fatal  
injuries each day -- down from 6,238 in 1997, according to the 
agency's Bureau of Labor Statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	``With employment at an all-time high, it is especially  
heartening to see a 3 percent drop in job-related fatalities,'' 
Labor Secretary Alexis Herman said Wednesday. ``It's good news for 
every family that sends a breadwinner into the workplace and waits 
for him or her to come home safe and whole at the end of the day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fewer workplace homicides -- the second leading cause of  
on-the-job deaths -- accounted for much of the overall decline. In 
1998, 709 people were murdered at work, compared with 860 in 1997. 
Overall homicide rates also declined nationally last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Most workplace homicides were related to robberies and occurred  
at grocery stores, bars and restaurants and gas stations. 
</P>
<P>
	Highway crashes continued to be the leading cause of on-the-job  
deaths and the number of those fatalities rose slightly in 1998, to 
1,431. About two-fifths of the victims were truck drivers. An 
additional 413 workers were fatally struck by vehicles last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Deaths from falls and electrocutions also increased in 1998,  
with the booming construction industry accounting for much of the 
rise in those categories. Meanwhile, the number of deaths from 
workers being struck by falling objects or getting caught in 
running machinery declined. 
</P>
<P>
	Among men, highway incidents were the leading cause of workplace  
deaths in 1998. Homicide topped the list for women. Workers under 
age 17 were most often killed while doing farm or construction 
work. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 20:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs Steel, Oil Loan Guarantee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House gave final congressional approval  
Wednesday to federal guarantees for $1.5 billion in loans for 
steel, oil and natural gas companies, aiming to help industries 
that have been rocked by low prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The 246-176 vote came seven weeks after the Senate passed the  
bill by 63-34. Supporters said they expect President Clinton to 
sign the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Sponsors of the leglislation said the three industries have  
suffered thousands of job losses as prices have dipped. Steel 
companies have also been battered by low-cost imports. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot allow foreign nations to export their unemployment  
to the United States,'' said Rep. Ralph Regula, R-Ohio, one of the 
sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents said the measure was little better than the  
protectionism the U.S. government criticizes other countries for. 
And they said it would force U.S. taxpayers to back some companies 
and banks that have simply made bad business decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sure there are a lot of people who lost their jobs,'' said  
House Minority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, speaking of a recession 
that hit the oil industry in the early 1980s. ``But the oil 
industry got through that deep depression and they're stronger for 
that today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., pushed the steel aid through the  
Senate earlier this year in legislation paying for the war with 
Yugoslavia. It was designed to help only some small steel 
companies, including Weirton Steel Corp. in West Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	He took it off that bill in exchange for promises that Congress  
would consider it separately. Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., won a 
similar pledge for assistance for oil and gas companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would provide steel companies federal guarantees for $1  
billion in loans. Steel companies would be eligible to borrow up to 
$250 million each at market interest rates. U.S. oil and gas 
producers and service companies could borrow up to $10 million each 
from a fund guaranteeing $500 million in loans. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would cost taxpayers an estimated $270 million to  
back the loans. That would come from trimming federal 
administrative costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a $187 million break for the struggling U.S. steel  
industry fell by the wayside as Congress rushed to assemble its 
tax-cut bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The House-approved tax break -- not a high priority for all  
manufacturers -- was dropped during House-Senate negotiations late 
Tuesday as lawmakers sought to complete work on the tax package 
before their August vacation at week's end. 
</P>
<P>
	The tax break for the steel industry would have allowed  
manufacturers to reduce their alternative minimum tax by using 
credits sooner than otherwise possible. Accelerating the schedule 
for those tax credits would have cost the government an estimated 
$187 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Phil English, a member of the tax-writing House Ways and  
Means Committee, said the provision did not survive because not 
enough steel manufacturers wanted it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The steel industry was unable to offer a united front,''  
English, R-Pa., said. ``In lieu of a consensus, there was 
inadequate support in conference to keep a provision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He would not name the companies that did not back the provision.  
</P>
<P>
	Despite losing a chance at special tax treatment, he said, the  
steel industry would benefit through a general reduction in the 
burden of the Alternative Minimum Tax, which many steel producers 
have had to pay because of low profit margins. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Clinton administration officials were to meet  
Thursday at the White House with steel manufacturers and union 
leaders and offer new proposals to help the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals include a pledge to oppose any new World Bank and  
International Monetary Fund loans that would further subsidize 
foreign steel industries and a Commerce Department review of 
foreign steel subsidies.	   But with the surge in steel imorts beginning to decline, the 
administration believes continuing to enforce existing laws is the 
right course, one administration official said, speaking on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry has filed trade complaints against a variety of  
countries, and won several cases, but those take a long time and 
have to be handled one kind of steel at a time. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturers have complained that as soon as one country  
reduces exports of a certain type of steel, another steps up its 
exports, leaving American docks just as loaded with inexpensive, 
hard-to-compete-against steel. 
</P>
<P>
	At least three publicly traded steel companies have declared  
bankruptcy since the import surge began, and many companies have 
reported operating losses. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
