<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 15:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban High Jumper Had High Profile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Of Cuba's high-profile athletes, one  
stood above them all: Javier Sotomayor. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Sotomayor went from a national hero to one of the  
most disgraced athletes in sports when Pan American Games officials 
said he had tested positive for cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	Sotomayor, the world indoor and outdoor record-holder in the  
high jump, is the only person to clear 8 feet. After winning four 
Pan Am Games titles, an Olympic gold medal in 1992, two world 
outdoor championships and four world indoor titles, Sotomayor now 
perhaps will be best remembered for the shame he brought upon his 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	Just like Ben Johnson.  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was hero-worshipped by Canadians after sprinting to a  
world record in the 100 meters at the 1988 Olympic Games. A couple 
of days later, he was stripped of his gold medal when Olympic 
officials found high levels of anabolic steroids in his urine 
sample. Johnson left Seoul in disgrace. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the International Amateur Athletic Federation, the world  
governing body for the sport, receives documentation on the drug 
test, it will order the Cuban federation to suspend Sotomayor for 
two years. Cuba can appeal, but Sotomayor must be suspended first. 
</P>
<P>
	With his familiar wraparound glasses, the long-legged, 6-foot-4  
Sotomayor is a presence wherever he goes in Cuba, and he thrives on 
the attention. 
</P>
<P>
	He is a wealthy man, with a home provided by the government, a  
red Mercedes Benz and a huge watch collection. 
</P>
<P>
	He is very influential in Cuba sports circles and has a close  
relationship with deputy sports minister Alberto Juantorena, the 
1976 Olympic 400- and 800-meter gold medalist. 
</P>
<P>
	Sotomayor is considered the best high jumper ever -- better than  
Dick Fosbury, better than Valery Brumel, better than John Thomas. 
No one has accomplished more than the 31-year-old Cuban. 
</P>
<P>
	Probably no one had more strength and speed than Sotomayor.  
Probably no one was a better technician. Probably no one was more 
of a perfectionist. 
</P>
<P>
	On the day of a meet, immediately before each jump, Sotomayor  
took several minutes to visualize a flawless performance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I try to imagine the perfect movements that I would make for a  
perfect jump and then I repeat that image in my mind,'' he has 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He then would sprint toward the bar for his backward, headfirst  
``Fosbury Flop.''. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel comfortable without a good rhythm,'' said  
Sotomayor, who started 15 to 20 feet farther back than most 
jumpers. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Sotomayor's biggest admirers was Dwight Stones, the  
former world record-holder. Stones was impressed with Sotomayor's 
powerful, aggressive, straight-ahead approach to the bar. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first time I saw it, I didn't believe it,'' Stones said.  
``I thought his knee was going to be left on the ground somewhere. 
I said this guy is doing exactly what you have to do to jump 
high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sotomayor is from Limonar, Cuba, a small town in the central  
part of the island, about 60 miles from Havana. Like most Cuban 
youngsters, he grew up playing baseball and loved playing center 
field. 
</P>
<P>
	He started in track at age 9, and by 13 he was exclusively a  
high jumper, clearing 5-5. Six years later, he had won junior 
titles at the Pan Am Games and the World Junior Championships, and 
raised his career best to 7-8 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Sotomayor won the first of his record four Pan Am titles in 1987  
at Indianapolis. Five days after missing the 1988 Olympics because 
of Cuba's absence, Sotomayor cleared a world record 7-11 1/2, nearly 
two inches higher than the winning jump at the Seoul Games. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1989, he broke world records twice, soaring 7-11 1/2 indoors,  
then making his historic 8-foot leap at San Juan. Sotomayor had one 
more world record in him, jumping 8-0 1/2 in 1993, one year after 
winning the Olympic gold. 
</P>
<P>
	All that great jumping, all those wonderful accomplishments, all  
that pride that made Sotomayor one of the world's great athletes 
was washed away Wednesday with one positive drug test. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
