<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Elway Plans Health, Money Web Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Retired Denver Broncos quarterback John Elway will  
team up with a Florida firm in a venture to create an Internet site 
focused on health, fitness and financial planning, his business 
manager said. 
</P>
<P>
	Elway and Boca Raton, Fla.-based JWGenesis Financial Corp. will  
be partners in MVP.com, a company to be launched at the Super Bowl 
in January in Atlanta. Elway and JWGenesis executives were to make 
a formal announcement about the venture in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Sperbeck, Elway's business manager, did not release details  
of the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	He described the planned company as ``not specifically sports  
related. It's more of a business venture than a sports venture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Wednesday's editions, the Denver Rocky Mountain News and The  
Denver Post cited unidentified sources as saying the company and 
Web site would feature products and services in fitness, health and 
financial planning as part of the concept of personal goal-setting. 
</P>
<P>
	Elway, who retired after leading the Broncos to a second  
straight Super Bowl victory this year, has been involved in 
planning the new Web site for months, the News reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Elway and JWGenesis President Marshall T. Leeds will be  
co-chairmen of the privately held company, with JWGenesis chief 
operating officer Joel E. Marks serving as day-to-day manager at 
its Atlanta headquarters, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Elway's other business ventures have included a string of  
Denver-area car dealerships that he sold in 1997 to Wayne 
Huizenga's Republic Industries Inc., since renamed AutoNation Inc. 
He also invested in a Spanish-language Internet company, 
QuePasa!com Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	JWGenesis is a diversified financial-services holding company  
with securities brokerages, investment banking, institutional sales 
and asset management. It trades on the American Stock Exchange. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
