<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Permanent War Crimes Court Sought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United States has held talks with more  
than 40 nations in the past 10 days to find a way to enable 
Washington to sign a treaty that would create a permanent 
international war crimes tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	Ambassador David Scheffer said Wednesday that the United States  
has no intention of trying to weaken the proposed court, even 
though some critics have alleged that Washington wants changes that 
would undermine the tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States was one of seven countries voting ``no'' when  
120 countries approved the treaty to establish the International 
Criminal Court just over a year ago in Rome. 
</P>
<P>
	American officials felt the treaty yielded too much power to the  
new court, leaving U.S. troops and citizens vulnerable to 
politically motivated prosecutions. And Washington's opposition 
hasn't diminished. 
</P>
<P>
	The court will begin operating when the treaty is ratified by 60  
countries, which diplomats estimate will take 2 1/2 to five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Scheffer said the United States' main objective is to close a  
gap in the treaty that unduly constrains countries from using 
military force legitimately. 
</P>
<P>
	As a commission preparing for the court's operation holds its  
second round of meetings, Scheffer has been meeting privately with 
delegates from every continent to discuss the U.S. conditions for 
supporting the court. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials said they approached the talks with hope, and  
believe that if American concerns can be accommodated the court can 
be strengthened. 
</P>
<P>
	But they don't expect to decide on a final proposal to present  
to delegates during the three-week meeting, which ends Aug. 13. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no intention of proposing anything that has the end  
result of weakening the treaty or the operation of the court,'' 
Scheffer said. 
</P>
<P>
	While he refused to discuss exactly what the U.S. is seeking,  
delegates said Washington is looking for an exception from 
investigation or prosecution by the court for personnel involved in 
official international military actions. 
</P>
<P>
	Delegates said the United States also wants to diminish the  
court's authority to determine when governments have failed to 
prosecute -- and to give ultimate decision-making authority to a 
body other than the court. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jelena Pejic of the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights said  
any attempt to bar prosecution for official acts ``is blatantly 
contrary to international law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The very purpose of this court is to prosecute and investigate  
the most serious crimes of international concern,'' she said. ``If 
any state can then come up and say, 'well the genocide we committed 
was in an official capacity,' what are we doing here?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
