<DOCNO> APW19990804.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 13:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HUD Won't Sue Gun Manufacturers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal housing officials have no plans to  
file their own lawsuit against gun manufacturers over the damage 
firearms cause, an official said today at a congressional meeting 
called after a report that such a suit was being considered. 
</P>
<P>
	Gail W. Laster, general counsel for the Department of Housing  
and Urban Development, didn't rule out the possibility that the 
agency would file a friend-of-the-court brief or join one of a 
string of lawsuits being filed by local governments trying to 
recoup taxpayer money spent dealing with gun violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Laster's remarks before the House Government Reform Committee's  
panel on criminal justice drew angry responses from House 
Republicans who said it was preposterous to blame the gun industry 
for the acts of criminals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quite frankly, I am baffled by the idea that the makers of  
guns are seen by anyone as being somehow legally responsible for 
those who acquire the weapons and misuse them,'' said Rep. John 
Mica, R-Fla., subcommittee chairman, who called the subcommittee 
meeting shortly after a Wall Street Journal article last week 
reported on HUD's exploration of the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said they didn't understand what all the fuss was  
about. It's perfectly appropriate for HUD to explore any idea that 
improves the safety of public housing residents and reduces the 
money the federal government must spent on security, said Rep. 
Henry Waxman, D-Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``To be in a fury over the fact that HUD may be thinking of  
something some of them don't like is certainly a strange notion,'' 
Waxman said. ``The Republican leadership is willing to jump to 
defend their friends ... even though some of their friends make 
products that kill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I see no justification for calling a hearing based upon a  
newspaper article,'' Rep. Patsy Mink, D-Hawaii, said. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-three cities and counties, including Los Angeles, Chicago  
and New Orleans, have filed suits accusing gunmakers of failing to 
equip weapons with adequate safety devices and marketing them in 
ways that allow handguns to fall into the hands of criminals. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, the NAACP filed suit against nearly 100 handgun makers  
in federal court, seeking injunctions that would place sweeping 
restrictions on handgun sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Laster said department officials have responded to questions  
from public housing authorities contemplating or involved in the 
suits. 
</P>
<P>
	And the department has conferred with private attorneys to  
increase its understanding of the issue, Laster said. A HUD lawyer 
traveled to a New York law firm last week for discussions, she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun manufactures testifying called the suits fundamentally  
unfair. 
</P>
<P>
	``We make a lawful product,'' said Jeff Reh, general counsel for  
Beretta USA Corp. ``We sell that product as requested by the 
public, in accordance with procedures set by the same federal 
government that is now talking about suing us for relying upon the 
very distribution system that the federal government established.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 08:07:40 </DATE_TIME>
