<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pats Owner Sponsors Israeli Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- They live in Israel, they work in Israel, they  
speak Hebrew and they serve in the Israeli army -- but they crave 
American football. 
</P>
<P>
	About 200 American expatriates turned out Wednesday to cheer  
Robert Kraft, owner of the New England Patriots, at the 
groundbreaking for Israel's first touch football field. Kraft is 
donating money to build the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Touch football is a taste of the old country for homesick  
Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	When Yonah Mishan, 27, a plumber, immigrated from Los Angeles in  
1984, no one played the game here. ``I really missed it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Arieh (``The Animal'') Bauman. who runs a steakhouse, said he  
once won a football scholarship to Penn State. Instead, he 
immigrated to Israel and joined the paratroops, intending to go 
back to Penn State later. But he was wounded in the knee while 
fighting in south Lebanon and had to give up his college football 
dream. 
</P>
<P>
	His old fire for the game is reflected in his nickname. He's  
known for going after opposing quarterbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Up to now, touch football has been played on underdeveloped  
soccer fields here. ``This has caused unnecessary injuries, made it 
very difficult to train youth and stunted the development of the 
sport,'' said Steve Leibowitz, chairman of ATFI, the American Touch 
Football Association. 
</P>
<P>
	At Wednesday's ceremony, Kraft donated $120,000 to transform one  
of those soccer pitches into a real touch football field. The Kraft 
Stadium will have new turf, new fences, plastic seats in the 
bleachers and lights for weeknight games. 
</P>
<P>
	When Leibowitz founded ATFI ten years ago, it had eight teams  
and 120 players. Now it has 33 teams and 500 players. Almost all 
are American immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
	That might change. A growing number of Israelis watch American  
football on television. All the Patriots games are screened on a 
local channel. 
</P>
<P>
	Kraft believes that when the new stadium is built, young  
Israelis will be attracted to the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Israelis have never had an opportunity to see football under  
the right conditions, but when they get exposed to it and get a 
feel for it, I'm sure they will want to play,'' he told The 
Associated Press. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
