<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft To Help Navajo Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft is giving a $1.2 million grant to fund  
technology training for teachers in 12 Navajo school districts in 
Arizona, New Mexico and Utah, the company announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	The grant to the Navajo Education Technology Consortium will  
help match a five-year, $7.6 million national Technology Innovation 
Challenge Grant awarded earlier this year to the consortium by the 
U.S Department of Education. 
</P>
<P>
	It aims to provide training for teachers in the use of  
technology in the classroom, Microsoft said in a statement today. 
</P>
<P>
	The consortium currently serves 2,750 teachers and 45,000  
students on Navajo reservations in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	``Technology infrastructure at the nation's Indian reservations  
has long been neglected,'' said Larry Shaw, project director of the 
Education Technology Improvement Plan, as the grant plan is 
formally named. 
</P>
<P>
	``These grants will go a long way to ensure that our students  
and teachers are on an equal playing field in terms of access to 
technology and the training necessary to advance themselves 
academically and professionally,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The software giant also will provide software to four training  
centers to support the initiative. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
