<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rock Beat: Johnnie Johnson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Johnnie B. Goode is back, and he's bad.  
</P>
<P>
	While most rock stars' heyday is in their youth, blues and  
boogie pianist Johnnie Johnson is approaching his 75th birthday and 
his popularity is on the rise. 
</P>
<P>
	He's no longer just known as the Chuck Berry sideman who  
inspired Berry's famous ``Johnny B. Goode.'' Nearly half a century 
after he first took the stage, Johnson's stepping out from Berry's 
shadow and gaining acclaim as a solo blues star. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson's adopted hometown of St. Louis recently honored him  
with a weeklong celebration, including a jazz festival and birthday 
party. And his ``Father of Rock 'n' Roll: The Johnnie 'B. Goode' 
Johnson Story,'' was recently published. 
</P>
<P>
	It took years and some crusading by modern rock musicians to  
push Johnson into the spotlight. 
</P>
<P>
	His biggest break came in 1987 during the compilation of a Chuck  
Berry documentary called ``Hail, Hail Rock 'n' Roll.'' During the 
filming, Johnson met Keith Richards of the Rolling Stones who urged 
Johnson to pursue his solo career. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years later, Johnson released his first solo album,  
``Bluehand Johnnie.'' The albums ``Johnnie B. Bad'' and ``Johnnie 
Be Back'' followed. 
</P>
<P>
	Then came a push from Houston businessman George Turek to get  
Johnson into Cleveland's Rock and Roll Hall of Fame. Turek, CEO of 
the physicians management service company MES Group, had hired 
Johnson to play at his wedding and quickly became a fan. 
</P>
<P>
	Turek even ran an advertisement in Billboard magazine featuring  
a letter to the hall-of-fame nominating committee to persuade them 
of Johnson's talent and influence. It was signed by other 
inductees, including Bo Diddley, John Lee Hooker, Little Richard 
and Etta James. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Hall of Fame said it didn't have a category in which to  
fit Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Inductees are nominated for work done in their own name or with  
a group. Even though Johnson collaborated with Berry on songs, the 
credit is given to Berry. Johnson's solo albums have only been 
released in the last decade, so it's too early for him to be 
nominated individually. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson isn't discouraged.  
</P>
<P>
	With Turek's help, ``the wheels have been going forward. I'm  
getting more exposure,'' Johnson said in a recent interview. ``Now, 
with the book, that'll be icing on the cake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was born in West Virginia and began playing the piano  
when he was 5 years old. He joined his first band, Blue Rhythm 
Swingsters, when he was 13. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson served in World War II and came to the St. Louis area  
after playing for three years in Chicago with top blues players. In 
1952, the young musician was in East St. Louis when a member of his 
band fell ill before a New Year's Eve gig. The replacement he hired 
was guitarist Chuck Berry. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest is musical history.  
</P>
<P>
	The duo wrote rock 'n' roll classics like ``Mabelline'' and  
``Roll Over, Beethoven.'' Johnson composed the music on piano, 
Berry converted it to guitar and wrote the lyrics. They blended 
blues, boogie and country to form the genre that helped shape rock 
music in the early 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	``When rock 'n' roll came in strong, it was really the guitar  
players that brought it in -- Chuck and Elvis Presley,'' Johnson 
said. Being the sideman to Berry never bothered him, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Today Johnson has tapped into a surge in the popularity of the  
blues. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, it seems like blues and jazz are the outstanding  
types of music,'' Johnson said. ``I've met quite a few young 
musicians. All these kids who are starting to play now are focusing 
on learning the blues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson's latest CD, due out in a couple of months, will be his  
seventh. Atlantic Records also is lining up artists for a special 
tribute album in Johnson's honor. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as I can lift a hand to play, I'll be playing,'' he  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 16:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Sues Texas Investment Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Federal regulators sued a Texas investment firm  
Wednesday charging it with fraud that may have cost investors up to 
$475 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit was filed by the Securities and Exchange Commission in  
federal court in San Antonio against InverWorld Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents from the FBI, the SEC and the IRS executed search  
warrants at the business offices of InverWorld and its chairman, 
Jose P. Zollino, in connection with a criminal investigation, an 
FBI spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC lawsuit and the search warrants are the latest  
developments in an emerging scandal surrounding InverWorld, which 
catered mostly to wealthy investors in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	In late June, InverWorld affiliates in Great Britain and the  
Cayman Islands told investors they were closing and freezing all 
accounts. Those affiliates are now in liquidation proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC said InverWorld, Zollino, 51, company President George  
F. Fahey, 62, and three affiliated companies may have lost 
investors' money through risky, unauthorized investments. The 
lawsuit also charged that an affiliate company issued practically 
worthless securities to investors. 
</P>
<P>
	According to related court filings by InverWorld affiliates, the  
company had as many as 1,000 investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC said InverWorld's clients were interested in low-risk  
investments outside Latin America, including money-market accounts 
and U.S. Treasuries, but that InverWorld put their money in risky 
investments in ``volatile emerging markets'' and with entities 
closely related to InverWorld. It said fraudulent statements 
concealed the nature of the investments from clients. 
</P>
<P>
	Allan Diamond, a Houston lawyer who said he is representing  
about 100 investors who put more than $100 million in InverWorld, 
said the SEC charges are similar to what clients have told him. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of questions of what else happened, given the  
size of the losses,'' Diamond said. ``Everyone believed they were 
investing money in safe investments that would have reasonable 
yields and they could rely on in their retirement. You had people 
putting their life savings in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lamont Jefferson, a Dallas lawyer for InverWorld's domestic  
companies, said the investments were all in accordance with 
contracts signed by the investors. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been bad investments in global markets. It's a  
risky business, and you can lose money in those markets,'' 
Jefferson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jefferson said he didn't know how the money was lost, whether it  
was one bad investment or a series of smaller ones. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC is seeking a freeze of assets at the companies, civil  
penalties and a repayment of funds. It asked that a temporary 
receiver be appointed to oversee InverWorld. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal officials said some of the securities sold to investors  
were issued by IWG Services Ltd., an InverWorld affiliate in London 
that was essentially a mail drop -- it had no offices or employees. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the SEC, InverWorld, Zollino and Fahey used IWG and  
Cayman Islands-based IG Services Ltd. as ``shells'' to move money 
beyond the reach of investors and regulators. The SEC said $210 
million was transferred to Swiss and Bahamian bank accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the SEC, only $90 million in securities may remain.  
</P>
<P>
	Zollino was unavailable for comment. The phone went unanswered  
at InverWorld's headquarters Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	InverWorld has had previous problems with the Internal Revenue  
Service, which is trying to collect $380 million it says InverWorld 
owes in back taxes and penalties for allegedly shifting income 
earned in the United States to foreign subsidiaries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
