<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 17:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Early Start Slows U.S. Basketball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Starting a basketball game at 10 a.m.  
was a little too early for the U.S. men. Around 10:30 would have 
been just right. 
</P>
<P>
	That extra 30 minutes was how long it took them to wake up  
Wednesday as the United States beat the Dominican Republic 95-83 to 
finish unbeaten in the preliminary rounds of the Pan American 
Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Travis Williams scored 24 points to lead the Americans (3-0),  
who trailed by 20 with seven minutes left in the first half before 
rallying with the help of a full-court press. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was our first early game and we just had to wake up,''  
Williams said. ``I think what woke us up is when we looked up and 
were down by 20. I was thinking, help me get this thing over 
with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States will play in the semifinals Friday night for  
the right to advance to Sunday's gold medal game. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. women, who already had qualified for the medal round,  
used solid defense to beat Canada 62-46 and finish 3-2 in 
preliminary play. Their semifinal opponent Thursday night is Cuba, 
which beat the Americans 95-64 Saturday, the worst loss ever for a 
U.S. women's team in Pan Ams play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being as we lost the way we did against Cuba, none of us liked  
it too well,'' U.S. forward Dana Wynne said. ``We were all looking 
forward to playing Cuba again and having the opportunity to show 
they're not 30 points better than we are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For quite some time, the American men weren't better than the  
Dominican Republic, which hit three 3-pointers, converted a 
three-point play and had a four-point possession during a 20-4 run 
that produced a 45-25 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those guys had played three morning games, so I think they  
were a little more adjusted to it,'' U.S. coach Mo McHone said. 
``They just came out shooting the ball. They made some tough shots 
early.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McHone then went to a smaller, faster lineup and it worked. The  
Americans forced seven turnovers while outscoring the Dominicans 
27-6 and trailed only 53-52 at halftime. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams scored nine points and had two steals during the run.  
Mikki Moore had three dunks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coach gave us the green light to press after every made basket  
and that's what we started doing,'' Williams said. ``The team 
picked up on that and we just took it from there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Hawkins' 3-pointer gave the United States the lead for  
good, 70-67, with 10:20 remaining, and the Americans pulled away at 
the end as the Dominican team wore down. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawkins and Doug Smith each scored 13 points, Moore had 12 and  
Carl Thomas 10. 
</P>
<P>
	The American women weren't sharp offensively but held Canada to  
18 points and 22.6 percent (7-for-31) shooting in the second half. 
Canada (2-3) trailed 37-33 early in the second half before the 
Americans went on a 21-4 run to break it open. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought our defensive effort was good,'' U.S. coach Nell  
Fortner said. ``We were there. I think we had a lot to do with why 
they missed shots. I thought our defense was just tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States played without two of its top interior  
players, 6-foot-5 Sylvia Crawley and 6-3 Danielle McCulley, both 
ill with the flu. That forced Wynne, Amy Herrig and Katryna Gaither 
to play extra minutes against Canada's physical front line. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was just trying to do everything I could do to help us come  
out with a victory, whether it was scoring, rebounding, setting 
good screens or defense,'' said Wynne, who had five points and 
three rebounds. ``We're a team. When one falls down, another steps 
in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michelle Marciniak led the Americans with 17 points and Edwina  
Brown scored 15. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
