<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bids May Hit $1M for Domain Name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- What's in a name? At least $260,000 so far,  
and maybe more than $1 million if the name is Drugs.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric MacIver, a 21-year-old Internet entrepreneur in Mesa,  
Ariz., stands to reap the windfall from drug companies' bidding for 
rights to the Internet domain name to which he owns the exclusive 
rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Intense bidding under way for the name highlights the  
competition among companies seeking the right name to lure 
customers in the increasingly crowded world of electronic commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	By Wednesday afternoon the highest confirmed bid was $260,000,  
but several large drug companies and well-heeled speculators have 
expressed an interest in bidding before the auction closes Friday 
evening, MacIver said in a telephone interview from his office. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very hard to spell Bausch &AMP; Lomb, but if they get  
Drugs.com, as I see it, it helps brand their name,'' he said, 
referring to the big health products company. 
</P>
<P>
	``These guys make hundreds of millions of dollars a year in this  
industry. There's one chance to get it. If I were in that industry 
I'd consider $1 million a bargain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at Greatdomains.com, one of two online brokers  
handling the auction, said confidentially agreements prevented them 
from releasing names of bidders, or saying whether Bausch &AMP; Lomb 
was among them. 
</P>
<P>
	Several major companies have verbally committed to bids well  
above $260,000, however. Greatdomains, based in Los Angeles, and 
Dotbroker.com, the other broker involved in the sale, were in the 
process of confirming the bids on Wednesday, said Jeff Tinsley, 
Greatdomains' chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies require bidders to back up verbal bids with a  
written contract. The agreement then must be reviewed by the 
seller's attorneys before the bid becomes official. 
</P>
<P>
	Other companies had inquired, but appeared to be waiting for the  
last day to better gauge the market, said Tinsley. 
</P>
<P>
	Bids were expected to exceed $1 million, he said. In May, the  
name Wallstreet.com was sold for $1 million to a Venezuelan 
company. And last year Compaq Computer Corp. paid $3.35 million for 
the name AltaVista.com for its AltaVista search engine. Since then, 
Compaq sold a controlling stake in the search engine to the 
Internet investment company CMGI Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are anticipating a big frenzy because we have been  
contacted by quite a few companies that are interested in making an 
offer: big drug companies, big venture capital companies,'' said 
Tinsley. 
</P>
<P>
	The activity is not surprising. Companies seeking an Internet  
presence are scrambling to find domain names that are easy to 
remember and likely to appeal to customers, said Preston Dodd, an 
analyst with Jupiter Communications in New York. But a successful 
site requires more than just a name. 
</P>
<P>
	``In terms of building the brand itself, there obviously could  
be a huge head start. It's even easier to remember than 
1-800-Flowers,'' said Dodd. ``It's not a silver bullet. They have 
to build a brand around it and they have to build awareness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In May, MacIver purchased on option to buy the name from Bonnie  
Neubeck, owner of a Minneapolis Internet marketing company. That 
deal means MacIver will get the lion's share of the auction price 
for Drugs.com. Mrs. Neubeck is entitled only to the option price. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, I'm not going to get all that money. I had the  
purchase price negotiated in May,'' said Mrs. Neubeck, who has sold 
other domain names for six-figure amounts. 
</P>
<P>
	She put the name up for sale several months ago, after watching  
the online pharmaceuticals market grow. At the time, MacIver's 
company, Sandline Productions, was planning to launch an online 
drug sales business. He later scrapped the plan and decided to put 
Drugs.com up for sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither she nor MacIver would say how much he paid to buy the  
name. 
</P>
<P>
	Profits from the sale will be plowed back into Sandline, a  
five-person Web site design and programming company MacIver founded 
18 months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to retire,'' he said. ``With the sale of this  
name, I'm just going to put it into Sandline and help it grow 
more.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
