<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Convicted of Burning Son </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- A woman was convicted of killing her  
15-year-old son by throwing a cup of kerosene on him and lighting 
because she was angry that other children in the apartment made 
noise while she tried to sleep. One of the boy's last acts was to 
drag his mother to safety. 
</P>
<P>
	Annie Pollard was found guilty of second-degree murder Tuesday  
by a Circuit Court judge, who said he will sentence her in a few 
weeks. She could be sentenced to up to life in prison with 
possibility of parole. 
</P>
<P>
	Her son Lamar was fatally burned on Dec. 16, 1997. Ms. Pollard  
had been drinking, police said. One of the children, now 11, 
testified that Lamar and his mother argued before Ms. Pollard 
tossed the kerosene on him and set it on fire. 
</P>
<P>
	In flames, Lamar ran around the second-floor flat, the child  
said. Then he and his mother tried to put out the flames with water 
from the bathtub. But by then, the fire had spread to one of the 
rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	The six children got out and Lamar dragged his mother to safety.  
Lamar died 35 days later of respiratory problems from burns that 
covered 60 percent of his body. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Pollard had said the death was accidental. She said kerosene  
had spilled on the boy during a quarrel. She didn't know how the 
fire started but testified that she had lighted a kerosene heater 
to warm the apartment. 
</P>
<P>
	She had been charged with first-degree murder, but the judge  
said he found no evidence that Ms. Pollard had deliberated before 
setting the fire. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
