<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush To Meet Hispanic Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Texas George W. Bush, who angered  
Hispanic-Americans by declining to address their convention in 
Houston, will meet this week with Hispanic leaders in Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides say Thursday's meeting had been on the schedule for weeks  
and was not designed to repair any damage that might have resulted 
from his decision not to attend the National Council of La Raza 
convention last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting originally was scheduled to be private and wasn't  
announced until Wednesday, after it was decided to open up the 
session to reporters, the aides said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The governor has been very diligent about bringing his  
campaign and his ideas to the Hispanic community in Iowa and he'll 
continue to do,'' spokesman Eric Woolson said. ``The campaign has 
been working very closely with members of the Hispanic community to 
bring them into the campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An Iowa State University study in 1997 said Hispanics made up  
1.9 percent of the state's population, with 53,092 Hispanic 
residents. They are the fastest growing of any minority population, 
increasing from 1.2 percent in 1990, the study said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has made a courtship of Hispanic voters an important part  
of his campaign for the GOP presidential nomination, routinely 
delivering part of his stump speech in Spanish. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush had told La Raza officials that he could not attend the  
convention because he was vacationing his family. However, his wife 
interrupted the family vacation the following day to campaign in 
Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas governor also declined to speak at a meeting of  
minority journalists in Seattle, though he was campaigning in that 
city at the time. He did make a brief appearance at that event. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore, who also routinely speaks Spanish on the  
stump, addressed both groups. Latinos are a growing and influential 
voting group that generally favors Democrats, but Bush has made 
some inroads in Texas. He carried nearly half the Hispanic vote in 
winning re-election last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush opened his latest campaign swing through Iowa in a carnival  
atmosphere, speaking Wednesday to about 500 supporters at a 
lakeside park in Clear Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	But he touched only briefly on the theme of Hispanic voters,  
noting that test scores have improved in Texas ``particularly among 
African-American and Latino children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before an almost entirely white audience, he decided against  
delivering a portion of his speech in Spanish. Hammering basic 
campaign themes, he said, ``We can give this great country a fresh 
start after a season of incredible cynicism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woolson said the meeting Thursday with leaders of the Hispanic  
community initially was a private session, but campaign aides 
decided to open it to reporters and it was added to the public 
schedule. He insisted there was no connection to earlier incidents. 
</P>
<P>
	Allowing reporters into the meeting clearly raises the profile  
of the encounter, however, and it likely will become central to 
news accounts of Bush's swing, which otherwise is filled with 
routine campaign events. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has met with Hispanic leaders in earlier campaign swings,  
but reporters have not been allowed in those sessions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
