<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mazda To Raise Pay of 500 Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Mazda Motor Corp. says it will award raises to  
about 500 women and promote two or three women to management in an 
effort to erase the sexual discrimination that is still common in 
Japanese offices. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is still a Japanese way of thinking in the company, and  
women weren't being utilized fully,'' Mazda spokeswoman Nobuko 
Watanabe said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda studied the performance and skills of 1,000 women  
employees and found that 500 deserved either promotions or a better 
job grade that determines their salaries, Watanabe said. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, two or three women will be promoted by this fall to  
the lowest managerial position, called assistant manager, a title 
now held by 2,300 men and only four women. Others will get raises. 
</P>
<P>
	The top managerial position held by women up to now has been  
section chief, but there are now only three women among 700 section 
chiefs. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda, a Hiroshima-based automaker that is 33.4 percent owned by  
Ford Motor Co., employs 1,400 women, mostly clerical workers, 
making up about 6 percent of the work force. It has about 90 women 
plant workers -- 60 of them hired this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Women in Japan still face major hurdles when trying to move up  
the corporate ladder. Many companies push women to quit when they 
marry or when they reach their mid-30s. 
</P>
<P>
	A majority of Japanese companies say they do not allow women in  
management positions because of ``lack of knowledge and judgment,'' 
according to a recent Labor Ministry survey. 
</P>
<P>
	Women headed 60,593 firms in June, just 5.3 percent of Japan's  
1.14 million companies, according to a survey by Teikoku Data Bank, 
a Tokyo research company. 
</P>
<P>
	Rewarding workers according to their productivity is still a  
relatively new concept in many Japanese companies. The traditional 
seniority system automatically gives workers pay raises as they get 
older. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Japan's top automaker, Toyota Motor Corp. said it  
will start a new pay system based on performance rather than 
seniority in October. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
