<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strawberry Reports to AAA Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Darryl Strawberry, set to join the New York  
Yankees' Triple-A Columbus team today, says his latest comeback 
will be his last. 
</P>
<P>
	``There won't be another,'' Strawberry told the New York Post as  
he prepared to begin his fifth comeback since being released by the 
Los Angeles Dodgers in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry's 120-day suspension for his arrest on solicitation  
and drug charges April 14 was reduced by baseball commissioner Bud 
Selig on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry said he was having a tough time when he was arrested.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was in a very bad place as far as the way I was thinking,''  
he told The Post. ``Everything was real complicated and I had a 
tough time thinking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry said he became depressed when he was told he wouldn't  
be on the Yankees' Opening Day roster, and stopped going to 
Alcoholics Anonymous meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I learned again that I am a recovering alcoholic and can't  
miss meetings ever,'' he said. ``I am no different than any other 
alcoholic. If I don't go to meetings, I am going to drink.' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry said he hasn't had a drink since the day he was  
arrested, and is eager to resume his career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm feeling good and I'm ready to get on with my life,''  
Strawberry said on Monday. ``I'm starting to get into the frame of 
mind of playing. I'm looking forward to it. I'm ready to get 
going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As he prepared to face live pitching for the first time since  
March, Strawberry said he didn't know how long he would be with 
Columbus before he is summoned to The Bronx again. 
</P>
<P>
	``One day at a time, that's the way I look at everything now,''  
he said. ``That's the way I look at life and baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry had a brief chat with Yankees owner George  
Steinbrenner and homered on the last pitch of batting practice to 
wrap up his final workout day in Tampa on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very grateful Mr. Selig has given me the opportunity to  
get back to baseball and just move forward with my life,'' said 
Strawberry. ``The whole situation is behind me now and I just want 
to concentrate on what I have to do on the field. Hopefully, I can 
help the ballclub throughout the remainder of the season.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
