<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Illuminata' Is a Family Affair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- John Turturro is star, director, co-writer and  
co-producer of ``Illuminata.'' But it is far from a one-man show. 
</P>
<P>
	The film follows a theater company in early 1900s New York as it  
performs a new play written by Turturro's character, Tuccio. 
</P>
<P>
	``To build or create anything, you need more than one person,''  
Turturro said during an interview. ``Most movies are about one or 
two people and that's it. This has so many characters that are 
interwoven, it's like any real-life community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Turturro and co-writer Brandon Cole completed the screenplay in  
1994. But they needed to attach some high-profile actors to the 
project before they could get it made. 
</P>
<P>
	``People always liked the script, but that's the problem with  
almost any movie -- you need a movie star to get a movie funded,'' 
Turturro said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ensemble cast includes Susan Sarandon, Christopher Walken,  
Ben Gazzara and Beverly D'Angelo. Casting was based on Turturro's 
instinct, using actors he admires. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was looking for people who could be inventive but people who  
you could also feel their heart and warmth,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	As the director of ``Illuminata,'' Turturro had to be even more  
passionate than usual about this project. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to sustain yourself five times as long -- from  
beginning to end -- and you're involved in every little aspect. In 
this film, I was never bored at all because every aspect and every 
person interested me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The on-screen community must have felt familiar to Turturro. His  
wife, Katherine Borowitz, is his leading lady; his cousin, Aida, is 
a member of the fictitious repertory company; his son, Amadeo, 
plays one of the young boys who lives with the company; and several 
of his Yale University classmates filled acting or production 
roles. 
</P>
<P>
	A central theme is the difficulty of making love last after  
infatuation has worn away. Setting the film within a theater 
company allowed the characters to exaggerate. But the beauty, lust 
and ridiculous behavior is rooted in reality, Turturro said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to make a film -- even though there is all this  
metaphor -- that actually resonates with what people go through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added, ``Women are in all of the powerful positions, more or  
less. And the men are trying to act powerful. That's how it really 
is. Only in the movies do you see the woman crying and the man 
swings in to save her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Turturro wrote the film with Borowitz in mind, describing his  
wife and her character as strong and confident, yet very feminine. 
</P>
<P>
	``We needed someone to ground it and give you -- the audience --  
someone to relate to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, ``Illuminata'' is not the Turturro-Borowitz story. That  
would be ``too boring,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Turturro has appeared in three dozen films. He is currently  
working on a new film with George Clooney. He has struck a 
professional balance that gives him enough clout in Hollywood to 
open doors but still maintain his everyday life in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some people who are really pure `movie stars,' but  
the whole idea of that doesn't really appeal to me as a person,'' 
he said. ``I think it's a very limiting position to be in. Life 
isn't like that, and we all have to have contact with other 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daily life for Turturro, 42, doesn't include pampering and  
comparing box-office grosses. Instead, he prefers to take his son 
to school, go to the gym, read a newspaper and run an errand for 
his wife. Sometimes, he'll even catch a matinee movie -- even though 
he finds watching his own films with an audience nerve-racking. 
</P>
<P>
	``I get to live interesting existences when I'm doing a movie,''  
he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
