<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Aug. 4, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Close Lower; Dow Down 2.54  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks collapsed in the final  
half-hour of trading today, deflating a rally fueled by the news of 
a $9.3 billion merger of Dow Chemical and Union Carbide. The Dow 
Jones industrial average closed down 2.54 at 10,674.77. The Dow, 
following what is becoming a familiar pattern, gave up nearly all 
its gains late in the day and wiped out what had been a 152-point 
advance. The broader market, plagued by fears of inflation, 
declined much more steeply. The Nasdaq composite index fell 48.07 
to 2,539.92. Analysts said the market fell prey to continuing 
worries that the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates in an 
attempt to stave off inflation. 

</P>
