</P>
<P>
	Dow Chemical To Buy Union Carbide  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The Dow Chemical Co., the maker of Styrofoam, is  
buying Union Carbide Corp., the leader in producing the chemicals 
used in making polyester and antifreeze. The $9.3 billion deal 
announced today would create the world's second-largest chemical 
business behind DuPont Co., strengthening Dow's perch in a sluggish 
chemical market beset by depressed prices. The merged company, 
which will operate under the Dow Chemical name, will have $24 
billion in annual revenue, putting it ahead of the current No. 2, 
Germany's BASF AG, according to the most recent rankings by 
Chemical Week magazine. About 2,000 jobs will be cut as a result of 
the merger, leaving about 49,000 employees. Shares of Dow were at 
118 5/8, down 6 1/16; Union Carbide was at 59 3/8, up 10 9/16 or about 21 
percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Factory Orders Rise in June  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Greater demand for autos and electronic  
equipment helped push orders to U.S. factories up 0.7 percent in 
June. It was the 10th gain in the last 13 months, and it is seen as 
a fresh sign that the manufacturing sector is recovering. The 
figure announced by the Commerce Department today followed a 1 
percent gain in May. The June rise was larger than many analysts 
had anticipated. 

</P>
<P>
	Chase Buys Mellon's Mortgage Outfit  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chase Manhattan Corp.'s mortgage subsidiary has  
agreed to purchase the residential mortgage business of Mellon 
Bank, N.A. Chase was the nation's third-largest residential 
mortgage originator last year, writing $85 billion in new loans, 
while Mellon originated $8 billion. Chase moved to first place in 
the first two quarters of this year, passing Countrywide and 
Norwest Mortgage. With the acquisition, Chase would rise to first 
place from third in servicing residential loans, surpassing Bank of 
America and Norwest, said Steve Kim, research director at Inside 
Mortgage Finance, an industry newsletter. Shares of Chase Manhattan 
were at 78 7/16, down 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Sega, AT&AMP;T Unveil Dreamcast Pact  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Owners of Sega's long-awaited Dreamcast  
video game console will be able to challenge gamers across the 
street or across the country, using a built-in modem and AT&AMP;T 
Corp.'s Internet service AT&AMP;T and Sega announced a deal today, 
making AT&AMP;T the preferred partner for hooking Dreamcast to the 
Internet. However those who are already online using a different 
Internet service provider will also be able to connect to the Sega 
Dreamcast Network. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Promises To Veto Tax Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today promised to veto a  
Republican plan that would lower the tax rate of every American who 
pays income tax. He called the bill ``risky and plainly wrong for 
America.'' The 10-year, $792 billion tax cut package put together 
by House and Senate Republicans would gradually cut 1 percentage 
point off each personal income tax rate. It also would provide 
relief from the so-called marriage penalty, cut the individual 
capital-gains tax rate and eventually eliminate the estate tax. 

</P>
<P>
	Exec: Auto Biz Needs New Talent  
</P>
<P>
	TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) -- The auto industry faces ``a  
potentially devastating shortage of talent'' worldwide and must 
change its outdated image to attract the highly skilled workers it 
needs, a top Ford Motor Co. executive said today. Vice Chairman 
Peter Pestillo told an industry conference that the general public, 
including educators and students, has a perception of auto 
manufacturing is a second-class industry taking place in dark, 
dirty environments, He added that the auto work force is perceived 
as uneducated and unskilled. ``We need to do a better job of 
informing the outside world that our industry offers opportunities 
for forward-thinkers.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Honda Vows To Stay Independent  
</P>
<P>
	TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) -- Honda Motor Co. is committed to  
remaining independent despite the trend toward consolidation of the 
auto industry, president Hiroyuki Yoshino said today. Speaking at 
an industry conference, Yoshino disputed the conventional wisdom of 
industry executives that only large, global automakers with great 
economies of scale will survive in the 21st century. Yoshino said 
Honda does not need to merge with another automaker to expand its 
global presence. It already has 100 plants in 34 countries, part of 
its longstanding policy of developing and building cars, 
motorcycles and other motorized products in the markets where 
they're sold. 

</P>
<P>
	Share Prices Mixed in Europe Trading  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Share prices were mixed on European stock  
exchanges today as rising steel stocks were offset by a drop in 
some technology and telecommunications shares. Dealers said steel 
shares were buoyed by hopes of a price increase and by news that 
plans for a merger between British Steel and Amsterdam-based steel 
manufacturer Hoogovens are on track. The Dow Jones Basic Resources 
index was the best performer on the day, with a gain of 2.3 
percent, as British Steel shares rose 4 pence to 170.45 pence and 
Hoogovens shares rose 1.80 euros to 56.70 euros. The Dow Jones Euro 
Stoxx Index, which tracks 297 companies in countries that have 
joined the single currency, closed down 0.99 points at 309.43. 

</P>
