<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 07:58:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Customs To Change Search Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dogged by investigations and lawsuits alleging  
abusive searches, the Customs Service is revising its policies for 
checking airline passengers for drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Customs already has posted new signs and brochures at airports  
explaining why body searches might be required and offering people 
comment cards to use in the event of mistreatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the agency is revamping its handbook and internal policies  
on personal searches, work that may be completed soon, law 
enforcement officials said Tuesday. They spoke on condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	An independent panel created in April to review the policies and  
procedures used by customs inspectors to search for drugs also is 
expected to release its findings soon, the officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	They would not discuss any specific changes under consideration.  
</P>
<P>
	Customs officers use searches to try to catch smugglers who hide  
cocaine or heroin inside their clothes or swallow packets of drugs. 
The searches usually begin with a pat-down and, with reasonable 
suspicion, can proceed to a strip search, X-ray or monitored bowel 
movement. 
</P>
<P>
	Just last week, the Customs Service announced that six major  
airports will be getting new high-tech scanning machines that will 
let inspectors see whether a passenger may be concealing illegal 
drugs. Inspectors could use the machines rather than performing the 
other kinds of searches. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency is facing numerous lawsuits over body searches,  
including suits, first reported by The Associated Press last 
December, alleging that people were singled out because of their 
race and gender. 
</P>
<P>
	Only 50,892 of the 71.5 million international air travelers who  
passed through customs in 1998 were subjected to some level of body 
search, most of them simple pat-downs, customs officials have said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those whose race was recorded, almost as many blacks and  
Hispanics as whites were subjected to the more serious strip or 
body cavity searches or sent to hospitals for X-rays in 1998, 
customs has said. A year earlier, 50 percent more blacks and 
Hispanics were subjected to those searches than whites. 
</P>
<P>
	For those subjected to such searches or X-rays, drugs were found  
on 30 percent of blacks, compared with 31 percent the year before; 
27 percent of Hispanics, down from 33 percent; and 19 percent of 
whites, down from 26 percent in 1997, customs has said. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, President Clinton ordered federal law enforcement  
officers, including customs, to document the race and gender of 
those they arrest or detain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 15:30:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ravens' Woodson Switches Positions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WESTMINSTER, Md. (AP) -- Rod Woodson spent the past 12 years  
doggedly pursuing the very best receivers in the NFL, zigging when 
they zigged and zagging when they zagged. 
</P>
<P>
	After 47 interceptions, 164 games and seven Pro Bowls, the  
future Hall of Famer is ready to take a break. 
</P>
<P>
	Retirement? Not a chance. Woodson, 34, is doing the next best  
thing, though -- this season he has moved from cornerback to safety 
for the Baltimore Ravens. The switch is an indication that he's 
lost a step, but Woodson has absolutely no complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	For one thing, he no longer walks off the field at training camp  
with his tongue hanging out and sweat pouring down his face. And he 
knows he doesn't have the legs to keep up with young cornerbacks 
Chris McAlister, Duane Starks and DeRon Jenkins. 
</P>
<P>
	``The coaches want to try the young guys and I understand that.  
They know I can play corner and now they want to see what I can do 
at safety,'' Woodson said. ``I'm fine with that. Safety is a lot 
easier than corner (and) it's a lot easier on the body.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woodson last played safety at Purdue in the mid-1980s. Drafted  
in the first round by the Pittsburgh Steelers, he was converted to 
cornerback and went on to become one of the finest ever to play the 
position. After spending a decade in Pittsburgh and one season in 
San Francisco, he joined the Ravens as a free agent last season and 
recorded a team-high six interceptions. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, as his career winds down, Woodson is getting reacquainted  
with the view from far off the line of scrimmage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Playing safety is fun. It's different,'' he said. ``I just  
want to help the team win. I always thought I was a natural safety, 
anyway. At corner, you have to be ready to run on every play. At 
safety, you run, but you can gamble a little more and kind of pick 
and choose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New coach Brian Billick is apprehensive about beginning the  
season with a trio of cornerbacks that have a combined three years 
of NFL experience, but having Woodson in the backfield makes him 
feels a little better about the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the athletic ability we have outside and the experience  
that Rod has, he ought to be able to hold things together back 
there,'' Billick said. ``Rod at safety, it just fits where he is in 
his career and I think he recognizes that. That doesn't preclude 
him from going to the corner in certain situations, but right now 
it's the best use of his abilities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woodson's value to the Ravens goes beyond interceptions, tackles  
and swatting away passes. Because he's played a dozen years and the 
rest of the backfield is relatively young, Woodson is also playing 
the role of an on-the-field teacher and coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been blessed with a lot of fine coaches who have taught  
me a lot about the game of football. I think it would be very 
selfish on my part if I didn't give something back to the guys,'' 
he said. ``I'll give them my input and they can take it for what 
it's worth.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 14:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: No Excuse for Infidelity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said Wednesday his childhood  
was no ``bed of roses'' but that it was no excuse for bad behavior 
as an adult. 
</P>
<P>
	His wife, campaigning for the Senate, said she hadn't meant to  
imply that childhood ``abuse'' explained away his infidelity. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Clintons said they ``love each other very much.'' Clinton  
added an extra ``very.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president's comments were his first public remarks on  
Hillary Rodham Clinton's magazine interview, in which she drew an 
apparent link between the chaos of Clinton's Arkansas boyhood and 
what she described as his ``weakness'' and lack of self-control as 
an adult. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe that anybody could fairly read the article and  
think that she was making any excuses for me,'' Clinton said. ``I 
have not made any excuses for what was inexcusable, and neither has 
she, believe me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His comments came in answer to a reporter's question at the  
close of a Rose Garden appearance on economic themes, including the 
GOP-passed tax cut bill. 
</P>
<P>
	During a visit to Jamestown, N.Y., Mrs. Clinton sang much the  
same tune. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody is responsible for their behavior, and I am a very  
strong proponent and believer in personal responsibility, so I hope 
that people will take that message away from this,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters later he knew  
of no plan to coordinate the Clintons' statements. 
</P>
<P>
	The first couple's comments were meant to quiet the hubbub about  
Mrs. Clinton's reference to childhood ``abuse'' in an interview in 
the debut issue of Talk magazine. She said Wednesday she believes 
the country has put the issue of the Clintons' marital problems 
behind it, and ``I have as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Talk interview was described by people close to Mrs. Clinton  
as a political calculation: lay out her thoughts on the Monica 
Lewinsky sex scandal now, and the issue will be less troublesome 
later in the 2000 Senate race the first lady is considering. 
</P>
<P>
	Without naming Ms. Lewinsky, Mrs. Clinton said of her husband in  
the interview, ``Yes, he has his weaknesses. Yes, he needs to be 
more responsible, more disciplined, but it is remarkable given his 
background that he turned out to be the kind of person he is, 
capable of such leadership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Expanding on her husband's background, Mrs. Clinton said he was  
scarred at age 4 by a struggle between his mother and grandmother. 
</P>
<P>
	``A psychologist once told me that for a boy being in the middle  
of a conflict between two women is the worst possible situation,'' 
she said. ``There is always a desire to please each one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Biographical accounts of Clinton's childhood describe a willful,  
powerful grandmother, ``Mammaw,'' and her hold on both her widowed 
daughter, Clinton's mother Virginia, and her grandson. 
</P>
<P>
	In her autobiography, Clinton's mother also recounted a power  
struggle with her mother, much of it while the young Clinton and 
his mother lived with his grandparents. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton looked pensive Wednesday as he spoke about his childhood  
in Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't have a bed of roses as a kid,'' Clinton said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think every reflective person thinks about his or her  
life,'' he added. ``But what I conclude about my childhood is what 
I said. It had its really tough moments, but I always knew I was 
well-loved, and I think that's important for all of our children.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 15:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers To Stay in Vero Beach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Dodgers will hold spring  
training in Vero Beach, Fla., for at least one more year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgers made the announcement Wednesday, saying they have  
formally declined the Fort McDowell Tribal Council's final proposal 
to construct a spring training facility on the Fort McDowell 
Yavapai Reservation in Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgers have conducted spring training at Dodgertown in Vero  
Beach every year since 1948. 
</P>
<P>
	``Together, we have made every effort to explore the various  
alternatives which would have enabled us to move our spring 
training operations to Fort McDowell,'' Dodgers president Bob 
Graziano said in a statement. ``Although we were unable to accept 
the Council's final proposal, we certainly appreciate the magnitude 
of the commitment that this project would have required from the 
people of Fort McDowell. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our plans are to continue our discussions with city and county  
officials in Vero Beach and to conduct spring training in 
Dodgertown in the year 2000.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 07:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tribes Seek Money for Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- American Indian tribes now run about half of  
the health care and other programs once managed by the federal 
government, but tribes have not gotten enough money to manage them, 
tribal leaders told a House committee on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The total shortfall for tribes' administrative costs was less  
than $200 million a year, said Dr. Michael Trujillo, director of 
the Indian Health Service. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, chairman of the House Resources  
Committee, said some of the blame lies with the budget-writing 
committees in the House and Senate, which have not provided the 
money needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a commitment. There is an entitlement. There is an  
obligation,'' Young said. ``The amount of money isn't that big. 
It's one cruise missile.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A 1975 federal law allows tribes to take over management of  
hospitals, clinics, law enforcement, social services, land 
management and other programs once run by the Bureau of Indian 
Affairs, the Indian Health Service or other government agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	The law, however, requires the government to provide enough  
money to pay for the tribes' overhead and startup costs for taking 
over those programs. Tribal leaders and officials in the Clinton 
administration, say Congress has not provided enough money to cover 
these costs for most of the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	Several tribes are suing the federal government to force it to  
pay all administrative costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indian Health Service, for example, now pays tribes between  
70 percent and 80 percent of the money they need to run health 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	At Arizona's Gila River Indian Community, officials are  
considering cutting back ambulance service from 24 to eight hours a 
day because there is not enough money to cover management costs, 
tribal Gov. Mary Thomas told the committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Gila River took over most of its reservation health programs in  
1996, but did not get paid for administrative costs until last 
year, when the tribe got 56 percent of what was needed, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The lack of money for administrative costs is just one example  
of how Indian programs are underfunded, said Kevin Gover, assistant 
Interior Department secretary who heads the BIA. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would need to triple our budget to meet the programmatic  
objectives given to us by Congress,'' said Gover, who urged the 
panel to pass legislation to give tribes more money to cover 
administrative costs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
