<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vikings Rookie Remains AWOL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANKATO, Minn. (AP) -- Dimitrius Underwood might have cost  
himself a job with the Minnesota Vikings by failing to return to 
training camp Wednesday as promised. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, a first-round draft pick, went AWOL after his first  
pro practice on Monday but apologetically called his agent 24 hours 
later saying he'd needed to tend to a family crisis and was on his 
way back to camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, who signed a five-year, $5.3 million contract on  
Sunday, was absent from Wednesday's workouts, too, leaving coach 
Dennis Green stewed and general manager Tim Connolly stumped. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have not talked to him at all,'' Green said. ``We've got a  
football camp here. He knows where it's at and he knows where his 
room is. He is not here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Green insisted Underwood's absence didn't distract the team.  
</P>
<P>
	``Our football players love the guys that are here and they  
don't care one bit about the guys that aren't,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although his tone suggested otherwise, Green said he wasn't  
angry. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, I'm focused on the football team,'' he said. ``I think  
every young man has a right to do what he wants to do, that's part 
of being a man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first thing Underwood would have to do upon his return is  
meet with Green, who would decide whether to take him back. 
</P>
<P>
	``If someone doesn't want to be here, there's no way that we can  
force him to be here,'' Connolly said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings have already acted to move on without Underwood.  
</P>
<P>
	They went to federal court in Minneapolis Tuesday to keep him  
from getting the more than $500,000 after-taxes bonus that was 
wired to his bank in Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	And they informed the league they had placed him on the  
active-left squad list, meaning Underwood has until Sunday to 
return or his season would be finished and his salary terminated. 
</P>
<P>
	If he returns, he could face fines of up to $5,000 per day  
missed and the team could also try to recover some or all of his 
signing bonus of $1,725,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Connolly said he didn't know what would happen.  
</P>
<P>
	``Denny makes the personnel decision and frankly (Underwood's)  
missing and it's impossible for us to have a dialogue,'' Connolly 
said. ``Of course, Denny's going to move on. Denny has to worry 
about this football team. We've got 81 other guys to worry about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A message left with Underwood's agent, Craig Domann, wasn't  
immediately returned Wednesday. Domann's voice mail said he was out 
of the office all day. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday night, Domann said that Underwood planned to meet  
with Green either that night or Wednesday morning. ``He apologized 
for his unprofessional exit without telling anybody that he had an 
urgent family matter,'' Domann said. 
</P>
<P>
	Domann declined to go into specifics about the player's  
explanation or the whereabouts of Underwood, a 6-foot-6, 276-pound 
defensive end from Michigan State and the 29th selection in the NFL 
draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood left without explanation Monday after a forgettable  
performance in his first workout. He left his personal possessions 
in his dorm room and caught a cab to the Minneapolis-St. Paul 
Airport 90 miles north, where he apparently bought a ticket to 
Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never had a player leave without letting you know, even  
though it happens, it's not unusual,'' Green said. ``There have 
been many stories of guys with their suitcase bouncing down the 
steps as they snuck out in the middle of the night. That wasn't the 
case. He left during the middle of the day and he didn't take his 
clothes with him.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
