<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Books and Authors: Judith Michael </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- What do you get when you combine journalist  
Judith Barnard and aerospace engineer Michael Fain? Best-selling 
novelist Judith Michael. 
</P>
<P>
	The husband-and-wife team have combined their names, her  
penchant for writing and his flair for the more methodical -- 
translation: editing -- into 10 best-selling novels that blend a 
love story with fantasy, reality and adventure. 
</P>
<P>
	At their spacious 16th-floor apartment overlooking Chicago's  
Lincoln Park and their home in a secluded section of Aspen, Colo., 
the pair have most recently completed ``A Certain Smile,'' the 
story of a widowed fashion designer who travels to China where she 
puts inhibitions aside and falls in love. 
</P>
<P>
	Their writing adventure began after they were married in 1979.  
They met in the corridors of a hospital. ``Bittersweet times as 
Michael's mother was dying and we were falling in love,'' Barnard 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnard already had written educational films, textbooks and a  
novel. Once married, the two began collaborating on magazine 
articles that appeared in publications such as Redbook and Good 
Housekeeping. 
</P>
<P>
	``We ... had such a good time working together that one day  
Michael said, 'Enough of this! Why don't we write a book?''' 
Barnard recalled as she sat on a sofa beside Fain in the living 
room in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The thought of giving up magazine writing to gamble the next two  
years on a novel frightened Barnard. ``I said, 'I would rather keep 
getting checks all the time.''' 
</P>
<P>
	But they pushed ahead, and in 1982, the first Judith Michael  
book, ``Deceptions,'' was published. In 1985, it was made into a TV 
movie. 
</P>
<P>
	The book was a success, but money wasn't the only consideration.  
Writer-editor relationships are often tense. And when the editor is 
the writer's husband? 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very difficult to have a working relationship with this  
person who you think has done really dumb things that day and is 
going to be in your bed,'' Barnard says. 
</P>
<P>
	While both acknowledge their endeavor was difficult at first,  
conflicts eased once both gained confidence. ``Michael learned how 
to give criticism and I learned how to take it. ... We really don't 
fight about'' it anymore, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	When tempers did soar, Fain, a photographer, would retreat to  
his darkroom, while Barnard, an avid cook, headed to the kitchen. 
``She would knead bread and take out her aggressions on the 
bread,'' Fain said. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, the couple, now in their 60s, have learned to  
respect each other's privacy and feelings. Both of their homes have 
his-and-her offices, each with its own library. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want either one of us to look at the other and say,  
'Why aren't you working?' which is what we did at the beginning,'' 
Barnard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Chicago offices offer views of the city's skyline and house  
personal objects -- a chess game in his, a collage her father made 
in hers. 
</P>
<P>
	Their home reflects the things they love. A mural depicts an  
Aspen scene. Art books rest atop a piano. A wall leading to the 
offices is lined with black-and-white photographs Fain has taken of 
a Holocaust memorial in Israel, an Aspen waterfall, a Chicago 
cemetery and more. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple's creative process begins with brainstorming until  
they agree on a general plot and characters. Then they write a 
summary, which always includes a fantasy such as winning the 
lottery. 
</P>
<P>
	They always travel to the countries they write about -- China,  
Switzerland, Australia, Egypt, Italy, France, Canada, England. In 
China, for example, they toured a food market the book's heroine 
also would visit. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, Barnard begins writing and Fain starts editing.  
</P>
<P>
	``That means writing it about six times because everything gets  
edited,'' Barnard said. ``It takes longer to write with two people 
than one,'' she added. 
</P>
<P>
	Fain, who also does technical research and scene-writing,  
believes the writing partnership has strengthened their marriage, 
``because it's made us think about how we interact.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he doesn't think it's for everyone. ``It takes a certain  
person, a set of personalities,'' he said. ``It also takes a real 
desire to want to do it. And it's difficult. ... But when it works 
like for us, it's wonderful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barnard offers a more lighthearted view:. ``It probably kept us  
married because we always had a book to finish. You can't leave if 
you're in the middle of a book. And then, by the time the book is 
done, the tension is gone so you don't remember even what you were 
arguing about.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
