<HEADLINE> Dow Chemical, Union Carbide Details </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Facts about The Dow Chemical Corp. and Union Carbide Corp.,  
which have agreed to merge, creating the world's second-largest 
chemical business after DuPont Co. 

</P>
<P>
 *THE DOW CHEMICAL CO.   	

</P>
<P>
	Headquarters: Midland, Mich.  
</P>
<P>
	Founded: 1897  
</P>
<P>
	1998 revenues: $18.4 billion  
</P>
<P>
	1998 earnings: $1.3 billion  
</P>
<P>
	Employees: 39,000  
</P>
<P>
	Products: Plastics, chemicals used in various industries,  
including Styrofoam insulation; herbicides. 
</P>
<P>
	Ranking: Third in the world in sales of chemical products behind  
No. 1 DuPont Co. and No. 2 BASF AG of Germany, according to 
Chemical Week. Ranks second to DuPont in U.S. sales. 

</P>
<P>
 *UNION CARBIDE CORP.   	
</P>
<P>
	Headquarters: Danbury, Conn.  
</P>
<P>
	Founded: 1917, as Union Carbide &AMP; Carbon Corp.  
</P>
<P>
	1998 revenues: $5.7 billion  
</P>
<P>
	1998 earnings: $403 million  
</P>
<P>
	Employees: 11,600  
</P>
<P>
	Products: Basic and specialty chemicals, including ethylene  
oxide (used in antifreeze) and ethylene glycol (used in polyester). 
</P>
<P>
	Ranking: 21st in the world in sales of chemical products and 7th  
in the United States. 



  	   	
</P>
