<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  MLS Boots Logan for NFL Executive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Seeking more fans and higher television ratings,  
Major League Soccer turned to the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	Don Garber, who has spent the last three years running the NFL's  
European league, was hired as MLS commissioner on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Doug Logan, the only commissioner in the four years of the  
soccer league, was forced to resign. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday I was an 'is,''' Logan said at the start of the news  
conference. ``Today I'm a 'was.' Tomorrow, I assure you, I'm going 
to be an 'is' again. There's no elegant way to say I was fired.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His resignation was sought by Stuart Subotnick, the MLS board of  
governors chairman of the New York-New Jersey MetroStars. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don brings expertise that Doug didn't have,'' said Subotnick,  
adding that the league must pay more attention to fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``A fan is no different than a customer,'' he said. ``If you  
want a successful business, you need to get the loyalty of the 
customer, in this case the fan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We started with a bang, it leveled off and we're creeping up  
again. That's OK if you want a middling business. We don't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Subotnick repeatedly referred to Garber's experience in  
marketing and public relations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not done a good job promoting the players,'' he said.  
``That's part of what you're going to find Don doing over time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garber is not well versed in soccer, but Subotnick said that  
will not be a liability. He pointed to Garber's success at 
introducing American football into Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	MLS attendance has only started to rebound after two straight  
years of decline, and is still well below the average crowd of 
17,406 it achieved in its first season. The league's TV ratings are 
flat, and have been that way since the beginning of the league's 
second year. 
</P>
<P>
	And some team officials have grumbled about Logan, particularly  
following his dismissal of deputy commissioner Sunil Gulati in 
February. 
</P>
<P>
	Gulati has been a major figure in American soccer for more than  
a decade. He played a key role in the organizing committee of the 
1994 World Cup, the U.S. Soccer Federation and the formation of 
MLS. 
</P>
<P>
	Gulati remains a consultant with the league, but Subotnick said  
he would not join the new administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Logan acknowledged he no longer had the confidence of the board  
of governors. When he finished his remarks, he stepped down from 
the dais and left the room. Garber and Subotnick then spoke. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're at an OK level, but not where we want to be as far as  
fan participation,'' Subotnick said in introducing Garber. 
</P>
<P>
	Garber, 41, has spent the last 15 years as a senior marketing  
and management executive with the NFL. Since 1996, he has been 
senior vice president/managing director of NFL International. 
</P>
<P>
	He was responsible for managing all business of the NFL outside  
the United States, overseeing TV production and distribution, 
marketing and fan development activities, sponsorship sales and 
licensing. 
</P>
<P>
	``He took a foreign sport and achieved success with it in an  
area of the world where they don't play the game or view it on a 
regular basis,'' Subotnick said. ``Don's experience will help MLS 
capitalize on the extraordinary opportunity to make its mark among 
American sports spectators.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garber said he wants to establish a closer connection to those  
who play soccer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to translate the tens of millions who play the game  
into those who go and watch it on TV,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
