<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Rise on Debt News / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bonds rose sharply Wednesday, snapping a  
four-session losing streak, as investors shrugged off worries about 
inflation and interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 25/32  
point, or $7.81 1/4 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, a key 
influence on borrowing costs, fell to 6.09 percent from late 
Tuesday's 6.16 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The market, which has been weighed down by signs of inflationary  
pressure, ended its recent slump as the White House said it is 
exploring ways to buy back part of the $3.6 trillion national debt 
held by the public, something that has not occurred since 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury Department released for public comment a proposal  
that would allow it to take competitive offers from bond holders on 
a voluntary basis to reduce the amount of debt. Officials said they 
hope to establish final rules for the procedure by January. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
rose 3/32 to 1/8 point, while intermediate-term Treasurys rose 5/32 
to 3/16 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Wednesday, yields on three-month Treasury bills  
fell to 4.75 percent while the discount fell to 4.63 percent, down 
0.07 percentage point from Tuesday's levels. Yields on six-month 
Treasurys fell to 4.97 percent as the discount fell to 4.78 
percent, down 0.03 percentage point. One-year yields fell to 5.07 
percent as the discount fell to 4.82 percent, down 0.07 percentage 
point from late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4.87 1/2 percent from 4.93 3/4 percent on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/16 point to 117 1/4. The average yield 
to maturity rose to 5.60 percent from 5.59 percent on Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
