<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. May Buy Back Debt  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States, which for most of the  
century has struggled to borrow money for the burgeoning national 
debt, is now figuring out ways to buy back some of the $3.6 
trillion debt held by the public. The Treasury Department today 
issued proposals for the debt buyback and plans to finalize details 
by Jan. 1. Officials said any government purchases of debt would be 
conducted through a reverse auction. The government would announce 
the type of securities it was interested in buying and accept 
competitive bids from holders of those securities. 

</P>
<P>
	Tax Bill Pushed Despite Veto Threat  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican leaders plan to move the $792  
billion tax cut package through the House and Senate tomorrow 
despite President Clinton's repeated veto threats. The 10-year 
package would gradually cut 1 percentage point off each personal 
income tax rate. It also would provide relief from the so-called 
marriage penalty, cut the individual capital-gains tax rate and 
eventually eliminate the estate tax. Clinton says the tax cut would 
use up almost all of the projected non-Social Security surplus over 
the next decade, leaving almost nothing for needed government 
programs and paying down the national debt. 

</P>
<P>
	Drought Takes Its Toll  
</P>
<P>
	ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) -- The drought is devastating crops and  
ruining lawns from Virginia to New England. Parts of the worst-hit 
Middle Atlantic States are seeing the driest 12-month period ever 
recorded. Experts say it could take a tropical storm to reverse the 
conditions. Maryland became the first state to impose mandatory 
water-use restrictions backed by the threat of fines up to $1,000. 
All of West Virginia has been declared a drought disaster, and 
Virginia is seeking the same designation for some areas. Delaware, 
Pennsylvania and New Jersey either have declared drought 
emergencies or are in the process of doing so. 

</P>
<P>
	Web Investors Still Optimistic  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The big selloff in Internet stocks that began  
quietly during the spring is accelerating, decimating the 
phenomenal gains achieved this year by many high-profile online 
companies. Online stocks dragged down the technology-laden Nasdaq 
composite index for a fifth-straight day today, leaving it 11.3 
percent lower than the all-time high it reached July 16. The 
40-stock Dow Jones Internet Index has shed more than 40 percent of 
its value since its all-time high April 13. 

</P>
<P>
	E-Commerce Means Business' Savings  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- A study being released tomorrow predicts  
that corporations around the world will save up to $1.25 trillion -- 
close to France's entire gross domestic product -- doing business 
over the Internet by 2002. Those savings range from reducing the 
amount of people it takes to process a sales request to making it 
easier and less expensive to order office supplies online. The 
study was conducted by Giga Information Group. 

</P>
<P>
	Strip Class Offered at Mt. Holyoke  
</P>
<P>
	SOUTH HADLEY, Mass. (AP) -- Students at one of the nation's  
oldest women's colleges can learn to take it off, all off. Susan 
Scotto, who stripped in clubs while earning her doctorate, said her 
noncredit how-to class in striptease at Mount Holyoke College was 
so popular last year that she will offer it again. Ms. Scotto shows 
students clips from movies featuring strippers, teaches them some 
basic bump-and-grind moves and supplies them with props, including 
feather boas, fans and high heels. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes Down 2.54  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks collapsed in the final  
half-hour of trading today, deflating a rally fueled by news of a 
$9.3 billion merger of Dow Chemical and Union Carbide. The Dow 
Jones industrial average closed down 2.54 at 10,674.77. On the 
NYSE, decliners led advancers 2,008-1,008. The technology-dominated 
Nasdaq was down 48.07 at 2,539.92, ending 11.3 percent below its 
July 16 record high of 2,864.48. 

</P>
<P>
	Clippers Trade Murray for Anderson  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Clippers acquired guard Derek  
Anderson and forward Johnny Newman from the Cleveland Cavaliers 
today in exchange for forward Lamond Murray. The Cavaliers had been 
unable to work out a long-term contract extension with Anderson. 
Terms were not disclosed but The Orange County Register reported 
today that Murray would get a seven-year, $25 million deal. 
Anderson, 25, was entering the final year of his contract and was 
reportedly seeking a seven-year, $60 million extension. 

</P>
<P>
	Faulk Signs $45M Deal With Rams  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The St. Louis Rams and holdout running back  
Marshall Faulk today agreed to a seven-year deal worth about $45 
million. Faulk, who has rushed for 5,320 yards in five NFL seasons, 
will be paid $19 million the first four seasons. He'll get $9.6 
million this year, including a $7 million signing bonus and $2.6 
million base salary. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
