<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Sues Texas Investment Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Federal regulators charge that a Texas investment  
firm defrauded investors of up to $475 million by making 
speculative investments and selling virtually worthless securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The Securities and Exchange Commission filed a lawsuit Wednesday  
in federal court in San Antonio against InverWorld Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents from the FBI, the SEC and the IRS executed search  
warrants at the business offices of InverWorld and its chairman, 
Jose P. Zollino, in connection with a criminal investigation, an 
FBI spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC lawsuit and the search warrants are the latest  
developments in an emerging scandal surrounding InverWorld, which 
catered mostly to wealthy investors in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	In late June, InverWorld affiliates in Great Britain and the  
Cayman Islands told investors they were closing and freezing all 
accounts. Those affiliates are now in liquidation proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC said InverWorld, Zollino, 51, company President George  
F. Fahey, 62, and three affiliated companies may have lost 
investors' money through risky, unauthorized investments. The 
lawsuit also charged that an affiliate company issued practically 
worthless securities to investors. 
</P>
<P>
	According to related court filings by InverWorld affiliates, the  
company had as many as 1,000 investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC said InverWorld's clients were interested in low-risk  
investments outside Latin America, including money-market accounts 
and U.S. Treasuries, but that InverWorld put their money in risky 
investments in ``volatile emerging markets'' and with entities 
closely related to InverWorld. It said fraudulent statements 
concealed the nature of the investments from clients. 
</P>
<P>
	Allan Diamond, a Houston lawyer who said he is representing  
about 100 investors who put more than $100 million in InverWorld, 
said the SEC charges are similar to what clients have told him. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of questions of what else happened, given the  
size of the losses,'' Diamond said. ``Everyone believed they were 
investing money in safe investments that would have reasonable 
yields and they could rely on in their retirement. You had people 
putting their life savings in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lamont Jefferson, a Dallas lawyer for InverWorld's domestic  
companies, said the investments were all in accordance with 
contracts signed by the investors. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been bad investments in global markets. It's a  
risky business, and you can lose money in those markets,'' 
Jefferson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jefferson said he didn't know how the money was lost, whether it  
was one bad investment or a series of smaller ones. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC is seeking a freeze of assets at the companies, civil  
penalties and a repayment of funds. It asked that a temporary 
receiver be appointed to oversee InverWorld. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal officials said some of the securities sold to investors  
were issued by IWG Services Ltd., an InverWorld affiliate in London 
that was essentially a mail drop -- it had no offices or employees. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the SEC, InverWorld, Zollino and Fahey used IWG and  
Cayman Islands-based IG Services Ltd. as ``shells'' to move money 
beyond the reach of investors and regulators. The SEC said $210 
million was transferred to Swiss and Bahamian bank accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the SEC, only $90 million in securities may remain.  
</P>
<P>
	Zollino was unavailable for comment. The phone went unanswered  
at InverWorld's headquarters Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	InverWorld has had previous problems with the Internal Revenue  
Service, which is trying to collect $380 million it says InverWorld 
owes in back taxes and penalties for allegedly shifting income 
earned in the United States to foreign subsidiaries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
