<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta Mourns Shooting Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Holding hands and wiping away tears, hundreds of  
relatives and friends of those killed in a day trader's shooting 
rampage gathered Wednesday near the site of the massacre to 
remember the victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``The loss you've suffered is without measure,'' Mayor Bill  
Campbell told the crowd, packed into a church. ``Your sorrow beyond 
words. But know that you are not alone. Today we come together as 
one Atlanta -- beyond race, beyond borders, beyond religion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, just blocks away, Mark O. Barton killed nine people  
and injured 13 at two brokerage offices, then shot himself. Before 
the shootings, he bludgeoned his wife and two children to death. 
</P>
<P>
	The memorial service began with a moment of silence. It ended  
with the lighting of small, red candles-- one for each of the 
victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will struggle with you,'' said the Rev. Don Harp, pastor of  
the church. ``We will work at finding light where darkness has 
come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alyce Wenzel of Huntley, Ill., lost her only son, 30-year-old  
Scott Webb. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess I've cried all I can cry. This was, of course, a  
tribute to Scotty and a way of being able to say it is true, it 
really did happen,'' she said. ``I'm looking at these pictures and 
I'm thinking Scotty's going to call me. He was everything a mother 
could want.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's been a deadly month for Atlanta -- 23 people died in three  
violent episodes last month. Six members of a family were slain in 
their home July 12 and two Cobb County police officers were killed 
in a standoff with a gunman July 23. They were also were honored at 
the service. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Barton's victims, Fred Herder, 54, was released from  
Grady Memorial Hospital Wednesday but eight others remained 
hospitalized, including two in critical condition. Among them was 
Yuzef Liberzon, 39, who was shot twice in the head. 
</P>
<P>
	For Hugh Thomas, 35, who was working in a travel agency on the  
first floor of the building where the rampage began, the memorial 
service was a step toward closure. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will never go away completely because there will always be  
a scar,'' said Thomas, a father of two who was not injured. ``The 
lesson I learned from this was never leave home without kissing 
your children or telling your wife you love her. You may leave and 
never get to see them again.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
