	Aug. 3  
</P>
<P>
	Le Figaro, Paris, on Albanian-Serb reconciliation in Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	Bernard Kouchner (the U.N. special representative who is  
Kosovo's top civilian official) is right to stress that the 
reconciliation between the Albanian and Serb population in Kosovo 
`will take time.' He is discovering the depth of hatred separating 
the two communities, a hatred that 70 days of NATO bombardments 
could in no way heal. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Albanians, it is now the turn of Kosovo's Serbs to be  
the main victims of intolerance. Last week's assassination of 14 
Serbian farmers close to the village of Gracko was by no means an 
isolated incident. 
</P>
<P>
	At the head of the U.N.-run temporary government in Kosovo,  
Kouchner is powerless. The 35,000 soldiers deployed by NATO since 
its victory against Milosevic are not enough to contain the 
violence which, according to KFOR, has so far led to about 30 
deaths a week, mostly Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of congratulating themselves at grand symbolic reunions  
such as the one in Sarajevo, Allied leaders should develop means 
for their objectives. For example, they should send promised police 
forces to Kosovo without further delay. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 3  
</P>
<P>
	The Times, London, on staffing the British Army:  
</P>
<P>
	If George Robertson is confirmed as the next NATO  
secretary-general, one problem will outrank all others in the 
in-tray marked ``most urgent'' that will await his successor. That 
is the Army's shortage of trained fighting manpower, which is now 
so acute that there is a serious mismatch between Britain's 
strategic policy choices and the capacity to implement them. Kosovo 
offers a high-profile example of this worsening dilemma. 
</P>
<P>
	... The disturbing truth is that the Army simply does not have  
enough soldiers. Nearly 50 percent of the Army is now on 
operational duty, and even when this is reduced to 28 percent by 
next year, the government's target of 24-month gaps between tours 
will still be beyond reach. The Army is more overstretched than at 
any time since the late 1940s. And the longer this continues, the 
harder it will be to recruit and retain career soldiers. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 3  
</P>
<P>
	Financial Times, London, on U.S. government surplus:  
</P>
<P>
	The prospect of an era of fiscal surpluses in the U.S., after  
almost 20 years of deficits, has left the Republican party 
leadership quite dizzy. Big tax cuts based on the promise of budget 
surpluses amount to bad economics. It may also be bad politics. 
</P>
<P>
	... The House and Senate Republican tax-cut plans differ in  
detail. But the core idea is the same: setting in place tax cuts 
now to give $800 billion of this notional surplus back over the 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	... The Republicans are desperate for big tax cuts. They appear  
to have got the politics wrong. Core Republican voters may want tax 
cuts. But opinion polls show no great appetite among the wider 
electorate. A stalemate with the White House looms. The Democrats 
must relish the fight. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 2  
</P>
<P>
	Neue Zuercher Zeitung, Zurich, Switzerland, on prospects for  
peace in Colombia: 
</P>
<P>
	Andres Pastrana took over as Colombia's president last August  
with a promise to bring peace to the country. 
</P>
<P>
	His highly publicized meeting with Manuel Marulanda, the leader  
of the FARC rebels, showed the nation even before his election that 
he was ready to sit at the table with the rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	It was clear to Pastrana that he didn't face a walk in the park,  
rather a long and tiring march. 
</P>
<P>
	But Colombia, tired of almost 40 years of civil strife, took the  
glimmer of hope as a new dawn heralding peace, justice without 
corruption and true democracy. 
</P>
<P>
	The bright horizon soon darkened again, and the small clouds on  
the horizon have developed into storm clouds. ... 
</P>
<P>
	A peace process worthy of the name has yet to get under way.  
</P>
<P>
	The extensive and ambitious agenda both sides agreed on last May  
has remained no more than a piece of paper, gathering dust as both 
sides fail to agree on the conditions under which the actual 
negotiations should be conducted. ... 
  	   	
</P>
