<DOCNO> APW19990804.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 10:33:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta Mourns Shooting Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- An investor's killing spree that took 13 lives,  
including his own, taught Atlanta a lesson about the power of 
unity, Mayor Bill Campbell told mourners at a citywide memorial 
service today. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today we come together as one Atlanta -- beyond race, beyond  
borders, beyond religion,'' he told the crowd that nearly filled 
the 1,125-seat Peachtree Road United Methodist Church. 
</P>
<P>
	Religious leaders from different faiths remembered the victims  
and offered words of encouragement during the service, held just 
blocks from where Mark O. Barton killed nine of his victims at two 
brokerage offices. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ernest Hemingway wrote, 'Life breaks us all and for many we  
become strong at the broken places,''' said the Rev. Don Harp, 
pastor of the church. ``We have gathered as a community to express 
that we are at one of those broken places. We gather to reaffirm 
our understanding of life and, unfortunately, death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harp also read a letter from President Clinton extending his  
sympathy to the victims' families and the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Candles were lit at the front of the church for each of the nine  
shooting victims and for Barton's wife, Leigh Ann, and children, 
11-year-old Matthew and 8-year-old Mychelle, who were bludgeoned to 
death in the days before the shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Barton killed himself hours after his rampage when police  
cornered him about 30 miles northwest of Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Also honored with candles today were six members of an Atlanta  
family slain in their home July 12 and two Cobb County police 
officers killed in a standoff with a gunman July 23. 
</P>
<P>
	The last of Barton's victims were buried Tuesday. About 300  
mourners gathered at River of Life Family Church to eulogize Joe 
Dessert, 60, a former real estate broker who, like Barton, had 
taken up the risky investment method known as day trading. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 10:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Abu-Jamal Backers Point To Evidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Supporters of death row inmate Mumia  
Abu-Jamal say a letter written by a former prison volunteer proves 
he lied when he said Abu-Jamal admitted murdering a police officer. 
</P>
<P>
	On a live morning broadcast on WHAT radio Tuesday, Abu-Jamal's  
supporters handed Philip Bloch's attorney the letter they say Bloch 
wrote the inmate at least seven months after the alleged 
confession. 
</P>
<P>
	``So -- it is possible to get justice from a jury -- not always --  
but sometimes. So, when you get a new trial -- I think that there is 
a good chance of acquittal,'' Bloch wrote in the July 17, 1993, 
letter. 
</P>
<P>
	Abu-Jamal's attorney, Leonard Weinglass, said the letter  
directly contradicts Bloch's allegation that Abu-Jamal had 
confessed to him a few months earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	``This contradicts in writing from the author's own hand,''  
Weinglass said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bloch, however, says he is no liar. He explained that it took  
time for Abu-Jamal's comment to sink in. 
</P>
<P>
	``My feeling toward Mumia didn't change overnight. It changed  
very gradually,'' Bloch said in a telephone interview from his York 
home. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview published in the August issue of Vanity Fair,  
Bloch came forward to say Abu-Jamal, a onetime Black Panther and 
radio reporter whose case has attracted widespread attention, 
admitted he murdered officer Daniel Faulkner in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	Bloch, a 47-year-old substitute teacher and former Pennsylvania  
Prison Society volunteer, told the magazine he had asked Abu-Jamal 
nearly seven years ago if he had any regrets about killing 
Faulkner. Abu-Jamal said ``Yes,'' Bloch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bloch said he came forward out of sympathy for Faulkner's widow.  
</P>
<P>
	Weinglass, however, accused Bloch of coming forward because  
prosecutors needed new evidence to use in Abu-Jamal's appeal for a 
new trial. He said Abu-Jamal searched his personal letters and 
found Bloch's among them. The Philadelphia Tribune first reported 
Bloch's letter on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a recorded radio broadcast last week, Abu-Jamal called Bloch  
a liar. The recording was played on the air again Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why write to a guy and write about a new trial or acquittal if  
that guy confessed his guilt to you? The answer is simple. There 
was no confession. Period,'' Abu-Jamal said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he does not remember writing the letter, Bloch said he  
imagines that during that time he believed Abu-Jamal shouldn't have 
been on death row. If the shooting was a crime of passion, at the 
time, ``I still did not want to see him in jail for life or get 
executed for it,'' Bloch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Abu-Jamal's appeal is pending before the U.S. Supreme Court.  
Weinglass said he expects the high court to reject the case in 
October and remand it to the federal district court in Philadelphia 
for further consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	Abu-Jamal is seeking a new trial on the grounds that the  
prosecution withheld evidence, the judge was biased, black jurors 
were kept off the jury, witnesses were influenced and his original 
defense was inadequate. Death penalty opponents have since rallied 
around Abu-Jamal and made him a worldwide symbol of their cause. 
</P>
<P>
	Police officers, government officials and others have recently  
rallied around Maureen Faulkner, the widow of the slain officer, to 
accuse Abu-Jamal supporters of ignoring the facts of the case and 
spreading misinformation in their efforts on his behalf. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 21:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Exec: Auto Biz Needs New Talent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) -- The auto industry needs an image  
makeover if it's going to fill its worldwide shortage of highly 
skilled workers and executives, a top Ford Motor Co. executive 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our industry is on the brink of a potentially devastating  
shortage of talent -- on the plant floors, in our salaried ranks and 
at our dealerships,'' said Ford Vice Chairman Peter J. Pestillo. 
``At every level, in all job categories, we need more good people 
and we need them today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pestillo told an industry conference that among educators,  
students and the general public ``the perception is that auto 
manufacturing is a second-class industry, that it takes place in 
dark, dirty environments, that our workforce is uneducated and 
unskilled. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to do a better job of informing the outside world that  
our industry offers opportunities for forward-thinkers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pestillo said the problem is affecting suppliers and dealers as  
well. 
</P>
<P>
	He cited a recent University of Michigan study that found 85  
percent of automotive suppliers reported they had been affected by 
the tight labor market, with the most critical need in the skilled 
trades. 
</P>
<P>
	He criticized the nation's school system for failing to produce  
high school graduates with the entrepreneurial skills the industry 
needs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today's workplaces need people who are flexible and adaptable,  
who have an intuitive ability to solve problems and work in teams, 
who are independent, creative thinkers and can communicate 
effectively,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even when schools do produce that kind of graduate, top students  
often don't want to work in manufacturing, Pestillo said. They're 
more likely to be lured into higher-profile, high-tech industries. 
</P>
<P>
	``The auto industry has an image problem among so-called  
high-tech people,'' he said. ``They don't think of us as a 
technology industry, but we are. The auto industry is one of the 
greatest consumers and producers of new technology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He urged industry leaders to get more involved in all levels of  
the education system, by taking part in curriculum planning and 
helping to set policy on local school boards. 
</P>
<P>
	Pestillo said Ford was working with 76 high schools in the  
United States, Canada and South Africa to educate students about 
manufacturing careers. 
</P>
<P>
	Other car companies are taking similar steps. DaimlerChrysler AG  
is working with high schools and the community college system in 
Oakland County, near Detroit, to promote manufacturing careers. 
</P>
<P>
	The labor shortage is especially critical in the car-repair  
business. The U.S. Labor Department estimates there's a shortfall 
of about 60,000 trained mechanics nationwide. Only two people enter 
the field for every 10 that leave. 
</P>
<P>
	To remedy the situation, automakers have instituted programs to  
help attract and train mechanics. Ford, for example, contracted 
recently with a private training firm to provide an intensive, 
54-week training program to produce entry-level mechanics. 
Participating dealers share the cost of graduates' tuition to 
retain them. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercedes-Benz has a similar program.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 08:05:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Asia Awash in Deadly Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Rescuers searched under twisted walls  
and roofs today for survivors after a landslide triggered by days 
of monsoon rains smashed into a housing development, killing at 
least 11 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Up to 50 more people could still be trapped in the landslide,  
Defense Minister Orlando Mercado said. It was the deadliest single 
incident from four days of torrential rains that have killed a 
total 42 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a continuing downpour, police and emergency workers pulled  
injured victims, muddy and bloodied, out of the wreckage of 57 
collapsed or damaged houses in Antipolo City, east of Manila. 
</P>
<P>
	Other Asian countries also tried to assess the damage caused by  
days of torrential rains. At least 35 people were killed and 25,000 
people left homeless in South Korea, 24 died in Vietnam, and five 
were killed in Thailand. 
</P>
<P>
	In South Korea, the sun peeked out of the clouds for the first  
time in four days after the latest storm moved out of the country 
late Tuesday. Twenty-eight people were missing and 98,800 acres of 
rice paddies were washed away. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm caused rivers to overflow, breaking dikes and  
triggering deadly landslides, including one that killed 10 
vacationers. 
</P>
<P>
	About 100 graves in cemeteries north of Seoul were washed away,  
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	After skirting the length of South Korea's west coast, the  
tropical storm veered into the mainland of North Korea and raced 
through its capital Pyongyang, wreaking more havoc on the 
famine-stricken country. 
</P>
<P>
	In a report by its foreign news agency, KCNA, North Korea said  
late Tuesday that the rains and strong winds ``adversely affected 
agriculture and other fields.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The storm left ``no small loss of human lives,'' it said,  
without giving specifics. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea is in its fifth year of acute food shortages caused  
by massive floods and economic mismanagement. A U.S. congressional 
report said more than 2 million people may have died there. 
</P>
<P>
	In Thailand, about 1,000 people were homeless after five days of  
flash floods engulfed the low-lying, coastal province of 
Chanthaburi, 130 miles southeast of Bangkok. Authorities estimated 
that about 90,000 people were affected by floods. 
</P>
<P>
	In Cambodia, families took refuge on their rooftops when the  
town of Kampot, 85 miles south of Phnom Penh, was completely 
flooded. Two bridges connecting the town to higher ground 
collapsed. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Philippines, President Joseph Estrada declared a state of  
emergency Tuesday in metropolitan Manila and three nearby 
provinces. Tens of thousands of homes were flooded, and around $2 
million in damage was caused to farmland, the Department of 
Agriculture said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Antipolo, residents reported seeing cracks in their houses at  
about midday Tuesday, said Joven Gatlabayan, an assistant to the 
mayor. At mid-evening the terraced land collapsed, setting off a 
chain reaction as the top row of houses plunged into buildings 
below, survivors said. 
</P>
<P>
	A TV report said sandbags were used as the foundation for some  
houses, but officials at building's Japanese developer refused to 
comment. Some residents said they would sue the company. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 08:05:26 </DATE_TIME>
