<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Won't Block Dairy Pricing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Stepping into a bitter feud between the  
nation's dairy farmers, the Senate today blocked legislation aimed 
at letting New England continue fixing milk prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure also would have stopped he Agriculture Department  
from overhauling the way milk is priced in the rest of the country. 
New England senators, however, fell seven votes short of breaking a 
filibuster against the legislation, which they wanted to add to a 
USDA spending bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote was being closely watched by producers in New York,  
Pennsylvania and the South, who also are seeking to set milk prices 
in their states. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very clear. ... The Senate doesn't like cartels, whether  
it be for dairy or another commodity,'' said Sen. Herb Kohl, 
D-Wis., who led the filibuster. 
</P>
<P>
	Producers in the upper Midwest fear the regional compacts would  
encourage overproduction and drive down the prices they get. They 
also would be the biggest beneficiaries of USDA's new pricing 
policy, which is intended to soften regional pricing disparities. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers are voting this week on the new pricing structure. While  
it could hurt many producers outside the upper Midwest, the plan is 
expected to be approved nationwide because milk prices would 
otherwise be deregulated on Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the USDA proposal are hoping that Congress will  
force the department to adopt an alternative plan that is closer to 
the current pricing system. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the current system, guaranteed minimum prices for fluid  
milk are lowest in the upper Midwest and highest in the South and 
West, up to $3 per hundred pounds higher in some places, because 
the price is based on a farm's distance from Eau Claire, Wis. The 
Depression-era system was designed to spur production in areas 
where it had been scarce. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Congress set the system for elimination and ordered  
USDA to come up with a new plan. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
