<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vikings' First-Rounder Leaves Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANKATO, Minn. (AP) -- The Minnesota Vikings thought they were  
finally getting an explanation for the mysterious disappearance of 
their first-round draft pick who went AWOL after his first pro 
practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Pass rusher Dimitrius Underwood skipped out on the Vikings to  
attend to a ``family matter'' and was expected to return to 
training camp today, his agent said after finally tracking down the 
rookie. 
</P>
<P>
	But when morning practice started, Underwood wasn't there.  
</P>
<P>
	General manager Tim Connolly said this morning that nobody in  
the organization knew where Underwood was. 
</P>
<P>
	The first thing Underwood would have to do upon his return is  
meet with coach Dennis Green, who would decide whether to take him 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a Denny decision -- if he ever shows up,'' Connolly said.  
``Denny's irritated. I'm irritated. The whole staff is irritated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A message left with Underwood's agent, Craig Domann, wasn't  
immediately returned today. Domann's voicemail said he was out of 
the office today. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday night, Domann said that Underwood ``called to inform  
me that he was planning to be back in Mankato tonight (Tuesday). He 
apologized for the way he took off without talking to anybody or 
asking for permission from the team or even letting me know or 
anyone else know that he was doing what he was doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He had to deal with a family matter that had gotten to crisis  
proportions, and he had to take care of it,'' Domann said. ``He is 
now focusing his energies back on football. I informed him that he 
would need to be talking to coach (Dennis) Green. He said he was 
looking forward to doing that either late tonight or first thing 
tomorrow morning depending on what time he got in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Domann declined to go into specifics about the player's  
explanation or the whereabouts of Underwood, the father of 
15-month-old twins. 
</P>
<P>
	Green wouldn't discuss Underwood's status after learning he had  
been located more than 24 hours after his disappearance. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Tuesday, Green was clearly annoyed by the matter,  
however. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, we're disappointed the guy would not want to play  
football. That's really what it comes down to,'' Green said 
following the morning practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood inexplicably disappeared from training camp Monday,  
worrying the team, his agent and his family, all concerned about 
his well being. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's been my only concern the whole time,'' assistant coach  
Andre Patterson said Tuesday before Underwood was tracked down. 
``Football's just a game. I couldn't sleep because of this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Domann didn't hear from his client until Tuesday evening.  
Neither did Underwood's mother and brother in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, a 6-foot-6, 276-pound defensive end from Michigan  
State, was the 29th selection in the NFL draft. He signed a 
five-year contract Sunday for more than $5 million, including a 
partially deferred signing bonus of $1,750,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings went to federal court in Minneapolis on Tuesday  
afternoon to keep Underwood from getting a $543,561.80 portion of 
his signing bonus it wired to his Milwaukee bank on Monday. 
Underwood's bank agreed to freeze the account for 48 hours. The 
lawsuit said Underwood breached his contract with the Vikings by 
failing to attend mandatory players' meetings and practices and for 
leaving training camp without permission. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
