<DOCNO> APW19990804.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 00:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Peach Prices May Rise / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Georgia peach farmers say the Environmental  
Protection Agency has taken away one of their most effective 
weapons against pests by banning a chemical used on 81 percent of 
the state's peach crop. 
</P>
<P>
	The methyl parathion ban came Monday, three years after the 1996  
Food Quality Protection Act required the EPA to reassess safety 
levels for hundreds of commonly used pesticides. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are taking away the most effective and safest and best  
pesticide that we've had,'' Robert Dickey, a Crawford County peach 
farmer, said Tuesday. ``We're going to have to substitute some 
others that are more expensive and less effective. It doesn't make 
much sense to us growers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dickey said the alternative pesticides could cost three times  
more. The pesticide ban will hit Southern growers more than their 
counterparts in California because the pest that attacks South 
Carolina and Georgia peaches is not as great a problem out West, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, he said, fruit imported from other countries may  
have been treated with the pesticide. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's probably costing us $40 or $50 an acre to spray now,'' he  
said. ``If I've got 1,000 acres of peaches, you see where my profit 
goes. The EPA just took it. It's a real blow to us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dickey said he will try not to pass the extra cost on to  
consumers in order to compete with other growers. 
</P>
<P>
	However, state Agriculture Commissioner Tommy Irvin said  
consumers may have to pay more for Georgia peaches because of the 
ban. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it will be a huge cost, but it will have some  
impact on the production costs,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin said he thinks consumers will be willing to spend a little  
more for Georgia peaches because ``our peaches are so much better 
in quality and taste that the price doesn't become a big factor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peach farmer Al Pearson said the agricultural community cannot  
absorb every regulatory action of the government and still maintain 
a profit level that will allow farmers to stay in business. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the American consumer should expect food prices to go  
up when the tools that have been efficient have been removed,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Azinphosmethyl, an insecticide used on 11 percent of the apples  
grown in Georgia, has also been banned. 
</P>
<P>
	The pesticides have been controversial because of concern that  
the residue levels the government deems acceptable pose risks to 
infants and children. Allowable residue levels for many pesticides 
were set decades ago, when the potential health impacts on infants 
and children were not taken into account. 
</P>
<P>
	The cessation date for using methyl parathion hasn't been  
issued. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin said peaches from this year's crop are safe to eat even  
though they have been sprayed with the pesticide. There is no 
evidence that the pesticide has ever caused harm, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``On one hand you hear them say that it's not an immediate  
danger. It's nothing to panic about,'' Pearson said. ``It makes me 
wonder if it's not a little overreaction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Ausfeld of Atlanta bought a half-dozen large peaches  
at the Harris Teeter supermarket in Dunwoody on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not immediately concerned, because they really haven't  
told us what the stuff can do to us. I have to know more about it 
before I get worried,'' she said. ``Besides, it's July and I have 
to have my peaches.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 07:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Factory Orders Report Due Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Commerce Department reports factory orders  
for July at 10 a.m. EDT today. 
</P>
<P>
	Orders to U.S. factories for big-ticket manufactured goods rose  
0.3 percent in June, boosted by gains in autos and electronic 
equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase followed a 0.8 percent gain in May, and a drop of  
2.4 percent in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. economy is poised to keep growing at least through the  
first half of 2000, leaving it on track for achieving the longest 
expansion ever, according to a key gauge of future activity 
released yesterday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board said today that its Index of Leading  
Economic Indicators, which is designed to help spot turning points 
in the economy, rose 0.3 in June to 107.7. That matched the May 
increase and brought gains in the indicator to eight out of the 
past nine months. The last decline, in April, was 0.1 
</P>
<P>
	The longest economic expansion in U.S. history lasted for 106  
months, from February 1962 until December 1969. The current 
expansion, which began in March 1991, would match the record if it 
continues through January 2000 and pass it if it lasts until 
February. 
</P>
<P>
	``The expansion is firmly on track,'' said Michael Boldin,  
director of business cycle research at the Conference Board. But 
because of concerns that the Federal Reserve may raise interest 
rates again to fight inflation ``some volatility can be expected in 
the second half of 1999,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets had little reaction to the report by the  
business-financed research group based in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists said that, if anything, it confirmed that the economy  
is growing at a slow and steady pace of about 2.7 percent annually, 
which should not meaningfully accelerate inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's figures came as investors were trying to predict  
whether the Fed would raise short-term interest rates for a second 
time this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank increased rates by a quarter point on June 30  
in a pre-emptive strike against inflation. Its chairman, Alan 
Greenspan, has warned it is prepared to act quickly again on any 
signs of rekindled inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists said that Tuesday's report did not signal that  
inflation is in danger of getting out of hand. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank ``may have to come in and do a small adjustment  
in rates,'' said Anthony Chan, chief economist at Banc One 
Investment Advisors in Columbus, Ohio. ``But this report is not 
telling the Fed that there's any kind of panic here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seven of the 10 indicators that make up the leading index rose  
in June. The most significant increases came in manufacturers' new 
orders of consumer goods and materials, in money supply, and in the 
difference between long-term and short-term interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	However, in a sign that the labor market may not be heating up  
enough to push up wages -- a key component of the inflation picture 
-- the average number of hours worked per week by production workers 
-- was unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board's index of current economic activity rose  
by 0.4 to 124.6 in June. But its lagging index decreased by 0.4 to 
108. The indexes are calculated from a base of 100, set in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``Taken together, the three composite indexes and their  
components show a very health economy,'' the Conference Board 
report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Thayer, chief economist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St.  
Louis, noted that other recent reports show that economic growth is 
slowing. Last week, the Commerce Department reported that economic 
growth has slowed to an annual rate of 2.3 percent in the second 
quarter from 4.3 percent in the first three months of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	A report Monday from an organization of industrial executives  
suggested manufacturing growth has slowed. And while Americans' 
wages and benefits surged in the second quarter by the largest 
amount since 1991, Thayer noted that help-wanted advertising is at 
its lowest level in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Thayer said, higher long-term interest rates should  
brake the economy even further. Thirty-year mortgages topped 8 
percent this week for the first time in more than two years. That 
should further slow the housing market, which is already reporting 
a sharp drop in new construction and refinancings. 
</P>
<P>
	Chan said the next important clue to the pace of growth in the  
economy will be provided Friday with a report on the July 
unemployment rate. Until then, he said, ``I think the economy is 
steady as she goes.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
