<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 13:50:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PGA Tour Charities Hit $500 Million  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	What began 61 years ago with a $10,000 contribution hit a major  
milestone Wednesday as charitable donations from tournaments run by 
the PGA Tour hit $500 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the money, it's what it does for people,''  
commissioner Tim Finchem said. ``It cements the relationships 
between our tournaments, the people who run them, the players who 
compete in them and the communities we visit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The growth of charitable contributions has nearly doubled since  
Finchem took over as commissioner in 1994. Last year alone, PGA 
Tour events raised about $39.7 million for charities. 
</P>
<P>
	The $500 million milestone represents charitable donations from  
all three of its tours. The Senior Tour has contributed nearly $70 
million since 1989, while the Nike Tour has added nearly $15 
million over the past nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	Not included is what players contribute on their own.  
</P>
<P>
	The announcement comes a day after Billy Andrade and Brad Faxon  
held the CVS Charity Classic in Rhode Island. Over the past nine 
years, they have raised more than $1.65 million for children's and 
women's charities in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Norman's Shark Shootout raised $1 million in November for  
children's cancer research, among other things. Fred Couples and 
Peter Jacobsen have charity tournaments in the Northwest. Tiger 
Woods will have his first such event, raising money for his 
foundation, at the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of them see what golf can do for charity and have their  
own charity tournaments,'' Finchem said. ``It has become a part of 
the fabric of the PGA Tour.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 80 percent of the PGA Tour events are dedicated to  
charity, meaning they contribute 100 percent of their net proceeds 
-- from revenue such as ticket sales and corporate hospitality tents 
-- to charity. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of these designate a single charity, such as the St. Jude  
Children's Research Hospital (Memphis) and the Egleston Hospital 
for Children (BellSouth Classic in Atlanta). Others, such as The 
Players Championship, divide their contributions among several 
groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The Byron Nelson Classic last year donated $4.3 million from its  
net proceeds -- top among PGA Tour events -- to the Salesmanship Club 
of Dallas. Its beneficiary is the Youth and Family Centers, which 
serves at-risk youth in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it reflects the necessary commitment we have,''  
Finchem said. ``It's clear the relationship with charitable 
contributions has grown on the PGA Tour to the point that we're 
only going to add tournaments that are committed to charity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tournaments such as the Bay Hill Invitational, started by Arnold  
Palmer, and Jack Nicklaus' Memorial Tournament are not required to 
donate their entire proceeds to charity but ``still make 
substantial contributions,'' Finchem said. 
</P>
<P>
	The first contribution was $10,000 by the Palm Beach  
Invitational in 1938, and the total contribution reached $1 million 
in 1950. 
</P>
<P>
	The next stop: $1 billion.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
