<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 17:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Chime In on Pan Am Drug Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Whether it's muscle-building steroids or a  
street drug like cocaine, athletes who use banned substances should 
face the same sanctions, anti-drug experts said Wednesday in the 
wake of sport's latest scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said the case of Javier Sotomayor, the Cuban  
high-jump star who tested positive for cocaine at the Pan American 
Games, contained elements similar to that of Ben Johnson, the 
Canadian sprinter who was thrown out of the 1988 Olympics for 
steroid use. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Ben Johnson thing clearly underscored the magnitude of the  
steroid problem and the use of performance enhancers,'' said Dr. 
Gary Wadler, a Long Island, N.Y., researcher who had studied and 
written about doping in sports. ``The Sotomayor situation shows 
again that athletes are susceptible to the foibles of the world, 
and cocaine poses a serious problem to our society.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, the White House drug office said all doping cases  
should be viewed in the context of using illicit substances in an 
area that demands fair play and high standards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cocaine is a devastating drug that destroys lives and the  
people who use it,'' said Bob Weiner, a spokesman for Gen. Barry 
McCaffrey, the federal drug policy director. 
</P>
<P>
	While refusing to discuss the Sotomayor case specifically,  
Weiner said any test that finds an athlete using banned substances 
for whatever reason ``emphasizes the need for concerted action 
against drugs in sports.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that McCaffrey has pressed the International Olympic  
Committee for strong, consistent anti-doping measures, such as 
year-round drug testing and an independent agency to police doping 
worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	A two-time Olympic gold medalist and the only person to high  
jump 8 feet, Sotomayor was the biggest name athlete to flunk a drug 
test since Johnson tested positive for the steroid Stanozolol at 
the 1988 Summer Games in Seoul. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was stripped of his gold medal in the 100 meters and his  
world-record time of 9.79 seconds was erased from the books. 
</P>
<P>
	Wadler said there was an important difference between the cases  
of Sotomayor and Johnson. While the sprinter took steroids solely 
to boost performance, ``there is little evidence to suggest that 
cocaine has a performance-enhancing effect,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, Wadler said, organizations draw up lists of banned  
drugs for reasons other than what the substance can do to 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is the performance-enhancing aspect, the role-model  
aspect and the health aspect,'' he said. ``An organization must 
known what it wants to do with its list before placing a substance 
on that list.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 02:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Training Camp Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANKATO, Minn. (AP) -- The Minnesota Vikings are finally getting  
some answers to the mysterious disappearance of their first-round 
draft pick who went AWOL after his first NFL practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Pass rusher Dimitrius Underwood skipped out on the Vikings to  
attend to a ``family matter'' and planned to return to training 
camp today, his agent said after finally tracking down the rookie, 
whose unexcused absence irritated the coaching staff and caused 
many to worry about his safety. 
</P>
<P>
	``He called to inform me that he was planning to be back in  
Mankato tonight. He apologized for the way he took off without 
talking to anybody or asking for permission from the team or even 
letting me know or anyone else know that he was doing what he was 
doing,'' agent Craig Domann said Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Dennis Green wouldn't discuss Underwood's status after  
learning that the rookie was located more than 24 hours after his 
mysterious disappearance. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Tuesday, Green was clearly annoyed by the matter.  
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, we're disappointed the guy would not want to play  
football. That's really what it comes down to,'' Green said 
following Tuesday morning's practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Domann declined to go into specifics about the family matter or  
the whereabouts of Underwood, the father of 15-month-old twins. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had to deal with a family matter that had gotten to crisis  
proportions, and he had to take care of it,'' Domann said. ``He is 
now focusing his energies back on football. I informed him that he 
would need to be talking to coach Green. He said he was looking 
forward to doing that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood inexplicably disappeared from training camp Monday,  
worrying the team, his agent and his family, all concerned about 
his well-being. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's been my only concern the whole time,'' assistant coach  
Andre Patterson said Tuesday before Underwood was tracked down. 
``Football's just a game. I couldn't sleep because of this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Domann didn't hear from his client until Tuesday evening.  
Neither did Underwood's mother and brother in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, a 6-foot-6, 276-pound defensive end from Michigan  
State, was the 29th selection in the NFL draft. He signed a 
five-year contract Sunday for more than $5 million, including a 
partially deferred signing bonus of $1,750,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings went to federal court in Minneapolis on Tuesday to  
keep Underwood from getting a $543,561.80 portion of his signing 
bonus it wired to his Milwaukee bank on Monday. Underwood's bank 
agreed to freeze the account for 48 hours. The lawsuit said 
Underwood breached his contract with the Vikings by failing to 
attend mandatory players meetings and practices and for leaving 
training camp without permission. 
</P>
<P>
	Domann dropped off his client at the team's dorm Sunday  
afternoon, and Underwood, dressed in military fatigues, proclaimed: 
``It feels good to be in Minnesota, a long anticipation. I got the 
war fatigues, got the Army fatigues, got to go to war.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He participated in Monday morning's workout, ate lunch with his  
teammates, then between noon and the players meeting at 3 p.m., he 
vanished, leaving most of his clothes and personal items, including 
a Bible, in his room. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings issued a statement saying Underwood, who missed his  
senior season at Michigan State because of an ankle injury, left 
camp without permission and without telling anybody where he was 
going or why. 
</P>
<P>
	Defensive coordinator Foge Fazio said nothing occurred during  
the morning practice that would have indicated there was a problem. 
And his roommate, rookie defensive end Talance Sawyer, said 
Underwood never said anything about leaving camp, although he said 
Underwood received a phone call shortly before his disappearance. 
</P>
<P>
	Green refused to say what, if any, disciplinary action Underwood  
faced for his unexcused absence from three workouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood is expected to back up Stalin Colinet at left end.  
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
                              *Bears    	
</P>
<P>
	Cade McNown took part in his first practice with the Chicago  
Bears after signing his contract 11 days into camp. 
</P>
<P>
	McNown, the 12th pick overall, ended his holdout Monday with a  
contract that could pay him up to $22 million over five years. The 
initial deal is for seven years and $15 million, but the last two 
years are voidable and he can make an additional $7 million in 
performance-based incentives. 
</P>
<P>
	He arrived late Monday after a solo drive from Chicago that  
included several wrong turns and a slight mishap when he discovered 
he didn't have any 75 cents change for a toll booth. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Cowboys    	
</P>
<P>
	Cornerback Deion Sanders will not return to the team until  
September, and even that may be a bit optimistic, team owner Jerry 
Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders is in training camp, but not practicing with Dallas as  
he rehabilitates his left big toe. He underwent surgery to fix an 
extreme case of turf toe in April. 
</P>
<P>
	There had been no estimate of when the All-Pro cornerback might  
suit up until Tuesday, when Jones said: ``I see him really trying 
to push himself sometime in September.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Jones also noted that if Sanders sits for all of  
September, he would miss only two games because Dallas has an early 
bye week. The Cowboys' third game is Oct. 3 against division rival 
Arizona in Texas Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
                            *Buccaneers    	
</P>
<P>
	First-round draft pick Anthony McFarland agreed to terms with  
Tampa Bay, ending a three-day training camp holdout. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Rich McKay said the 6-foot, 300-pound defensive  
tackle from LSU would arrive to sign the deal Tuesday night and 
practice today. 
</P>
<P>
	McFarland was the first defensive lineman selected in the draft  
and 15th pick overall. His contract is believed to be worth more 
than $6 million for five years, including a $4 million signing 
bonus. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Giants    	
</P>
<P>
	Jason Sehorn's attempt to return to the New York Giants' lineup  
is going to be delayed about another 10 days because of a torn 
hamstring in his left leg. 
</P>
<P>
	The cornerback, who missed all of last season with a serious  
knee injury, had the tear detected Monday night after undergoing an 
MRI in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	It is almost certain that Sehorn will miss the Giants preseason  
opener at Minnesota on Aug. 13. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the NFL's top cover cornerbacks, Sehorn injured the  
hamstring working out about three weeks before training camp 
opened. He didn't think it was serious then, but it cramped about a 
week before camp opened. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Falcons    	
</P>
<P>
	Jamal Anderson wasn't on hand for Atlanta's two workouts and is  
now facing at least $30,000 in fines -- the maximum $5,000 per day -- 
even if he reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pro Bowl running back, set to make $2.6 million in the final  
year of his deal, is seeking a five-year contract with an $8 
million signing bonus. The Falcons have offered a $7 million bonus 
and at least $1 million less in guaranteed money over the life of 
the contract. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Titans    	
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee quarterback Steve McNair left Tuesday morning's  
practice with back spasms. 
</P>
<P>
	He was treated and is not expected to miss any workouts. The  
afternoon session was limited to special teams, so McNair, who has 
started the last 33 regular-season games, was not scheduled to 
participate. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Dolphins    	
</P>
<P>
	Tyrone Wheatley, a bust for the New York Giants, lasted less  
than a week into training camp with Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheatley was unimpressive in the Dolphins' first scrimmage  
Sunday. He carried seven times for 18 yards. Wheatley, 27, was the 
Giants' first-round draft choice in 1995. But he started just eight 
games in four seasons and carried only 14 times for 52 yards last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dolphins acquired Wheatley from New York in February for a  
seventh-round draft choice. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Patriots    	
</P>
<P>
	New England coach Pete Carroll said the left knee injury  
suffered by tight end Ben Coates in practice Monday was nowhere 
near as serious as reported. Carroll termed the injury ``a very 
mild strain'' and said the veteran Pro Bowler's status would be 
evaluated on a daily basis. 
</P>
<P>
	Coates is unlikely to participate in Saturday's intrasquad  
scrimmage at Foxboro Stadium. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
