<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 15:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colt's Tough Draw for Hambletonian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Don't blame Bob Stewart for  
wondering if he'll ever catch a break in the Hambletonian. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, who trains Angus Hall, thought everything was going his  
way after his colt won an elimination last week by 4 1/2 lengths in a 
career-best 1:54 3-5. 
</P>
<P>
	Three days later, Angus Hall had the misfortune to draw the No.  
9 post position for Saturday's $1 million final for trotting's 
biggest race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought we'd overcome everything,'' Stewart said. ``Then  
came the draw. Still, I really believe he'll be good Saturday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Angus Hall has a first, a second and two thirds in four starts  
this year. Stewart didn't plan it that way. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were going to take him to Canada but he got sick,'' Stewart  
said. ``It took him three weeks to get well and another three weeks 
before he was ready to run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His full brother, 1998 Hambletonian entrant Conway Hall, the  
1997 2-year-old trotting colt of the year, had similar problems 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Conway Hall developed a bone cyst on his stifle and lost 45 days  
of training. He drew the ninth post for the Hambletonian, finishing 
fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was worse last year,'' Stewart said. ``This horse is  
bigger, stronger and has more tactical speed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So what is the strategy for Saturday?  
</P>
<P>
	``I believe you hire the best driver you can get,'' said  
Stewart, who will have five-time Hambletonian winner John Campbell 
in the bike. ``John knows the horses and he knows the other 
drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we drew the 10 hole for the Beacon Course we decided not  
to race him too hard with the Hambo in mind,'' Stewart said. ``But 
on Saturday I'll leave it up to John. He won the Meadowlands Pace 
from the 10-hole'' this year with The Panderosa. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell, the youngest driver ever to be elected to the Harness  
Racing Hall of Fame and the sports' career earnings leader, was 
tight-lipped about his plan for Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish we had drawn better,'' Campbell said. ``But it's only a  
starting point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The horse to beat in this year's Hambletonian is Self Possessed.  
Because of common ownership and trainers, the colt will be part of 
a heavily favored three-horse entry that includes Angus Hall and 
Raffaello Ambrosio. 
</P>
<P>
	Self Possessed tied the Meadowlands track record for 3-year-old  
trotting colts of 1:52 2-5. The Mike Lachance-driven colt drew the 
No. 4 post on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The team of Lachance and trainer Ron Gurfein will be shooting  
for a third Hambletonian victory in five years, after winning with 
Victory Dream in 1994 and Continentalvictory in 1996. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 22:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HIV Levels Influence Transmission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The higher the level of HIV in a pregnant woman's blood, the  
more likely she was to transmit the virus to her baby, researchers 
reported today in the New England Journal of Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers also found that pregnant women with the highest  
levels of HIV were one-third less likely to transmit the virus if 
they were treated with the anti-retroviral drug AZT than those who 
were not. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers concluded that aggressive anti-retroviral  
therapy is probably the best way to lower the risk that babies will 
be born with AIDS. However, they warned that the benefits must be 
weighed against the possible long-term effects of the drug, which 
are unknown. 
</P>
<P>
	One study, led by Dr. Lynne Mofenson of the National Institutes  
of Health, looked at women who were treated with AZT while pregnant 
and whose babies also were treated with the drug for several weeks 
after birth. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the 84 mothers in the study who had undetectable levels of  
the HIV at 20 to 30 weeks of pregnancy, none of the babies tested 
positive for HIV. 
</P>
<P>
	The second study, led by Dr. Patricia Garcia of Northwestern  
University, looked at 552 pregnant women from 1990 to 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	It found that among women with the highest levels of HIV,  
representing the most advanced cases of AIDS, 20 percent of those 
who had been treated with AZT transmitted the virus to their babies 
compared to a 63 percent transmission rate among those not treated 
with AZT. 
</P>
<P>
	In countries that cannot afford AZT treatment, about one-fourth  
of all babies born to HIV-positive mothers get the virus. Since AZT 
therapy became standard in the United States, that rate has dropped 
to 9 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 10:20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Entertainment highlights during the week of Aug. 8-14:  
</P>
<P>
	55 years ago: ``Hail the Conquering Hero'' starred Eddie  
Bracken, Ella Raines and William Demarest. The film was directed by 
Preston Sturges. 
</P>
<P>
	35 years ago: The Beatles starred in ``A Hard Day's Night.'' The  
soundtrack included ``Can't Buy Me Love'' and ``I Should Have Known 
Better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	30 years ago: Jethro Tull's ``Stand Up'' topped the British  
album chart. 
</P>
<P>
	25 years ago: Art Carney and Ellen Burstyn starred in ``Harry  
and Tonto.'' Carney won an Oscar for his performance. 
</P>
<P>
	And Roberta Flack hit the top of the charts with ``Feel Like  
Makin' Love.'' 
</P>
<P>
	10 years ago: The Who held its 25th anniversary concert at the  
University of Colorado in Boulder. The crowd cheered to the band's 
reprisals of the overture to ``Tommy'' and ``My Generation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Abyss'' starred Ed Harris and Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio.  
The film was directed by James Cameron. 
</P>
<P>
	And Ziggy Marley and The Melodymakers began a world tour. Their  
starting point was Culver City, Calif., where they showed reporters 
a new video for ``Look Who's Dancing,'' from the album ``One Bright 
Day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago: Singer Janet Jackson tied Aretha Franklin for  
the most gold single records by a female artist. Jackson's 14th 
gold single was ``Any Time, Any Place,'' from the album ``janet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Woodstock '94 was held in Saugerties, N.Y. About 350,000  
attended. The show included performances by Green Day, Nine Inch 
Nails and Crosby, Stills and Nash. 
</P>
<P>
	One year ago: Welsh-born actor Anthony Hopkins pledged about  
$1.6 million to help preserve 4,000 acres of Mount Snowdon, the 
highest peak in Wales. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS announced it was canceling ``Public Eye,'' the newsmagazine  
featuring Bryant Gumbel. ``Public Eye'' first aired the previous 
September, after CBS signed Gumbel, former host of NBC's ``Today'' 
show, to a five-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	And Jon Stewart was named host of Comedy Central's ``The Daily  
Show.'' Craig Kilborn was leaving the show to take over for Tom 
Snyder at CBS' ``Late Show.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken 10 years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``After having taken time out for reorganization, Public Enemy  
is back in action. The show must go on. Brace yourselves for 
1990.'' -- Chuck D., leader of the rap group Public Enemy. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken five years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``Doing a talk show is the easiest gig in show business. It is  
so easy, it does not even require talent. Having talent is just an 
extra, like having a nice wife or a big red car.'' -- Comedian Steve 
Allen, the original host of the ``Tonight'' show. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken one year ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``It took me a long time to get over the `you're ugly and stupid  
thing.' From age 13 to 18, it was consistent in my life, from my 
peers. You want desperately to fit in, and I tried hard, but I 
didn't.'' -- Singer Sarah McLachlan. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
