<DOCNO> APW19990804.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 08:07:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Troops Seal Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEBRON, West Bank (AP) -- Israeli troops sealed the troubled and  
divided city of Hebron today, a day after two Jewish settlers were 
wounded in an ambush blamed on Palestinian militants. 
</P>
<P>
	The shooting was the first attack on Israelis since moderate  
Prime Minister Ehud Barak took office last month and came at a time 
of tension between Israel and the Palestinian Authority over 
implementation of the Wye River peace accord. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak has hinted he would break off negotiations with the  
Palestinians over terror attacks and said after Tuesday's shooting 
that he would wage an uncompromising war against terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the army's response was in line with previous  
practices. Troops imposed a curfew on the Israeli-controlled 
downtown area of Hebron and set up roadblocks around the city, 
barring Palestinians from leaving and entering. 
</P>
<P>
	Streets were deserted today in the Israeli sector, which is home  
to 30,000 Palestinians and 450 Jewish settlers. The Palestinians 
were confined to their homes while the settlers were allowed to 
move freely. Palestinian residents watched from the windows as 
Israeli troops searched homes and questioned people. 
</P>
<P>
	A dozen teen-agers threw stones at Israeli troops.  
</P>
<P>
	In Tuesday's attack, gunmen opened fire on two settlers driving  
through downtown Hebron en route to their homes in the tiny Jewish 
enclave of Tel Romeida in the heart of a Palestinian neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the victims, Ephraim Rosenstein, who lost two fingers in  
the attack, demanded that Barak respond harshly. ``I would expect 
that Barak, as a proven security hawk, would do something ... more 
than just words,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak demanded that the Palestinian Authority track down the  
gunmen who apparently fled into the Palestinian-controlled part of 
the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Major Gen. Yitzhak Eitan, the Israeli army official in charge of  
the West Bank, complained that the Palestinian Authority was not 
doing enough to catch the attackers. A meeting between Israeli and 
Palestinian security officials set for today was canceled because 
of the shooting, Israel's army radio said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinians, meanwhile, renewed their criticism of Barak,  
saying he was trying to get out of a full implementation of the Wye 
accord under which Israel is to withdraw from 13.1 percent of the 
West Bank in three stages. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak's hard-line predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu, carried out  
the first phase, but then suspended the accord, saying the 
Palestinians did not do enough to fight terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak hopes to skip over the last pullback because he fears it  
will isolate several Jewish settlements and expose them to attack 
by Palestinian militants. However, Barak has also said he would 
carry out Wye in full if the Palestinians rejected his idea. 
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has repeatedly turned down Barak's 
proposal, insisting on a full implementation of the accord. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 16:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bourbon Belle Wins Saratoga Feature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARATOGA, N.Y. (AP) -- Bourbon Belle made it look easy in taking  
Saratoga's Wednesday feature, the eighth running of the $112,600 
Grade III Honorable Miss Handicap. 
</P>
<P>
	Carrying 116 pounds and her regular rider, Pat Johnson, the  
filly who has raced at eight different tracks in her last 12 starts 
led wire to wire in her first appearance at the Spa to post a 
3 1/2-length victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold Princess was second of 10. It was another head to License  
Fee, who raced coupled in the wagering with Ruby Rubles. 
</P>
<P>
	The win was the third in seven starts this year for the  
4-year-old by Storm Boot from the Whitesburg mare Timeless Girl. 
Bourbon Belle covered six furlongs in 1:09.2 on the fast track to 
earn $67,560 and return $11, $6.50 and $5. Gold Princess paid $7.30 
and $5.10, and the License Fee-Ruby Rubles entry was $4.80. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0289 </DOCNO>
