<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 16:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Liberians in US Lose Special Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Nearly 10 years ago, Torli Krua escaped from a  
group of machete-wielding warlords who hunted him down in the 
middle of the night because he was from a rival tribe. 
</P>
<P>
	But soon he may be forced to confront the assailants again.  
</P>
<P>
	After war erupted in the West African nation of Liberia in 1989,  
Liberians were granted temporary permission to live and work in the 
United States until their homeland settled down. 
</P>
<P>
	The special immigration status was extended year after year, and  
many Liberians were able to begin new lives here. But the State 
Department now says Liberia is stable and has recommended that the 
1,000 to 1,500 Liberians granted the special status return home by 
Sept. 28. 
</P>
<P>
	Krua and others are pleading for permission to remain, saying  
Liberia is still too dangerous. 
</P>
<P>
	``The (Liberian) government has not shown it will tolerate  
dissent,'' said Krua, 48, who has been living in Boston. ``Here, I 
go to bed freely. I speak freely. If I go back, I don't know if I 
will be able to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department and the State Department say that while  
Liberia continues to struggle from the effects of the civil war, 
Liberians here should be safe. 
</P>
<P>
	The Temporary Protected Status allows foreigners to stay in the  
United States if their home countries suffer political violence or 
natural disasters. Liberians whose temporary protected status 
expires have the right to apply for political asylum. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberia's civil war ravaged the country between 1989 and 1996,  
leaving an estimated 200,000 people dead. While the country is 
largely at peace, much of it is still without electricity, passable 
roads, and supplies remain short. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberia's political system is riddled by tribal division. A  
person's tribe often makes or breaks their position in society. 
</P>
<P>
	Some critics of Liberia's president, Charles Taylor, say the  
former warlord has rewarded supporters and punishes those who are 
not obedient. 
</P>
<P>
	``People who had homes, property and skills fled because they  
had to,'' said Rev. Henry James, a Liberian who lives permanently 
in Stoughton. ``If some of these Liberians go back, they will be 
hunted because of who they are and their tribal backgrounds.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 10:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Age Doesn't Deter Sex Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sex isn't just for the young. It's also for  
the young at heart, according to a survey that finds many older 
Americans continue to have active sex lives and find their partners 
attractive as they age. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey was conducted by the AARP, the nation's largest  
organization of older adults, for the September-October issue of 
its ``Modern Maturity'' magazine, devoted to the topic: ``Great 
sex: What's age got to do with it?'' The racy issue is part of 
AARP's campaign to attract aging baby boomers -- who led the 1960s 
sexual revolution -- as members. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest myth out there of all is the myth that old people  
don't have sex or aren't interested in sex -- that basically after a 
certain age you're supposed to go to Florida, play golf and wait 
for Ed McMahon to knock on the door and not to think or even do 
sex,'' said the magazine's editor, Hugh Delehanty. ``We all know 
this is patently absurd and we wanted to look and see what the 
truth was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The survey by the American Association of Retired Persons found  
that more than six in 10 men between the ages of 45 and 59 and a 
similar percentage of women in middle age report having sex at 
least once a week. One in four people over age 75 reported similar 
frequency. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline in sexual activity does not seem to be caused by a  
lack of physical attraction between couples as they age, the survey 
found. 
</P>
<P>
	About 59 percent of men between the ages of 45 and 74 say the  
phrase ``physically attractive'' strongly applies to their partner, 
while 62 percent of those over age 75 agree. About half of women in 
both middle and old age said physical attraction to their partner 
was strong. 
</P>
<P>
	What does seem to make the difference is lack of partners, who  
may be lost to death or divorce. While eight in 10 people aged 45 
to 59 have sexual partners, only 58 percent of men and 21 percent 
of women aged 75 and older do. 
</P>
<P>
	However, changing morals may make this less of a constraint for  
the baby boomers than it is for their parents. While 66 percent of 
women age 75 and older think that people should not have sexual 
relationships if they are not married, only 36 percent of women 
aged 45 to 59 do. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are left to speculate how sexual behaviors and attitudes of  
those mid-life adults that we queried, who came of age during the 
sexual and gender revolutions of the 1960s, how their attitudes and 
behaviors will change as they age,'' said AARP's director of 
research, Constance Swank. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining health is the other thing holding older people back in  
the bedroom. More than half of men and a third of women said better 
health for themselves or their partners would improve their sex 
lives. Other changes that people said would help included less 
stress and more free time. 
</P>
<P>
	One in four men acknowledged being completely or moderately  
impotent, although despite the publicity of new treatments such as 
the drug Viagra, only 41 percent of them said they had sought 
medical help. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey of 1,384 adults age 45 and older was conducted by  
mail during March. The margin of error is plus or minus 2.6 
percentage points. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 16:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bills' Thomas Might Start Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FREDONIA, N.Y. (AP) -- Thurman Thomas reluctantly accepted his  
role as a backup behind Antowain Smith last season. A groin injury 
could sideline Smith and force Thomas -- who has 11,786 career yards 
-- back into the spotlight. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas would take the heat for a while, the 12-year veteran said  
Wednesday. But he doesn't want to make it a permanent thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it does come to me being a full-time starter, and having to  
play 60 to 70 plays a game, I'm willing to do that early in the 
season,'' Thomas said. 
</P>
<P>
	For 10 years, Thomas, who occupies a prominent place in the  
hearts of Buffalo fans and 12 pages in the Bills' media guide, took 
a back seat to nobody. Ninth in rushing in NFL history, Thomas 
trails only Emmitt Smith among active backs now that Thomas' old 
college teammate, Barry Sanders, has retired. 
</P>
<P>
	He's also one of three Bills, along with Bruce Smith and Andre  
Reed, still around who played in the team's four straight Super 
Bowl losses of the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	It was understandable that he wasn't crazy at first about  
slipping into the shadows last year behind Smith, the top draft 
pick in 1997. While the Bills still believed Thomas had more 
100-yard games in him -- he has 52 -- they gave Smith the starting 
job because he was younger, bigger and faster. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas, 33, settled in as a situational back and has grown fond  
of actually being able to walk on Monday mornings after games. 
That's why he'll agree to go back to being a starter only in a 
pinch. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like my role that I'm in,'' Thomas said. ``I've gotten to  
the point now where I'm feeling good after ball games and not all 
beat up to where I'm not practicing well until Thursday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Wade Phillips listed Thomas and Smith as co-starters on  
the depth chart but that was seen as a ploy to prod Smith, who 
averaged just 3.8 yards per carry last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, also sparked by the Bills' courting of troubled running  
back Lawrence Phillips, showed up at camp 12 pounds lighter and 
running well. The road seemed to smooth out for Smith when Phillips 
ended up in San Francisco, but Smith aggravated an old groin injury 
and hasn't practiced at full speed since Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas is an obvious candidate to step in, however reluctant he  
might be. But the Bills play their first exhibition game Aug. 14, 
so there's still time for Smith to heal and for Thomas to retain 
his reduced role. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now it's too early to tell what's going to happen,''  
said Thomas, who shares the backfield in the two-back set with 
All-Pro fullback Sam Gash, second-year reserve Jonathan Linton and 
rookie fullback Shawn Bryson from Tennessee, among others. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now Jonathan and I are just waiting for Antowain to get  
healthy,'' Thomas said. ``We wouldn't want this injury keeping him 
out for a long time. But the talent and competition is still 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bills' concern over Smith's condition has ranged from  
borderline panic to relaxed optimism. Wade Phillips used the word 
``chronic'' in describing the injury earlier in the week, but 
Wednesday said he was expecting Smith back. He couldn't say when. 
</P>
<P>
	``You go to the alternatives if he's not there,'' Phillips said.  
``We know what we would do in those situations, but those 
situations haven't come up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bills hope they have enough depth to handle any situation.  
</P>
<P>
	``If it does carry on into the regular season, I would probably  
be the starter and Jonathan (Linton) probably would come in like I 
did with Antowain,'' Thomas said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas says he's not thinking about retirement, despite Sanders  
calling it quits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always been on winning football teams; he's always been  
on losing football teams,'' Thomas said. ``It's easier for me to 
stay here and not think about retirement.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 16:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
