<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TV Helicopter Spots Women Adrift </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Three people whose boat sank during a thunderstorm  
spent a night floating in the Atlantic Ocean before they were 
spotted by a passing boater and a television news helicopter. 
</P>
<P>
	Vicky Scanlon, Daniel Hernandez and Anna Goodwyn, who were all  
wearing life jackets, suffered dehydration, jellyfish stings and 
nasty sunburns. But they were treated and released from a hospital 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm finished with the water for a while,'' Ms. Goodwyn said.  
``I don't think I'm going fishing anymore, unless it's in a little 
pond about 3 feet deep.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The three were caught in a thunderstorm about 3:30 p.m. Monday  
while out in a 15-foot boat. It went down off Elliott Key, about 20 
miles southeast of Miami, in or near Biscayne National Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``The waves come into your mouth so strong that you can't  
breathe,'' Ms. Goodwyn said as she was brought ashore and airlifted 
to a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	After they floated together through the night, Hernandez said he  
decided to try swimming 11 miles back to shore for help. He was 
rescued by a boater about 9:30 a.m. Tuesday, and the Coast Guard 
asked news helicopters to watch for the missing women. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Goodwyn and her daughter, tied together and bobbing around a  
channel marker miles offshore, were located by the crew of 
WTVJ-TV's chopper around 11:30 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	The Miami station aired live shots of the women bobbing in the  
water, Ms. Scanlon crying with relief and waving at the helicopter. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
