<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge: No Bias in Clinton Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Political considerations had nothing to do  
with the assigning of two cases involving President Clinton's 
friends to Clinton-appointed judges, the chief judge of the U.S. 
District Court said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, who personally assigned the two  
cases to judges named by Clinton, said court rules allow chief 
judges to specially assign complex or drawn-out cases to judges 
under their command and that it was her responsibility to ``move 
the docket as expeditiously as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Politics was not and is never a factor in our case  
assignments,'' Johnson said in a letter to the editor published in 
The Washington Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was responding to an Aug. 1 Associated Press story  
published in the paper that said she bypassed the traditional 
random assignment method and sent two criminal cases against 
presidential friends Webster Hubbell and Charlie Trie to judges 
appointed by Clinton who are friendly with key players in the 
cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson assigned the Trie case to Judge Paul L. Friedman and  
sent the Hubbell case to Judge James Robertson. 
</P>
<P>
	Random assignment is used in almost all cases.  
</P>
<P>
	The story quoted court officials and judges, speaking on  
condition of anonymity, as saying that Johnson's decision to assign 
the cases caused several judges to be concerned about an appearance 
of a conflict of interest. 
</P>
<P>
	The judges said they did not believe either Friedman or  
Robertson were improperly influenced. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, Friedman and Robertson had all declined repeated AP  
requests for interviews. 
</P>
<P>
	In her letter, Johnson said the assignment method enables ``our  
court to handle expeditiously high-profile criminal cases with 
unique demands on judicial resources.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several judges who attended a meeting Johnson called on Monday  
to discuss the matter said she told colleagues that several judges 
had heavy workloads at the time of the Trie and Hubbell cases and 
that was a factor in assigning the cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Criminal cases arising from Watergate and the Iran-Contra affair  
were handled through special assignment, she noted in the meeting 
and in her letter to the editor. 
</P>
<P>
	Those assignments, however, were to some of the most experienced  
judges in the courthouse at the time and not to recent appointees, 
AP reported this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson dismissed the tax case against Hubbell, who eventually  
pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor when an appeals court reinstated 
the case. Robertson was later chosen, at random, to handle a felony 
case against Hubbell, charging him with lying to federal 
regulators. Robertson threw out the central felony count in that 
case, but again an appeals court reversed him, and Hubbell 
eventually pleaded guilty to one felony count. 
</P>
<P>
	Friedman tossed out various charges against Trie. After one of  
Friedman's rulings was overturned on appeal, Trie agreed to plead 
guilty. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson also addressed the article's assertions that Robertson  
and Friedman had longtime friendships with key players in the cases 
they got. 
</P>
<P>
	``A judge's prior affiliations or acquaintances, alone, do not  
require recusal or disqualification,'' Johnson wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Lots of judges in the U.S. District Court know lawyers and  
public officials in Washington, she noted. If they were required to 
be disqualified from cases because ``of these innocuous 
connections, it would wreak havoc on case scheduling,'' Johnson 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
