<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Killer Can Stand Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- A man who received As and Bs in college  
after originally being declared incompetent to stand trial in his 
girlfriend's slaying has now been deemed mentally fit. 
</P>
<P>
	Superior Court Judge George Thim declared Tuesday that Kenneth  
Curtis' self-inflicted gunshot wound to the head should not excuse 
him from facing charges in the shooting of Donna Kalson. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is quite clear to this court that Kenneth Curtis has  
purposely exaggerated his symptoms in an effort to influence the 
outcome of this criminal prosecution,'' Thim wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Police say Curtis, now 33, fatally shot Ms. Kalson on Oct. 30,  
1987, then turned the gun on himself. After several hearings in the 
late 1980s, courts concluded that the injury left Curtis so 
impaired that he was incompetent to stand trial. 
</P>
<P>
	But 10 years after his release, police discovered Curtis had  
been taking classes at several colleges. He earned a B-plus average 
from 1992 to 1995, then enrolled in the pre-med psychiatry program 
at Southern Connecticut State University in New Haven. 
</P>
<P>
	He was rearrested in November 1997.  
</P>
<P>
	His lawyer, Salvatore C. DePiano, had argued his client, who  
uses a wheelchair and still has the bullet lodged in his brain, 
wasn't competent to understand the charges against him. 
</P>
<P>
	During his appearances in court, Curtis kept his chin on his  
chest, seemingly oblivious to everything going on around him. The 
image was in stark contrast to videotaped evidence, showing Curtis 
attending classes, and talking about his plans for the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have said he's been exaggerating, and I've said it from Day  
One,'' said Barbara Kalson, the victim's mother. ``He's a great 
actor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DePiano did not return a phone message seeking comment.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
