<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Factory Orders Rise in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Orders to American factories for manufactured  
goods posted a bigger-than-expected increase in June, led by higher 
demand for autos and electronic equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department reported today that factory orders rose  
0.7 percent, following a 1 percent increase in May, a little less 
than the government previously estimated. Many analysts were 
expecting a 0.4 percent rise in overall factory orders in June. 
</P>
<P>
	June's overall performance marked the 10th increase in the last  
13 months. 
</P>
<P>
	The transportation sector helped bolster June's overall  
performance with a 2.3 percent increase. A rise in orders for autos 
and car parts more than offset a decrease in orders for airplane 
and aircraft parts. In May, transportation posted a hefty, 9.9 
percent gain. 
</P>
<P>
	However, excluding the volatile transportation category, factory  
orders would have risen a solid 0.5 percent in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Orders for electronic and other electrical equipment, the  
category that includes household appliances and communications 
equipment, rose 2.4 percent in June, following a drop of 0.9 
percent in May. 
</P>
<P>
	June's overall gain in factory orders came despite a steep, 5.1  
percent decrease in orders for industrial machinery and equipment, 
the sector that includes computers. It was the second straight 
monthly decline. In May, orders for industrial machinery fell 4.5 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's report offered some positive signs for the steel  
industry. Orders for primary metals, the category that includes 
steel, rose 0.4 percent in June, following gains in April and May. 
The steel industry has been one of the hardest hit by the Asian 
crisis, suffering from a flood of cheaper imported steel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, orders for durable goods -- items expected to last at  
least three years -- also went up in June, rising 0.4 percent. And, 
orders for nondurable goods, such as food and fuel also increased, 
posting a 1.2 percent gain. 
</P>
<P>
	The solid showing in overall factory orders in June appears to  
be good news for the U.S. manufacturing sector, which is recovering 
from the global economic crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturing has been the hardest-hit sector from the turmoil,  
suffering from dampened overseas demand for U.S. goods and 
competition from a flood of cheaper imports. Since March 1998, 
488,000 manufacturing jobs have been lost. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, a report from the National Association of Purchasing  
Management said the U.S. manufacturing sector grew in July for the 
sixth straight month, but not as strongly as most analysts 
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets have been rattled over concerns that the  
Federal Reserve, which raised interest rates on June 30, may raise 
them again, possibly as early as this month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
