<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed; Dow Up 52.55 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading today as a  
planned $9.3 billion merger of Dow Chemical Co. and Union Carbide 
Corp. propped up the blue chips but broader market indicators 
lagged well behind. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 52.55 at 10,729.86. On Tuesday, the blue-chip index rose 31.35 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	Following Tuesday's pattern, other market indexes struggled  
while the Dow marched higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was 
down 1.82 at 1,320.36, and the Nasdaq composite index was down 8.66 
at 2,579.33. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow's gains came largely from the news that Dow Chemical is  
buying Union Carbide, building its position as the No. 2 chemical 
company behind DuPont. The two companies said they expect the 
combination to save $500 million a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Union Carbide soared 11 7/16 to 60 1/4, while Dow Chemical fell 4 1/4  
to 120 7/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, traders remained unconvinced of the market's underlying  
strength. Bond prices, which have tumbled amid the growing belief 
that the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates, were holding 
steady today. But the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond now offers a 
yield of 6.16 percent, high enough to lure some investors away from 
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks were expected to stay in a fairly narrow range through  
Friday, when the Labor Department releases its monthly unemployment 
report. The report is expected to offer the latest indication of 
whether wage pressures are escalating enough to persuade the Fed to 
raise rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 90.8 million 
shares, ahead of Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 0.67 at 621.73, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was up 1.95 at 782.42. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.58 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.6 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.4 percent, and France's CAC-40 was 
down 0.3 percent. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
