<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sandpiper Teams With RealNetworks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. (AP) -- Sandpiper Networks Inc., which  
helps the LATimes.com site and America Online put content on the 
Internet, is teaming with RealNetworks Inc. to provide streaming 
media services to its clients. 
</P>
<P>
	In the agreement announced Wednesday, customers of Sandpiper can  
acquire RealNetworks software licenses for broadcasting live events 
through Sandpiper. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, Sandpiper, through its network of more than 400  
worldwide server computers, has delivered real-time events such as 
the 1999 Academy Awards and the release of the Ken Starr Report for 
its clients, the company's vice president of marketing Scott Yara 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The financial terms of the deal weren't disclosed, but the  
Seattle-based RealNetworks will receive software licensing fees and 
a share in revenue resulting from the venture, Yara said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandpiper's network of computers, known as Footprint, lets  
publishers outsource the delivery end of their operations. 
</P>
<P>
	While many of its clients' sites already have their own  
streaming media services, Sandpiper's providing it via its network 
will mean better quality and quicker service, Yara said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandpiper, based in Thousand Oaks, Calif., can do that because  
it gives viewers of its clients' Web sites information they request 
from a server that is geographically closest to them. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Sandpiper announced that it received a $21.5 million  
round of financing involving AOL, Inktomi and an affiliate of 
Times-Mirror, which owns the Los Angeles Times. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
