<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Springer in Senate Frightens Some </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- There's a joke going around about how Ohio  
Democrats could find a rich and famous candidate for U.S. Senate: 
Jerry Springer might throw his chair into the ring. 
</P>
<P>
	Not everybody's laughing.  
</P>
<P>
	Springer, 55, has said he'll consider running as a Democratic  
challenger to Sen. Mike DeWine, who is up for re-election next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first thing I thought when I heard his name proposed was,  
`Are these guys nuts? Are they totally insane?''' Jim Schifrin, who 
publishes an independent political newsletter called The 
Whistleblower, said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Springer is a former two-term mayor of Cincinnati who ran for  
governor in 1982, then embarked on a TV career, working as an 
anchor and commentator before discovering that brawling, 
chair-throwing freaks and geeks could make him the nation's No. 
2-rated daytime talk show host. 
</P>
<P>
	DeWine is a former prosecutor whose low-key earnestness led  
colleagues to choose him to preside over Monica Lewinsky's 
deposition in President Clinton's impeachment trial. Messy affairs 
like that are mainstays of ``The Jerry Springer Show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DeWine has not commented on Springer, but the state's Republican  
chairman, Bob Bennett, has been brandishing jabs like, ``Was Howard 
Stern busy?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schifrin put out a Top 10 list of reasons for a Springer  
candidacy, with entries such as No. 9, ``He's promised to stop 
paying prostitutes with checks.'' Springer did that once as a young 
councilman in 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea of a Senate run surfaced July 20 in The Plain Dealer of  
Cleveland. Springer's hometown pal in Cincinnati, Hamilton County 
Democratic Party Chairman Tim Burke, told the newspaper the 
talk-show host would be a ``viable, fascinating, interesting 
candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Wrong, wrong and wrong,'' the Plain Dealer editorialized the  
next day. A spasm of righteousness rippled across the state. An 
editorial in The Vindicator of Youngstown called Springer 
``ringmaster of the nation's sleaziest circus.'' Toledo Mayor Carty 
Finkbeiner said Springer would get in the way of his party's 
emphasis on ``family values.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Springer put out a statement saying: ``I'm obviously flattered  
and honored by the interest. It's just that at this time I don't 
know whether it's practical or possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Springer said he's giving the Senate race serious consideration  
and will decide by Labor Day. The filing deadline is not until Jan. 
7, but to put on a campaign, Springer would have to deal with 
residency -- he lives in Chicago -- and figure out what to do with 
the syndicated show that has earned him millions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Springer left the country for a vacation late last month after  
his show went on hiatus, and was not available to comment further, 
his publicist Linda Shaffron said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio Democratic chairman David Leland said the party executive  
committee would decide later this year whether to endorse a 
candidate. Columbus lawyer Richard Cordray, the party's 
unsuccessful candidate for state attorney general last year, is 
seeking that backing. 
</P>
<P>
	Leland said he hadn't heard from Springer, but if he does he'll  
tell him that people across the state have strong feelings about a 
possible candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are people who are incensed about the fact that he would  
do this,'' Leland said. ``They think it would not be a good 
thing,'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, Leland said, some people are volunteering to help  
Springer, others think he has no chance, and yet a third group is 
scared he'd win. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
