<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 11:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes Inventor Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- By a wide margin, the House approved  
legislation today that would strengthen the patent system and 
safeguard independent inventors, though opponents said the bill 
would threaten the livelihoods of small-scale inventors. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would protect inventors from predatory promoters,  
guarantee them 17 years' protection after the Patent and Trademark 
Office has granted a patent, and maintain confidentiality for some 
patent applications. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar legislation died in the Senate in 1997 after winning  
approval in the House, 220-193. Lawmakers made some changes this 
year to address concerns that the bill made small-scale inventors 
more vulnerable to theft and litigation, leading to House passage 
by a 376-43 vote Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., who led the opposition in 1997,  
said the new bill was a ``major victory for the independent 
inventor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The chief sponsor, Rep. Howard Coble, R-N.C., said it would make  
the patent system, ``already the world's best, even better in the 
new millennium.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, which now goes to the Senate, would give an inventor  
17 years of protection after being granted a patent. The protection 
now is 20 years from application, which can be shorter than 17 
years if the patent office takes longer than three years to grant 
the patent. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would track European and Japanese practices by  
publishing applications after 18 months, but inventors who seek 
patents only in the United States still could claim 
confidentiality. 
</P>
<P>
	Coble and others argued that publication would make it easier to  
attract investors and inform potential rivals that someone has 
already staked a claim. Palo Alto, Calif., patent litigator Jim 
Pooley noted it is ``the collective judgment of the industrial 
world that 18 months ought to be plenty of time'' for an inventor 
to describe his creation. 
</P>
<P>
	But critics said it would make it easier for big corporations  
and foreign countries to steal a small-scale inventor's product. 
</P>
<P>
	``A big company can come in and wipe out an inventor,'' said  
Beverly Selby, executive director of the Alliance for American 
Innovation. ``We will pay a price for this over the next 50 
years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Selby and other representatives of inventors also objected to  
``prior user rights'' in the legislation that provides a legal 
defense against charges of patent infringement filed by parties 
that later get a patent. 
</P>
<P>
	Phyllis Schlafly of the conservative Eagle Forum said it would  
``enable corporations to claim a 'prior use right' and thereby 
steal the independent inventor's constitutional right to 
'exclusive' ownership of his discovery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But supporters argued that the defense can only be used for  
methods, not products, and would help small businesses who rely on 
trade secrecy laws rather than going to the trouble of trying to 
get patents for every method used in production. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also aims, through early publication, to counter  
``submarining'' -- the practice by which people delay action on 
their patent applications and then file huge lawsuits against 
competitors, who, not knowing a patent is on file, come out with 
similar products. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1907.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
