<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. City Claims School Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COMPTON, Calif. (AP) -- City officials have declared a state of  
emergency in Compton's schools following a series of arson fires, 
the latest blow for a troubled district that serves 29,000 
students. 
</P>
<P>
	The city also said it would pursue a plan for volunteer  
``sentinels'' to patrol schools 24 hours a day. Compton and the 
school district each are offering $10,000 for information about the 
eight fires this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The state of California is responsible for these fires even if  
they haven't set them themselves,'' Mayor Omar Bradley said 
Tuesday. ``We intend to make sure when the state leaves we still 
have schools to administer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fires have caused $1.7 million in damage at six facilities  
in the 40-school district. Six fires damaged classrooms; two others 
were set in unoccupied buildings. No one has been hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	Fire and police officials would say little about the  
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of the nature of the fires and the location of the  
fires we believe it's more than a firebug at this time,'' Fire 
Chief Milfred Fonza said without elaboration. 
</P>
<P>
	The Compton Unified School District was taken over by the state  
in 1993 as it teetered near bankruptcy. It has been the object of a 
battle by local officials to regain control. 
</P>
<P>
	About 20 people signed up as volunteers after the City Council  
approved the emergency declaration on a 4-0 vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``I teach in the district and I don't want to see the schools  
burn down,'' said Carl Robinson, 64, offering to watch schools for 
six hours a week. 
</P>
<P>
	The district viewed the patrol plan with caution.  
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is nobody will be allowed on our campus,''  
said district spokesman Fausto Capobianco. ``It would be in 
violation of state law and it would create confusion on our 
campuses. Who is to tell if one of these people is the perpetrator 
himself?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Capobianco said the district has already increased patrols and  
is spending $3.5 million on installing fire and intruder alarms at 
its schools. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
