<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 13:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Promises To Veto Tax Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today promised to veto a  
Republican plan that would lower the tax rate of every American who 
pays income tax. He called the bill ``risky and plainly wrong for 
America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 10-year, $792 billion tax cut package put together by House  
and Senate Republicans would gradually cut 1 percentage point off 
each personal income tax rate. It also would provide relief from 
the so-called marriage penalty, cut the individual capital-gains 
tax rate and eventually eliminate the estate tax. 
</P>
<P>
	As details were worked out at the staff level, one senior Senate  
aide said the package would propose reducing the 15 percent bracket 
to 14.5 percent next year, with a further cut to 14 percent in 
2006. At that point, the income level under which people would fall 
into the 14 percent, or lowest bracket, would be raised by between 
$4,000 and $5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they conclude this plan and send it to me,'' Clinton said,  
``I will have to veto it. I will refuse to sign any plan that signs 
away our commitment to America's future, Social Security, Medicare, 
paying down the debt.'' Speaking with reporters in the Rose Garden, 
Clinton said the GOP formula would jeopardize the economic success 
the nation has enjoyed under his administration and ``revert to one 
that is a proven failure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with the start of the August vacation at the end of the  
week, negotiators moved with unusual speed over two days of talks 
to resolve differences in the House and Senate bills, each of which 
totaled $792 billion in cuts but differed substantially in details. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP leadership intends to move the bill through both the  
House and Senate on Thursday, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and House Speaker  
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., were actively involved in the negotiations, 
while Democrats, who overwhelmingly opposed the GOP plans, were 
shut out of the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Republicans have sequestered themselves in a room in order  
to piece together a political bill they know is going nowhere,'' 
said Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., ranking Democrat on the Ways and 
Means panel. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House brushed off warnings by Lott and House Majority  
Leader Dick Armey that prospects are dimming that Congress and 
Clinton can agree on a tax bill this year. ``The remarks sound like 
two leaders in a sandbox,'' presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart 
said. ``If they don't get their way, they don't want to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the GOP tax numbers ``just don't add up. It's pretty  
clear the Republican leadership is interested in making a political 
statement.'' And he countered a question about the political 
consequences of vetoing a tax cut with assurances that voters are 
cognizant of the administration's economic record. 
</P>
<P>
	``Others will handicap the risks of what the president is going  
to do, but he's going to do it because it's the right thing for the 
public,'' Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has said repeatedly that he will veto the GOP bill  
because he says the tax cut would use up almost all of the 
projected non-Social Security surplus over the next decade, leaving 
almost nothing for needed government programs and paying down the 
national debt. Clinton and most Democrats have said that any cut 
over $300 billion would be unacceptably risky to the nation's 
economic future. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans insist they can return the money to the taxpayers  
that rightfully belongs to them and still have enough to save 
Social Security and Medicare and pay down part of the national 
debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the GOP plan, each of the five tax brackets would go down  
by 1 percentage point. The lowest 15 percent tax bracket would fall 
to 14 percent in 2001, and the highest 39.6 percent bracket would 
become 38.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The House-passed bill included a 10 percent across-the-board tax  
cut, which was strongly criticized by the White House and Democrats 
as disproportionately favoring wealthy taxpayers. The 1 percentage 
point cut would give taxpayers in the 15 percent bracket a 7 
percent cut, better than that in the higher brackets. 
</P>
<P>
	To alleviate the marriage penalty, under which some married  
couples pay more in taxes than if they were single because their 
combined income moves them into a higher bracket, the Republican 
bill would gradually raise the standard deduction for couples until 
it is double the level permitted for individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, it would widen the current 15 percent bracket for  
couples so it would apply to some income that currently is taxed at 
28 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	There would be no cuts in the corporate capital gains tax, but  
personal capital gains taxes would be reduced from 20 percent to 18 
percent on some gains and 10 percent to 8 percent on others -- and 
adjusted annually for inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. William Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Senate Finance  
Committee, said contribution limits to individual retirement 
accounts would rise gradually from $2,000 to $5,000 annually. He 
said the self-employed would be permitted to deduct the entire cost 
of their health insurance premiums. Other officials said medical 
savings accounts, tax-deductible accounts set aside for 
health-related costs, would be more readily available. 
</P>
<P>
	However, it would not be sent to the president until after  
Congress returned to work in September, giving supporters the 
chance to return home and tout the bill's benefits to their 
constituents. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans ``would like to take our message to the American  
people,'' Lott said. ``Maybe the president will conclude at some 
point that he needs to work with us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 09:40:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Market Fever Takes Hold of Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) -- Market fever has taken hold in Cyprus. It  
has gotten to the point, islanders joke, that even a poor village 
shepherd -- symbol of the country's enduring traditions -- would sell 
his goats to buy shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Never mind that the three-year-old market lists only 116  
securities and merits barely a tick on international financial 
screens. Investing in shares is an obsession with Cypriots, with 
thousands throwing caution to the wind and abandoning the safety of 
deposit accounts and land, until recently the dominant investment 
choices on this Mediterranean holiday island. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, there are stories making the rounds of a couple playing the  
market with money that had been set aside for their children's 
college education, or a grandmother who is a first-time investor at 
age 70. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-eight-year old architect George Alexandros bought shares  
for the first time in late July, putting $5,430 in savings into a 
local retailer. Married with two children, Alexandros wanted to get 
into the market earlier, but had no cash to spare. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did not want to do what everyone else is doing, and borrow  
money to play the market. Now, I have put just enough that even if 
the market crashes, I won't go hungry,'' Alexandros said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like to gamble and I am likely to make more money in the  
market than betting on football,'' he added. ``I need to make 
enough money on the market to pay 6,000 pounds ($10,860) 
outstanding on a debt I took to buy a piece of land.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Less than two years ago, brokers at the Cyprus Stock Exchange  
complained that trade was so thin they played games on their 
computers on some days to pass the time. A volume of $900,000 was 
not unusual and not many of the island's 700,000 people even knew 
their country had a market. 
</P>
<P>
	Not anymore.  
</P>
<P>
	The Cyprus market's capitalization stood at $6.11 billion by the  
end of June, nearly double what it was in December. Bank shares 
account for more than two-thirds of the market's capitalization. 
</P>
<P>
	State television recently began broadcasting prices live during  
the 90 daily minutes of trading, Monday through Friday. Bankers are 
reporting an unusual upsurge in borrowing by clients to buy shares, 
prompting the Central Bank to instruct them to tighten credit 
facilities offered to what it called ``market speculators and 
gamblers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A meteoric rise in share prices since the start of the year -- an  
increase of more than 212 percent through today from its lows in 
the first week of January -- was both evidence of demand and the 
trigger that unleashed a new wave of interest. 
</P>
<P>
	The dramatic increase in prices was accompanied by a surge in  
volume that is partly caused by the introduction in early May of 
automated trading to replace a cumbersome open-cry system. The 
average number of daily transactions has since shot up from 500 to 
4,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The volume, which registered an all-time record $124.85 million  
July 28, caused such a backlog of administrative work that the 
market was closed July 26 and 27 to give brokerages and listed 
companies time to clear transactions. On Monday, a further closing 
for the week starting Aug. 9 was announced, after brokers 
complained that two days was not enough. 
</P>
<P>
	There are fears that shares are becoming overvalued and that the  
market was turning into a speculative bubble that might burst. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has gone crazy,'' said senior economist Marios Clerides.  
``We have reached a stage where there is no connection between a 
company's actual value and its share capital. People are buying 
shares like tomatoes and cucumbers. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one is looking at the fundamentals of companies in which  
they are buying, the same way no one is going to look at the 
fundamentals when the selling begins,'' he said, warning of a 
downward correction that might trigger panic selling. 
</P>
<P>
	The market has occasionally dipped for one or two sessions and  
then returned to bullishness. 
</P>
<P>
	Beside demand from newcomers, the market's rally is being  
sustained by relative political stability on the war-divided island 
and the positive sentiment arising from the prospect of the 
island's leading banks being listed in the boisterous Athens Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rally is also fed by the belief that the island's European  
Union accession is going smoothly,'' said Yiannos Tirkides, chief 
economist at the Popular Bank, the island's second largest. ``But 
you must also factor in human greed.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
