<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Agreement Near on HMO Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Democrats and a group of moderate  
Republicans were close to agreement on writing legislation to 
impose new regulations on health maintenance organizations and 
allow patients to sue them, aides said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bipartisan proposal was to be announced before the end of  
the week, when Congress leaves for its August vacation, Democratic 
and Republican aides said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Dingell of Michigan, the senior Democrat on the House  
Commerce Committee, and Rep. Charles Norwood, R-N.C., were working 
to put the final touches on the proposal, said Norwood's spokesman, 
John Stone. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate last month passed a Republican-backed modest set of  
patient protections for Americans worried that their health care 
needs are of secondary concern to cost-cutting HMOs. Administration 
officials said President Clinton would veto that bill if it was 
sent to him. 
</P>
<P>
	Efforts by Republican leaders to offer a similar bill in the  
House hit a snag when a group of Republicans led by Norwood, Tom 
Coburn of Oklahoma and Greg Ganske of Iowa -- all health care 
providers before entering Congress -- said they preferred the 
tougher approach sought by Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan to be introduced by Dingell and Norwood would give  
patients the right to seek a third opinion from medical specialists 
if their HMO plan denies coverage and allow a patient to sue an HMO 
if an injury results from a covered benefit being denied. 
</P>
<P>
	However, HMOs that abide by federal rules establishing internal  
and external appeals procedures for patients would be exempt from 
liability suits. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dingell-Norwood proposal also would require HMOs to pay the  
bills of medical specialists who are not provider members of the 
organization and any emergency care. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate-passed plan does not allow lawsuits, which most  
Republicans contend would drive up the costs of health care, but 
does include easier access to specialists, emergency rooms and 
obstetricians and gynecologists. 
</P>
<P>
	Sources said the House negotiators were down to a few relatively  
minor issues such as how to protect hospital whisteblowers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 14:10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Chemical To Buy Union Carbide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The Dow Chemical Co., the maker of Styrofoam, is  
buying Union Carbide Corp., the leader in producing the chemicals 
used in making polyester and antifreeze. 
</P>
<P>
	The $9.3 billion deal announced Wednesday would create the  
world's second-largest chemical business behind DuPont Co., 
strengthening Dow's perch in a sluggish chemical market beset by 
depressed prices due to a drop in demand in struggling overseas 
economies. 
</P>
<P>
	The merged company, which will operate under the Dow Chemical  
name, will have $24 billion in annual revenue, putting it ahead of 
the current No. 2, Germany's BASF AG, according to the most recent 
rankings by Chemical Week, a magazine covering the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	About 2,000 jobs will be cut as a result of the merger, leaving  
about 49,000 employees. Dow Chemical said the cuts would come 
through reduced hiring and attrition, but Dow Chemical President 
and chief executive William S. Stavropoulos declined to be more 
specific about where the cuts might be made. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies said they expect the combination to save $500  
million a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger would unite two companies that have faced crises.  
</P>
<P>
	A 1984 leak at Union Carbide's pesticide plant in Bhopal, India,  
killed 4,000 people and injured 50,000 in the world's worst 
recorded industrial accident. A court in Bhopal later ruled that 
exposure to the gas claimed thousands of additional lives over the 
years since the leak. Union Carbide paid a $470 million settlement 
in India's Supreme Court in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Chemical is a half-owner of Dow Corning Corp., the former  
silicone breast implant manufacturer which has offered to pay $3.2 
billion to settle claims from 170,000 women who claim illnesses 
resulted from their implants. Dow Corning no longer makes breast 
implants. 
</P>
<P>
	The merged company's corporate headquarters will remain in  
Midland, Mich., where Dow Chemical is based. 
</P>
<P>
	``This transaction is a giant step in our strategy to transform  
Dow into the world's most productive, best 'value-growth' company 
in the chemical industry,'' Stavropoulos said. Dow is ranked third 
in the world in chemical sales and second in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow ``is the ideal partner to move forward,'' said William  
Joyce, Union Carbide's chairman and chief executive. ``The new Dow 
is much, much stronger than either company has been in the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Union Carbide is ranked 21st in the world in chemical sales and  
seventh in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, Union Carbide shareholders will receive 0.537  
share of Dow Chemical for each of their Union Carbide shares -- or 
$66.96 based on Tuesday's closing price of Dow Chemical's stock. 
Dow Chemical will also assume $2.3 billion in debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Union Carbide shareholders will own about 25 percent of Dow  
Chemical after the deal is complete, and Joyce will become vice 
chairman of the Dow Chemical board of directors. 
</P>
<P>
	News of the merger sent Union Carbide's stock soaring $10.56 1/4,or  
by almost 22 percent, to $59.37 1/2 a share Wednesday on the New York 
Stock Exchange, where Dow Chemical's stock slid $6.06 1/4, or by 
almost 5 percent, to $118.62 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock market analysts said the deal made sense.  
</P>
<P>
	``We like it,'' said Alex Hittle, an associate analyst at A.G.  
Edwards &AMP; Sons. ``You've got two companies, both of whom are in the 
down part of the commodities cycle now. That's a good time for Dow 
to be a buyer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hittle said the companies complement each other, with little  
duplication in businesses, but there was still some risk for Dow. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Dow Chemical has been weathering the industry's downturn  
because it has built up its business in specialty chemicals, which 
are designed to enhance the performance of other products and have 
specialized markets. The acquisition of Union Carbide ``seems to be 
a move back to basic chemicals,'' which are sold in bulk to a wide 
range of industries. 
</P>
<P>
	``That could be risky for them if they have trouble operating  
Carbide's assets or if the trough drags on longer than expected,'' 
Hittle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Raj Kothari, director of GMA Capital, a mergers and acquisitions  
firm in Farmington Hills, Mich., said there were logistical 
challenges in making the merger work. 
</P>
<P>
	``The short-term hurdle will be how do you integrate two global  
organizations as big as these two. Basically what you're trying to 
acheive is one plus one equals three,'' Kothari said. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger requires the approval of Union Carbide shareholders  
and U.S and European antitrust regulators. The companies said they 
expect the deal to be completed by the first quarter of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Chemical, with earnings of $1.3 billion on sales of $18.4  
billion in 1998, produces a variety of chemicals, plastics and 
herbicides. Its product lines includes Styrofoam insulation. 
</P>
<P>
	Union Carbide, based in Danbury, Conn., had profits of $403  
million in 1998 on sales of $5.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	It was born in a merger of several companies in 1917 as the  
Union Carbide &AMP; Carbon Corp. Over the years, it developed Prestone 
antifreeze, Glad plastic bags and Eveready batteries, brands it 
later sold to other manufacturers. From the 1940s to 1984, it ran 
the U.S. government's nuclear laboratories in Tennessee and 
Kentucky. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 23:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Nomination Clears Hurdle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The high-profile post of U.S. ambassador to  
the United Nations, long vacant, appears close to being filled as 
the Senate finally prepares to vote on the nomination of Richard 
Holbrooke. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders of both parties are predicting easy confirmation for the  
combative career diplomat when the Senate takes up the nomination 
today -- after 14 months of delay, partisan wrangling and suspense. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke, an investment banker, is a former ambassador to  
Germany and was architect of the 1995 accord that ended the war in 
Bosnia. He also has served as Clinton's special envoy in the Kosovo 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	A confirmation vote was all but assured on Wednesday when Sen.  
Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, the final senator blocking the 
nomination, lifted his objections. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley said his tactics hadn't been personal. ``I intend to  
vote for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley is in a standoff with the State Department over its  
treatment of a career employee he claims was punished for sharing 
information on U.N. financial irregularities with Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	But Grassley's tactics created new problems for other diplomatic  
nominees. Grassley said he instead would block three other pending 
nominations, including that of Peter Burleigh as ambassador to the 
Philippines. 
</P>
<P>
	Burleigh has been filling in for Holbrooke at the United Nations  
since last September. In New York, Burleigh said he would have no 
comment on Grassley's hold on him. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley said he was also putting ``holds'' on Carl Spielvogel  
to be ambassador to the Slovak Republic and Richard Fredericks to 
be ambassador to Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton announced the Holbrooke nomination in June 1998. But it  
quickly became tangled, first in internal investigations at the 
Justice and State departments into Holbrooke's contacts with former 
State Department colleagues and then in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Three other senators had also sought to block the nomination --  
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky, 
and Sen. George Voinovich, R-Ohio -- but they earlier abandoned the 
tactics. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Senate tradition, any member without explanation may block  
action on legislation or a nomination for as long as the majority 
leader permits. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley used the technique to protest the State Department's  
treatment of a whistleblower, Linda Shenwick. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley contends that Shenwick, who worked at the U.N. mission  
in New York, was demoted and transferred to a lesser job in 
Washington in retaliation for her telling members of Congress about 
waste and inefficiency at the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``My interest in this matter is very simple,'' Grassley said.  
``Congress cannot function as an institution if government 
employees cannot communicate with Congress about wrongdoing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department has said Shenwick was reassigned because of  
unsatisfactory job performance, not because she was a 
whistleblower. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. post has been vacant since the last ambassador, Bill  
Richardson, stepped down last September to become energy secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	During the intervening time, the United States launched  
airstrikes against both Iraq and Yugoslavia. Burleigh, the 
assistant U.N. ambassador, served a stint as presiding officer of 
the Security Council and had to deal with the issue of delinquent 
U.S. payments to the international body. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke, 58, had been confirmed by the Senate three times  
previously: in 1977 as assistant secretary of state in the Carter 
administration, again in 1993 as ambassador to Germany, and later 
as assistant secretary of state for European and Canadian affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	He also was a contender for secretary of state in Clinton's  
second term before the president chose Madeleine Albright. 
</P>
<P>
	But Holbrooke, ambitious and with a forceful personality, has  
produced detractors as well as fans, both in Congress and within 
the State Department. 
</P>
<P>
	He has been at odds at times with Albright. And he is a favorite  
target for Republicans since he's widely viewed as a likely 
secretary of state if Vice President Al Gore wins the presidency. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 11:10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pan Am Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- One high jump winner has been stripped  
of a gold medal at the Pan American Games. Is another, Javier 
Sotomayor, about to be? 
</P>
<P>
	After announcing that Juana Rosario Arrendel of the Dominican  
Republic, winner of the women's high jump, was stripped of her 
medal for failing a drug test, organizers said another athlete's 
first test had come back positive. A news conference with Pan 
American Sports Organization president Mario Vazquez Rana and 
medical officers was scheduled for 5 p.m. EDT. Another news 
conference, with Cuban team medical officials, was scheduled for 6 
p.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Felix Quintero, Sotomayor's personal physician, will attend  
that news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Sotomayor is the world indoor and outdoor record-holder and the  
only man to clear 8 feet. He also is the 1992 Olympic champion and 
a four-time Pan Ams winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Rodrigo Alvarez Cambra of the Cuban delegation traveled  
Tuesday to the drug analysis facility in Montreal, sources close to 
the Cuban team said. The sources emphasized that a key medical 
officer of the delegation would not be sent on such an assignment 
if the drug test did not involve a leading Cuban athlete. 
</P>
<P>
	Sotomayor won the high jump on the last day of the track and  
field competition. But neither Vasquez Rana nor the medical 
director of the games, Eduardo de Rose, would confirm that the 
positive A test came from the last day of that competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked specifically if that test came from the final day, de Rose  
said, ``I don't want to answer your question. I have the right to 
no comment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arrendel did respond to charges she tested positive for the  
banned anabolic steroid stanozolol, the same substance that caused 
Ben Johnson to be stripped of his gold medal in the 100 meters at 
the 1988 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Arrendel was quoted in the Dominican Republic as denying she  
used stanozolol and said the test may have picked up a decongestant 
she used before the event. 
</P>
<P>
	``In six years in athletics, I have never used substances to  
enhance my performance,'' she said in remarks published Tuesday in 
the newspaper La Informacion. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Ray Martinez, a baseball player from Mexico, refused to  
take a drug test Monday after his team's loss to Canada in the 
bronze medal game. That was tantamount to a positive test, 
organizers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Arrendel won the high jump with a leap of 6 feet, 4 inches and  
had been the Dominican Republic's only gold medalist at the games 
so far. Argentina's Solange Witteveen, the runner-up, now gets the 
gold. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second drug case announced at these games. In the  
first, Steve Vezina, goalkeeper for the Canadian in-line roller 
hockey team that beat the United States 7-6 in the title game, 
tested positive for stimulants and steroids. Canada was stripped of 
the gold, which was awarded to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	American middleweight Arthur Palac advanced to the boxing  
semifinals, using his reach and unorthodox style to outpoint David 
Sanchez of Mexico 8-3. 
</P>
<P>
	At 6-foot-4 and 165 pounds, the left-handed Palac makes an  
awkward opponent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, I don't want to fight, although I can if I need  
to,'' said Palac, whose father is a former Polish boxer and his 
coach. ``I want to box and keep them at the end of my punches. And 
being left-handed is good for the computer system, because the 
judges will always count your jabs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another U.S. winner in the quarterfinals was welterweight  
LaChaunce Shepherd, who decisioned Francisco Calderon of Columbia 
8-3. But light heavyweight Joseph Pastorello, a captain in the U.S. 
Air Force, lost a tight 3-2 decision to Brazil's Laudelino Barros. 
The match was tied heading into the fourth and final round. 
</P>
<P>
	Three Cubans scored lopsided victories.  
</P>
<P>
	Welterweight Juan Hernandez, the 1996 Olympics silver medalist,  
had an 11-1 win over Guillermo Saputo of Argentina; middleweight 
Yohason Martinez routed Canada's Trevor Stewardson 10-1; and light 
heavyweight Humberto Savigne was awarded a referee's decision after 
knocking down Barbados' Shawn Cox in the first round with a shot to 
the head. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time since 1955, U.S. swimmers failed to get at  
least one medal in an individual event at the Pan Ams. Jarod 
Schroeder of Morrison, Ill., and Sabir Muhammad of Atlanta failed 
to qualify for the final of the men's 100-meter butterfly. 
Schroeder was 11th overall in the prelims at 55.89, Muhammad was 
17th at 57.20. Only the top eight qualify for the final. 
</P>
<P>
	Francisco Sanchez gave Venezuela its first gold ever in the 100  
butterfly with a games record of 53.33. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. men's 800 freestyle relay won the nation's only gold  
Tuesday. Adam Messner, Dan Phillips, Devin Howard and Scott Tucker 
finished just ahead of Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Danielle Henderson of Commack, N.Y., pitched her second perfect  
game of the softball competition, beating the Bahamas 12-0 in five 
innings. She fanned 13 of 15 batters. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 17:41:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Falcons' McDaniels Unique Off Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- For Pellom McDaniels, football is merely  
a starting point for discussion. 
</P>
<P>
	Very quickly, the conversation shifts away from zone blitzes and  
blocking schemes to very un-football-like passions such as writing, 
painting and poetry. 
</P>
<P>
	McDaniels is not just a defensive end for the Atlanta Falcons.  
He's an artist and entrepreneur, inventor and philosopher, civic 
crusader and willing role model, dreamer and renaissance man. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once I finally made it to the NFL, I knew if I put my mind to  
something I could do it,'' McDaniels said. ``I started using 
football to get me in a lot of other doors, with my writing, my 
invention and all that other stuff. I just took a chance. I found 
out the worst thing in life that people could tell me was `no.' I 
find out the reasons they say no, then turn around and use it to my 
advantage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He's written two books, with a third on the way. ``My Own  
Harlem'' offers poetic musings and deeply personal thoughts of a 
complex young man in search of a place for himself and his people. 
``So You Want To Be A Pro?'' shares with young people his views on 
discipline, coping with peer pressure, time management and the 
importance of education. 
</P>
<P>
	There's more.  
</P>
<P>
	McDaniels and his wife, Navvab, launched the ``Arts for Smarts''  
program, which acquaints thousands of disadvantaged kids with 
dance, theater and literature. He owns and operates a clothing 
business. Even something as common as an unpleasant trip to the 
dentist started the wheels spinning: He invented his own flavored 
gel, got it cleared through the Food and Drug Administration and 
put it on the market. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm an eclectic-type person,'' McDaniels said. ``I let myself  
do anything I want to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McDaniels, 31, signed with the Falcons after seven years in  
Kansas City, providing the NFC champions with some much-needed 
depth on the defensive line. It's the same role he played with the 
Chiefs, filling in wherever he was needed on a team that featured 
Neil Smith, Derrick Thomas and Chester McGlockton. 
</P>
<P>
	``I figured out a long time ago that if you wanted to do  
anything, you have to know more about it than anyone else,'' 
McDaniels said. ``I learned every position to get the job in Kansas 
City. Whenever I was called upon -- whether it was nose guard, left 
end or right end -- I had to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McDaniels' work ethic stems from the rejection he felt on draft  
day in 1990, when no team called despite a solid career at Oregon 
State. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was devastating,'' said McDaniels, who earned a degree in  
communications and political science. ``I thought I did everything 
right in college, in athletics and academics, and it just didn't 
pan out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He took a job selling health and beauty care products, but  
football was still in his blood. The following year, he played for 
the World League's Birmingham Fire, earning a tryout from the 
Philadelphia Eagles. Failing to make the team, he returned to 
Birmingham for another season in the minors. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, he earned a spot with the Chiefs in 1992.  
</P>
<P>
	``It all stems from not making it,'' McDaniels said. ``I feel  
blessed going to work every day. I don't take it for granted. It's 
a job, but this game has given me a lot. Confidence, for one. 
Self-esteem. A feeling of accomplishment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For him, the greatest feeling is discovering an opponent's  
weakness in the film room, then taking advantage of it on the 
field. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, for instance, he noticed the Steelers ran a sweep  
every time the tight end went in motion to that side of the field. 
During a Monday night game, he seized on that revelation to tackle 
Jerome Bettis in the backfield for a 7-yard loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a great feeling,'' McDaniels said. ``I may not be a  
starter, but when I play I make plays.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also makes a difference away from the field.  
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't know about all that other stuff until we started  
talking about signing him,'' Falcons coach Dan Reeves said. ``I've 
never had anybody that has their own company, writes books. ... 
It's really intriguing to see all the stuff he's done.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 17:41:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Falcons' McDaniels Unique Off Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- For Pellom McDaniels, football is merely  
a starting point for discussion. 
</P>
<P>
	Very quickly, the conversation shifts away from zone blitzes and  
blocking schemes to very un-football-like passions such as writing, 
painting and poetry. 
</P>
<P>
	McDaniels is not just a defensive end for the Atlanta Falcons.  
He's an artist and entrepreneur, inventor and philosopher, civic 
crusader and willing role model, dreamer and renaissance man. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once I finally made it to the NFL, I knew if I put my mind to  
something I could do it,'' McDaniels said. ``I started using 
football to get me in a lot of other doors, with my writing, my 
invention and all that other stuff. I just took a chance. I found 
out the worst thing in life that people could tell me was `no.' I 
find out the reasons they say no, then turn around and use it to my 
advantage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He's written two books, with a third on the way. ``My Own  
Harlem'' offers poetic musings and deeply personal thoughts of a 
complex young man in search of a place for himself and his people. 
``So You Want To Be A Pro?'' shares with young people his views on 
discipline, coping with peer pressure, time management and the 
importance of education. 
</P>
<P>
	There's more.  
</P>
<P>
	McDaniels and his wife, Navvab, launched the ``Arts for Smarts''  
program, which acquaints thousands of disadvantaged kids with 
dance, theater and literature. He owns and operates a clothing 
business. Even something as common as an unpleasant trip to the 
dentist started the wheels spinning: He invented his own flavored 
gel, got it cleared through the Food and Drug Administration and 
put it on the market. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm an eclectic-type person,'' McDaniels said. ``I let myself  
do anything I want to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McDaniels, 31, signed with the Falcons after seven years in  
Kansas City, providing the NFC champions with some much-needed 
depth on the defensive line. It's the same role he played with the 
Chiefs, filling in wherever he was needed on a team that featured 
Neil Smith, Derrick Thomas and Chester McGlockton. 
</P>
<P>
	``I figured out a long time ago that if you wanted to do  
anything, you have to know more about it than anyone else,'' 
McDaniels said. ``I learned every position to get the job in Kansas 
City. Whenever I was called upon -- whether it was nose guard, left 
end or right end -- I had to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McDaniels' work ethic stems from the rejection he felt on draft  
day in 1990, when no team called despite a solid career at Oregon 
State. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was devastating,'' said McDaniels, who earned a degree in  
communications and political science. ``I thought I did everything 
right in college, in athletics and academics, and it just didn't 
pan out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He took a job selling health and beauty care products, but  
football was still in his blood. The following year, he played for 
the World League's Birmingham Fire, earning a tryout from the 
Philadelphia Eagles. Failing to make the team, he returned to 
Birmingham for another season in the minors. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, he earned a spot with the Chiefs in 1992.  
</P>
<P>
	``It all stems from not making it,'' McDaniels said. ``I feel  
blessed going to work every day. I don't take it for granted. It's 
a job, but this game has given me a lot. Confidence, for one. 
Self-esteem. A feeling of accomplishment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For him, the greatest feeling is discovering an opponent's  
weakness in the film room, then taking advantage of it on the 
field. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, for instance, he noticed the Steelers ran a sweep  
every time the tight end went in motion to that side of the field. 
During a Monday night game, he seized on that revelation to tackle 
Jerome Bettis in the backfield for a 7-yard loss. 
</P>
