<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Proposes `Pay-to-Play Rule' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators, imposing a $10,000 fine on  
a former board member of Florida's Housing Finance Agency accused 
of taking a bribe, also proposed Wednesday a rule to bar money 
managers from making campaign donations to officials who oversee 
public-employee pension funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The practice, known as pay-to-play, is legal but can unfairly  
tilt the political playing field, securities regulators and other 
critics say. They contend that thousands of police, firefighters, 
teachers and other public employees may be unwittingly entrusting 
their retirement savings to financial companies with the strongest 
political ties rather than those most qualified to manage the 
funds. 
</P>
<P>
	At stake is the management of such pension funds, which hold  
more than $2 trillion in assets nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	William Jay Ramsey, the former board member, is one of several  
public officials ensnared in a criminal investigation of alleged 
bribes that steered Florida municipal bond business to Stephens 
Inc., a prominent investment firm based in Little Rock, Ark. 
</P>
<P>
	The wide-ranging federal probe already has led to the criminal  
conviction of a former Arkansas state legislator who paid bribes to 
help the Stephens firm get two bond underwriting contracts in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	In a civil settlement with the U.S. Securities and Exchange  
Commission announced Wednesday, Ramsey agreed to pay the $10,000 
fine, return the compensation he allegedly received plus interest, 
a total of $2,190.03, and refrain from future violations of 
securities laws. 
</P>
<P>
	In the settlement, Ramsey neither admitted to nor denied the  
SEC's allegation that he failed to disclose having secretly agreed 
to receive from Stephens $1,500 a month for a year, though he 
allegedly only received one payment. The SEC said that the 1995 
payment was a bribe in return for Ramsey voting to select Stephens 
for bond underwriting business of the housing finance agency. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, federal criminal prosecutors secured an indictment  
against Ramsey on related charges. Stephens agreed the same month 
to pay $3.1 million to federal and north Florida officials to 
settle a civil suit, and the company was barred from underwriting 
bonds in Florida for five years. Stephens also agreed to pay a 
$2.25 million civil fine to the SEC. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramsey's attorney, David McGee of Pensacola, Fla., declined  
comment on the matter Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC's action shows the agency ``is continuing to  
aggressively investigate and bring enforcement actions in an effort 
to stamp out pay-to-play practices,'' Kathleen Hamm, an assistant 
enforcement director at the SEC, said in a telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	The rule proposed by the SEC would apply to legal campaign  
contributions to officials by money managers, which regulators want 
to stop on ethical grounds, as opposed to the illegal bribe that 
Ramsey allegedly received. But Ms. Hamm said both kinds of payments 
were examples of pay-to-play. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new proposal, which the SEC opened to a 75-day public  
comment period, money managers would be barred from making 
political donations to state and local officials who oversee 
public-employee pension funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Plaze, associate director of the SEC's investment management  
division, acknowledged that the proposed rule ``is not campaign 
finance reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not naive enough to expect that we're going to entirely  
eliminate pay-to-play,'' Plaze told reporters in a conference call. 
</P>
<P>
	The rule would prohibit money management firms with more than  
$25 million in assets under management from providing investment 
advice to public pension funds for two years after the firm, or any 
of its partners or executives, contributed to the campaigns of 
certain elected officials or candidates. Donations of $250 or less 
would be exempt. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, money management firms with government clients  
would be required to keep records of their political contributions. 
The records would not be made public but would be provided to SEC 
examiners. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC took similar action in 1994 with regard to the $1.3  
trillion municipal bond market, restricting how much money 
bond-underwriting firms can contribute to state and local 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Since that action, many bond underwriters have gotten around the  
municipal pay-to-play restrictions by making donations to political 
parties rather than particular state and local candidates. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
