<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 23:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Angels 4, Royals 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Ben Molina, playing his third major  
league game and first of the season, went 3-for-4 with two RBIs as 
the Anaheim Angels beat the Kansas City Royals 4-3 Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Molina, who went 0-for-1 last season, had an RBI double in the  
second, a run-scoring single in the fourth and in infield single in 
the fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Ken Hill (4-10) won for the first time in seven decisions,  
allowing three runs and five hits in 6 2-3 innings. The 
right-hander was lifted after surrendering an RBI single by Rey 
Sanchez that narrowed Anaheim's lead to a run. 
</P>
<P>
	Troy Percival pitched the ninth for his 25th save.  
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Huson also had three hits for the Angels, whose third  
victory in 19 games was tinged with another injury. Just two days 
after Jim Edmonds played for the first time this season following 
surgery on his right shoulder, first baseman Mo Vaughn sat out 
because of a staph infection in his right shin. 
</P>
<P>
	Anaheim scored two unearned runs in the second inning with the  
help of a pair of foul balls -- one that should have been caught and 
one that shouldn't have. 
</P>
<P>
	Darin Erstad, given a second chance when catcher Chad Kreuter  
misplayed his foul pop near the first base dugout, led off with a 
bloop single to left-center. Huson singled with one out and Molina 
doubled past a diving Jermaine Dye in right-center for his first 
big-league hit and RBI. 
</P>
<P>
	Orlando Palmeiro then got a gift sacrifice fly when Johnny Damon  
caught his foul ball in the left field corner and Huson scored 
easily. 
</P>
<P>
	Molina, batting in the ninth spot, increased Anaheim's margin to  
3-1 with an RBI single that chased Kansas City starter Jay Witasick 
(4-8). Two outs later, Molina scored on Garret Anderson's single. 
</P>
<P>
	Kansas City scored in the fourth on a leadoff double by Damon  
and a two-out single by Mike Sweeney, which extended his hitting 
streak to a career-best 17 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Witasick allowed four runs -- two earned -- and six hits in  
three-plus innings. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Molina, 25, was called up on Tuesday when 12-year veteran  
catcher Charlie O'Brien was designated for assignment. He batted 
.286 with seven home runs and 41 RBIs in 65 games at Triple-A 
Edmonton. ... Plate umpire Tim Tschida wasn't too thrilled about 
Orlando Palmeiro flinging his bat back toward home plate after 
taking a called third strike in the first inning -- until it was 
explained to him that on-deck hitter Gary DiSarcina was about to 
use the same bat. ... Everyone in the Angels' lineup used Edmonds' 
bat the first time through the order. His teammates went 4-for-7 
with a walk. ... DiSarcina went 0-for-3 and remained hitless in his 
last 21 at-bats. ... Witasick's problems could have stemmed from a 
one-hopper by Anderson that struck him just above his pitching 
elbow in the first inning. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
