<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 08:50:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Corn, Soybeans Extend Rally / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Corn and soybean futures extended their rally  
early today on the Chicago Board of Trade, while wheat futures also 
gained. 
</P>
<P>
	After initially opening lower, corn and soybeans moved higher as  
investors worried about recent yield losses from hot, dry weather 
across key growing states. Analysts continue to revise downward 
their estimates for final fall production after the government 
earlier this week reported steep drops in the condition of the 
crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat moved higher in step with corn and soybeans.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 3 1/4 cents to $2.91 a bushel;  
December corn rose 4 cents to $2.34 3/4 a bushel; December oats rose 
1 1/2 cents to $1.18 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans rose 14 1/2 cents to 
$4.93 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and lean hog futures were higher on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while pork bellies were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose .38 cent to 64.65 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .15 cent to 76.47 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs rose .82 cent to 50.52 cents a pound; August pork bellies rose 
2.28 cents to 61.90 cents a pound, while other contract months 
retreated. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 08:04:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Van Gogh Drawing Returned to Heir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- German officials returned a van Gogh drawing and  
two other pieces of art on Wednesday to the heir of a Jewish 
collector forced by the Nazis to sell the works for a fraction of 
their true value. 
</P>
<P>
	The van Gogh drawing, titled ``Olive Trees,'' has been in Berlin  
museums since 1935, the year the original owner, Max Silberberg, 
was forced to auction off his collection. 
</P>
<P>
	The drawing and two other pieces were the first from  
Silberberg's extensive collection returned to his only surviving 
heir, daughter-in-law Gerta Silberberg, now 85 and living in 
Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	``The return of these artistic and valuable drawings can send a  
signal'' for future returns of Jewish property, said Karl Brozik, 
director of the Conference of Jewish Material Claims against 
Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	The Claims Conference, which identified the van Gogh drawing in  
1997, has found at least 1,000 more pieces of art in former 
communist nations that were looted by the Nazis from Jewish owners. 
About half are in Berlin. 
</P>
<P>
	Silberberg, a factory owner in what was then Breslau,  
present-day Wroclaw in Poland, was forced to sell his art 
collection, house and eventually his factory. 
</P>
<P>
	The art alone would be valued at $60 million today, said Konrad  
Matschke, a Claims Conference spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an important collection of Impressionist and  
Expressionist art, including works by Cezanne and Pisarro,'' 
Matschke said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two more paintings from the Silberberg collection have been  
identified, one in the United States and one in Russia, Matschke 
said. Terms for a handover, however, have not been reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Returned with the van Gogh were two other pieces: a drawing by  
Caspar David Friedrich seized by the Nazis from Silberberg in 1940 
and a painting by Hans von Marees sold at the same 1935 auction. 
The painting is being loaned for an exhibit in Bremen. 
</P>
<P>
	Like the van Gogh, the other pieces had been in museums in  
Berlin and neighboring Brandenburg states under control of the 
Foundation for Prussian Cultural Collections. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerta Silberberg and her husband, Alfred, emigrated to Great  
Britain ``under difficult circumstances'' in 1937. Max Silberberg 
remained in Silesia and later died in a concentration camp. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 02:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McNown Joins Bears at Training Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PLATTEVILLE, Wis. (AP) -- Forget all those records Cade McNown  
set at UCLA. Never mind those two fourth-quarter touchdown drives 
against Stanford or that 24-point rally in the last 17 minutes 
against Oregon State. 
</P>
<P>
	The way McNown sees it, everything starts over in the NFL.  
</P>
<P>
	``The college part of my life is over. Most of the people in  
Chicago, most of the people around the country, haven't seen me 
play. I'm looking to make an impact with the Bears, and I'm 
starting now,'' he said Tuesday after practicing with the Chicago 
Bears for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	As far as first impressions go, the rookie did pretty well. His  
passes were quick and strong, and he probably could have gone deep 
if his receivers weren't in their 12th day of training camp. 
Instead of getting flustered or confused, he looked as if he'd been 
running the Bears' offense for weeks rather than minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	And when the coaches decided to use him in the goal-line drills,  
McNown's first pass went for a touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	``He came in, stepped right in and did what he had to do,''  
receiver Curtis Conway said. ``He's a big-play quarterback that 
will make plays. He kind of reminds me of a young Brett Favre 
because he's smart and he's chancy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears hope McNown will be just as successful as Favre, too.  
After making him the 12th pick in the draft, Chicago signed McNown 
to a contract that could pay him up to $22 million over five years. 
The initial deal, signed Monday, is for seven years and $15 
million, but there are two voidable years and the possibility of an 
additional $7 million in incentives. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he arrived at training camp about a week and a half after  
his teammates, missing the heat and humidity that made life almost 
unbearable last week, McNown got a warm welcome in the locker room 
Tuesday morning. Teammates were quick to say hello, and coach Dick 
Jauron stopped by to say he was happy to see him. 
</P>
<P>
	As he left the field after his first practice, he walked with  
Shane Matthews, whose time as the Bears' No. 1 quarterback is now 
almost done. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like I'm trying to come out here and prove something  
right away,'' McNown said. ``I just need to learn, and everybody 
knows that. I think most of these guys are concerned with bettering 
themselves. They're not thinking about me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNown can take some of the credit for his warm-and-fuzzy  
welcome. When Curtis Enis arrived at camp last year after his 
holdout, he was out of shape and way behind, and it took weeks for 
him to learn the offense. 
</P>
<P>
	McNown, on the other hand, hired a personal trainer and worked  
out twice a day. He studied his playbook, memorizing what of the 
offense he learned during minicamps. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a very confident person, I think everybody sees that,''  
quarterbacks coach John Shoop said. ``He wants to take every rep. 
He just showed up today, but he'd have taken every single rep if we 
put him in for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNown isn't expected to play in Saturday's exhibition opener  
against the Indianapolis Colts, but that will probably be the last 
time he spends any significant time on the bench. He may not be 
very big, but he's got a strong arm and more mobility than many 
other quarterbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	More importantly, Jauron said, he's got a great mind.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's gifted physically, but his attitude and his mental  
abilities are what have made him special in college and what we 
hope will make him special here,'' Jauron said. ``He's got a great 
belief in his ability to compete with anybody -- probably in 
anything, I'd guess -- and come out on top. 
</P>
<P>
	``He feels like he can win all the time. That's the kind of guy  
you want in your huddle controlling your offensive football team. 
So we're happy he's here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
