<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Murder Conviction Overturned in Mo. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Ellen Reasonover missed the preschool plays,  
kissing scraped knees and the other joys and tribulations of 
motherhood. Now she's hoping to make up for lost time. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Reasonover, 42, was released from prison Tuesday, one day  
after a federal judge overturned her 1983 murder conviction. She 
said she was eager to renew life with her 18-year-old daughter, 
Charmelle Buford, who was 2 when Ms. Reasonover went to prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a dream come true,'' Ms. Reasonover said, crying and  
shaking as she left prison. ``I always kept faith, and I believe 
one day my innocence would be proven.'' 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis County Prosecutor Robert McCulloch said Wednesday he  
will not refile charges -- though he still believes Ms. Reasonover 
was involved in the crime -- unless further evidence surfaces. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury convicted Ms. Reasonover in 1983 shooting a 19-year-old  
man during a botched robbery attempt at a gas station. She could 
have received the death penalty -- if she had, she probably would 
have already been executed -- but was sentenced to life in prison. 
She would not have been eligible for parole until 2033. 
</P>
<P>
	No witnesses saw her and no fingerprints were found. But when  
she called police with a tip and gave a phony name, she became a 
prime suspect. Then two jail informants supplied key testimony 
against her. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Jean C. Hamilton overturned the conviction  
after a weeklong hearing in which Ms. Reasonover's attorney 
presented new evidence, including a tape-recorded conversation that 
contradicted the testimony of the jailhouse informers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
