<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Chemical Awaits Settlement News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Dow Chemical Co. has a big stake in whether a federal judge  
will approve a $3.2 billion settlement for 170,000 women with 
silicone breast implants. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement is part of a $4.5 billion bankruptcy  
reorganization plan for Dow Corning Corp., which is owned 50-50 by 
Dow Chemical and Corning Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Corning filed for bankruptcy court protection from its  
creditors in 1995 after thousands of women sued the company, saying 
their silicone breast implants had caused various health problems. 
The company no longer makes implants. 
</P>
<P>
	Hearings on the plan ended Friday. U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Arthur  
Spector, who must rule on whether the plan should take effect, has 
given no indication when such a decision might come. 
</P>
<P>
	Spector said he would focus on one the most contentious parts of  
the settlement -- a provision that bars further lawsuits against Dow 
Chemical and Corning over silicone breast implants. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those objecting to the plan are 49 women with implants  
from Nevada. The Nevada Supreme Court upheld a civil decision 
against Dow Chemical, and lawyers for the women argue the proposed 
settlement unfairly takes away their right to sue. 
</P>
<P>
	A Nevada woman won a $4.2 million verdict against Dow Chemical  
last year, saying the company was liable for her health problems 
because it tested silicone products for Dow Corning in the 1960s. 
Her case, later settled, is the only one of its kind to be upheld 
so far. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
