<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Recalling Union Carbide's Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Many people know about Union Carbide Corp. only through the  
worst industrial accident ever. 
</P>
<P>
	A subsidiary of Union Carbide operated a chemical plant in  
Bhopal, India, which released a deadly cloud of toxic gas the night 
of Dec. 2, 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Overnight, the cloud of methyl isocyanate killed 4,000 people in  
an adjacent shantytown. Thousands more died later from exposure to 
the fumes, a court in Bhopal has ruled. Estimates of the death toll 
in the 15 years since the leak range as high as 15,000; tens of 
thousands more suffer health effects including cataracts, lung 
diseases, cancer and gynecological disorders. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1989, Danbury, Conn.-based Union Carbide paid $470 million --  
one- twelfth of India's original claim -- in an out-of-court 
settlement that guaranteed immunity from prosecution for company 
executives. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indian Supreme Court later struck down the immunity  
provision, while allowing the financial settlement to stand. But 
few victims enjoyed quick access to the money, which was tied up in 
a convoluted claims process. 
</P>
<P>
	Union Carbide has said its investigation of the leak points to  
sabotage by a disgruntled employee. 
</P>
<P>
	Victims and their relatives have sought criminal charges against  
Warren Anderson, who was chairman of Union Carbide at the time of 
the disaster. The Indian government has repeatedly refused to act 
on victims' demands for Anderson's extradition. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
