<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stranded Sailors Finally Go Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- After a nearly yearlong ordeal aboard  
a ship stranded off the coasts of Mexico and Texas, Capt. Maqsood 
Ahmed is finally going home, empty-handed but not downhearted. 
</P>
<P>
	He's going to get to see his 2 1/2-year-old daughter, who was 6  
months old when he left Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to pick her up and hug her,'' he said. ``I want to  
see what she looks like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, with the help of charities, Ahmed and four others  
flew to Houston on the first leg of their journey home. They were 
the last of the 23 crew members from the freighter Delta Pride to 
be leaving Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Delta Pride was stranded off the coast of Tampico, Mexico,  
beginning in May 1998, because the Pakistani company that owned it 
went bankrupt. A financial dispute with Mexican officials led to 
the seizure of the ship's documents and the crew's passports. 
</P>
<P>
	The seamen lived off rain water and whatever fish they could  
catch, but developed signs of scurvy and had no clean water for 
bathing. 
</P>
<P>
	Last November, after Ahmed found a $10 bill in a drawer and was  
inspired by the words ``In God We Trust,'' the desperate crew used 
the last of their fuel to sail the derelict ship 300 miles to the 
Texas coast. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Tuesday that if he had not found that bill, ``I would  
not be alive today. I would have died.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, because of their lack of papers, they sat off the Texas  
coast for several more months. 
</P>
<P>
	The 740-foot freighter was finally auctioned as scrap for  
$300,000. The last crew members came ashore in March. 
</P>
<P>
	The men had been waiting to receive their wages from the auction  
proceeds, but that money is still tied up in legal disputes, so 
they finally decided to go home. 
</P>
<P>
	First Officer Shamshad Ahmed said his wife and six children, two  
of whom are in college, have been borrowing money to survive. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they are in very bad shape,'' he said. ``We didn't  
send a single penny back to them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
