<HEADLINE> Sega, AT&AMP;T Unveil Dreamcast Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Owners of Sega's long-awaited Dreamcast  
video game console will be able to challenge gamers across the 
street or across the country, using a built-in modem and AT&AMP;T 
Corp.'s Internet service 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T and Sega announced a deal Wednesday making AT&AMP;T the  
preferred partner for hooking Dreamcast to the Internet. However 
those who are already online using a different Internet service 
provider will also be able to connect to the Sega Dreamcast 
Network. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dreamcast and its built-in 56k modem will list for $199.99  
when it is released domestically on Sept. 9. Sega says 200,000 
consoles have already been pre-sold in the U.S., the strongest 
launch ever for a video game console. Sega has sold more than 1 
million units in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Users of the Sega Network Web site will also have access to chat  
rooms, bulletin boards and e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sounds like a good vote of confidence for Dreamcast from  
AT&AMP;T,'' said analyst Sean McGowan of Gerard Klauer Mattison in New 
York. ``It's a good way for AT&AMP;T to get into Internet gaming 
without a large capital investment.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
