<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McGwire Says He Hasn't Taken Andro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Mark McGwire, adamant in spring training that  
he would keep taking androstenedione, disclosed Wednesday he has 
not used the over-the-counter dietary supplement for four months. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire made the revelation before his St. Louis Cardinals  
played the San Diego Padres. Hours later, he hit his 499th career 
home run and 42nd of the season, tying Sammy Sosa for the major 
league lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought long and hard about it and I don't like the way it  
was portrayed like I was the endorser of the product, which I 
wasn't,'' McGwire said. ``I don't like how it's portrayed, but 
young kids take it because of me. I don't like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire said the fact his record 70-homer season in 1998 was  
linked to andro, a testosterone booster, likely encouraged 
youngsters to try it. That was perhaps the biggest reason for his 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``I discourage young people from taking it,'' he said. ``If  
you're old enough and you have your own mind, you can do whatever 
you want.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Androstenedione is metabolized into testosterone, which is  
considered a steroid. It is banned by the Olympics, the NCAA, the 
NFL, and the men's and women's tennis tours though it is permitted 
in baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire's admission that he used andro sparked a tenfold  
increase in sales of the supplement last fall, much of it through 
the Internet, and led many steroid experts to warn of serious 
health consequences for teen-agers who take it to emulate McGwire. 
</P>
<P>
	Major league baseball has commissioned a study of andro by  
Harvard scientists. No decision is expected until later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Last August, McGwire acknowledged to The Associated Press that  
he had used andro for more than a year. Colorado's Dante Bichette 
was among a group of other players who said they took it. 
</P>
<P>
	As spring training opened this year, McGwire said andro was  
legal and that it had ``absolutely nothing to do with me hitting a 
baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said then he took it to get through late-season workouts.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't endorse the product and I never did,'' he said then.  
``Someone stuck their nose in my locker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire's recent statistics appear to show that he's fine  
without andro. Including Wednesday's shot, he has homered 15 times 
in 19 games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0346 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 18:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Removing Predators Has Consequences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	House cats and other small animals are becoming the dominant  
predators in many of San Diego's rugged canyons, replacing wild 
coyotes that were driven away by urban development, according to a 
new study. 
</P>
<P>
	Because cats, opossums, skunks and raccoons are no longer preyed  
on, they are free to eat more rodents and birds, threatening their 
populations, said biologist Kevin Crooks, co-author of the study in 
Thursday's journal Nature. 
</P>
<P>
	``Predators like coyotes are often persecuted by humans, but  
they can have important ecological roles,'' Crooks said. 
``Sometimes you can't predict what kind of roles they play until 
they disappear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For two years, Crooks and his colleagues surveyed about 30 of  
San Diego's rugged canyons that are rural oases in the sea of the 
city's urban expansion. 
</P>
<P>
	They found that where coyotes still live, dead felines were  
found in most of those areas and 21 percent of coyote droppings 
contained cat remains. 
</P>
<P>
	But when the coyote threat disappears, more felines are allowed  
to roam and hunt on their own. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one has really looked at this particular relationship  
before,'' said Lee McClenaghan, professor of biology at San Diego 
State University. ``It shows if you destroy habitat and remove 
components of an ecosystem, effects are seen throughout.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0347 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 15:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Nomination Clears Hurdle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After 14 months, the Senate moved closer  
Wednesday to confirming Richard Holbrooke as U.N. ambassador when 
the final senator blocking the nomination lifted his objections. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa., said he would fight an unrelated  
battle with the State Department in other ways, calling it ``not a 
personal dispute'' with Holbrooke. ``I intend to vote for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That removed the final obstacle to a Senate vote confirming  
President Clinton's nomination of the veteran diplomat. 
</P>
<P>
	But it created new problems for other diplomatic nominees.  
Grassley said he instead would block three other pending 
nominations, including that of Peter Burleigh as ambassador to the 
Philippines. 
</P>
<P>
	Burleigh has been filling in for Holbrooke at the United Nations  
since last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials from both parties said they expected the combative  
Balkans negotiator to be confirmed overwhelmingly with only brief 
floor debate -- despite the long delays and problems that have 
dogged him until now. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke, an investment banker, is a former ambassador to  
Germany and was architect of the 1995 accord that ended the war in 
Bosnia. He also has served as Clinton's special envoy in the Kosovo 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton announced the nomination in June 1998. But it quickly  
became tangled, first in internal Justice and State Department 
investigations into Holbrooke's contacts with former State 
Department colleagues and then in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley announced he was releasing a ``hold'' that had  
prevented a Senate vote on Holbrooke. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Grassley said he was transferring the delaying tactics  
to three other ambassadorial appointments. 
</P>
<P>
	Three others had also sought to block the nomination -- Majority  
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky, and Sen. 
George Voinovich, R-Ohio -- but they earlier abandoned the tactics. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Senate tradition, any member without explanation may block  
action on legislation or a nomination for as long as the majority 
leader permits. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley used the technique to protest the State Department's  
treatment of a whistleblower, Linda Shenwick. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley said that the dispute continues but that he no longer  
wants to hold up the long-delayed Holbrooke nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he said he was switching his ``holds'' to Burleigh and  
two other nominees: Carl Spielvogel to be ambassador to the Slovak 
Republic and Richard Fredericks to be ambassador to Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley contends that Shenwick, who worked at the U.N. mission  
in New York, was demoted and transferred to a lesser job in 
Washington in retaliation for her telling members of Congress about 
waste and inefficiency at the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department has said Shenwick was reassigned because of  
unsatisfactory job performance, not because she was a 
whistleblower. 
</P>
<P>
	``My interest in this matter is very simple,'' Grassley said.  
``Congress cannot function as an institution if government 
employees cannot communicate with Congress about wrongdoing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The executive branch should not be allowed to shoot the  
messenger,'' he said. He said he wanted to make sure ``the process 
for Ms. Shenwick remains fair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley also said he had taken ``additional steps which I  
choose not to disclose at this time. They are designed to increase 
my and other interested colleagues' ability to insist that Ms. 
Shenwick be treated fairly.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 07:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spielberg Getting Award From Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- He has won countless awards as a filmmaker.  
Now Steven Spielberg is being feted for his humanitarian works. 
</P>
<P>
	The man behind films including ``Schindler's List'' and ``Saving  
Private Ryan'' will be awarded the James Smithson Bicentennial 
Medal by The Smithsonian Associates at an Aug. 11 ceremony in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The Smithsonian Institution, composed of museums, galleries and  
research facilities, was established in 1846 with money bequeathed 
to the United States by Smithson, a British scientist. 
</P>
<P>
	The award in his name is given each year to individuals who have  
made contributions to areas of interest to the Smithsonian. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am both surprised and deeply honored to be designated for  
such a prestigious medal from an institution that is a national and 
international treasure,'' Spielberg said in a statement released by 
the Smithsonian. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to film credits, Spielberg has established the  
Righteous Persons Foundation, a grant-making organization dedicated 
to strengthening Jewish life. He also established Survivors of the 
Shoah Visual History Foundation in order to preserve the personal 
stories of survivors, and through them the victims, of the 
Holocaust. 
</P>
<P>
	Past award recipients include the late ocean explorer Jacques  
Cousteau, former first lady Lady Bird Johnson, filmmaker George 
Lucas and television newsman Walter Cronkite. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0349 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 15:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Canes, Primeau Still at Stalemate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- There has been no movement on a new  
contract for Carolina Hurricanes captain Keith Primeau as the start 
of training camp looms a month away. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest offer to the all-star center this week was rejected  
by agent Don Reynolds. The Carolina offer to the restricted free 
agent was believed to have been a five-year package averaging $4 
million a season. Primeau made $2 million last season. 
</P>
<P>
	The sides have not talked face-to-face or on the telephone in  
more than a month. The latest offer was rejected by fax. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a game to be playing cat-and-mouse at this  
point,'' Carolina general manager Jim Rutherford said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Reynolds has refused to say what Primeau, 27, is seeking, but it  
is believed to be more than the $5 million a year teammate Ron 
Francis received as an unrestricted free agent last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one thing I've learned in this process based on some of  
the comments is it looks like I'm not supposed to sign any free 
agents -- like Ronnie Francis,'' Rutherford said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That has been held against me, `Well, if Ronnie Francis got  
this I should get this too.' Well, if that's the case then I should 
tell the players in training camp I'm not going to try to improve 
the team. I don't think that is a fair bargaining chip, but I've 
heard that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-5, 220-pound Primeau, who scored a team-leading 30  
goals last season, could have filed for salary arbitration by July 
15, but elected not to. Now, his leverage is to hold out. 
</P>
<P>
	Reynolds said Wednesday that Primeau is the sixth or seventh  
best center in the NHL, and should be paid accordingly. 
</P>
<P>
	``He brings as much to the table as any center in the league,''  
Reynolds said. ``Is he the top guy? No, he's not the top guy, but 
he's got to be coming up next after the first few centers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If that's the case, Rutherford insisted Primeau should have  
filed for arbitration. 
</P>
<P>
	``He (Reynolds) should have told an arbitrator that,''  
Rutherford said. ``That seems to me it would have been the fairest 
way to resolve this. Whether he's right or wrong where he has Keith 
slotted, it doesn't matter, Keith is now going to be slotted into 
our payroll and our structure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Primeau has 406 career points in 597 games. However, he has been  
a major disappointment during the postseason, scoring only six 
goals in 70 career playoff games with Detroit and Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Rutherford said he would welcome Primeau to training camp Sept.  
5 even if he's not signed. Two unsigned players came to camp last 
year -- defensemen Nolan Pratt and Steve Halko -- and both were 
signed within a week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most teams in the NHL have a policy that unsigned players  
can't come to training camp. That is not our policy,'' said 
Rutherford. ``I feel that when a player does sign he has to be 
ready to play. To tell a player not to come to camp and keep up 
conditioning on his own I don't think is fair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a restricted free agent, Carolina has the right to match any  
offer for Primeau or risk losing him for a series of No. 1 draft 
picks. So far, no team has given Primeau a contract offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Rutherford also said he has fielded no trade offers for his star  
center. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0350 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 15:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Backs Gore 100 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAMESTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton said Wednesday  
that Vice President Al Gore is ``the best partner any president has 
ever had'' and that she will do whatever she can to support his bid 
for the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could not be more strongly in support of his campaign and  
the kind of president he would be for this country,'' Mrs. Clinton 
said during a campaign stop in Jamestown. The first lady is 
exploring a possible run for the Democratic Senate nomination in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will do whatever I can in whatever way is open to me in  
supporting his candidacy because I truly believe he would be the 
best person we could have to lead our country into this new 
century,'' Mrs. Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she was ``absolutely 100 percent behind the vice  
president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A statewide poll released this week by the Quinnipiac College  
Polling Institute showed Gore leading his only Democratic opponent, 
Bill Bradley. But in one-on-one matchups with the Republican 
front-runner, George W. Bush, Gore was in a statistical dead heat 
with the Texas governor while Bradley was ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	New York is considered a must-win state for the Democrats if  
they are to retain the White House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
