<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Korean IOC Official Mum on Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A powerful South Korean member of the  
International Olympic Committee is ``not too concerned'' about tax 
fraud allegations that have been linked to his son, a spokesman 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first criminal case stemming from the U.S. federal  
investigation into Salt Lake City's winning bid for the 2002 Winter 
Olympics, which has been tainted by alleged influence-peddling. 
</P>
<P>
	A businessman from Utah admitted Tuesday that he had helped John  
Kim, the son of Kim Un-yong, obtain permanent U.S. resident status 
by setting up a sham job at his now-defunct communications company. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Kim Un-yong cannot comment until he reviews all the  
details on the case,'' his chief secretary, Baek Sung-il, said in 
Seoul. ``But he is not too concerned about the latest 
development.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kim, an IOC executive member, has denied any wrongdoing in the  
bidding scandal. Critics allege Salt Lake City officials illegally 
tried to influence Olympic delegates into awarding them the 2002 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	The businessman, David E. Simmons, has admitted that he used  
fake contracts and phony invoices to conceal the fact that John 
Kim's salary was being paid by the Salt Lake City Olympic Bid 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim has previously said the money Simmons paid his son was for  
consulting and other services and had nothing to do with the 
Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC official has said any deal between Simmons and the Salt  
Lake City bid committee was kept secret from his family. 
</P>
<P>
	The Salt Lake City scandal has never loomed large in South  
Korea, where senior government officials are routinely jailed on 
bribery charges. It has received little coverage in the news media. 
</P>
<P>
	President Kim Dae-jung's office said it was following Kim's case  
but there has been no probe or questioning by the South Korean 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the Culture and Tourism Ministry, which oversees  
sports affairs, said they didn't know enough about the case to 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC's own investigation in March gave Kim Un-yong a ``severe  
warning'' for his conduct, but stopped short of harsher sanctions 
in the inquiry that led to an unprecedented 10 expulsions or 
resignations. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim was a key organizer of the 1988 Seoul Olympics. He is  
president of the South Korean Olympic Committee, the World 
Taekwondo Federation and the General Assembly of International 
Sports Federations. 
</P>
<P>
	He is an influential power broker in the IOC, and has been cited  
as a candidate to replace Juan Antonio Samaranch as IOC chief in 
2001. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
