<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Blazer Smith Wants To Win Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Steve Smith, apparently expendable to the  
Atlanta Hawks, seems a perfect fit for the Portland Trail Blazers. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith gets a chance to play for a proven winner, whose deep  
roster allows him to lessen the pounding on his aching knees. The 
Blazers, meanwhile, get a veteran scorer who might be the missing 
piece to reaching the NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been going to the playoffs, but never got past the second  
round,'' Smith said Wednesday, two days after the Hawks traded him 
and Ed Gray to Portland for Isaiah Rider and Jim Jackson. ``And for 
me, the only thing is to win. That was a place I really wanted to 
go, somewhere where they're committed to winning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, 30, has averaged 18.6 points a game and nearly 37 minutes  
the past five seasons. That certainly will change next season with 
the Blazers, a team that won the Pacific Division title and 
advanced to the Western Conference finals with loads of talent but 
no dominant leader. The team's top scorer, Rider, averaged fewer 
than 14 points a game. 
</P>
<P>
	Playing fewer minutes is just fine with Smith, who hopes to  
extend his contract before the last four years of the deal -- which 
will pay him $36 million -- are up. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after the Blazers announced the trade Monday, they  
finalized the signing of 36-year-old free agent Detlef Schrempf, 
who took Portland's middle-class exception of $4.2 million over two 
years after flatly turning down Seattle's offer to re-sign for one 
year and $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``You look at me and Detlef coming in, you hope you're the two  
pieces that get them over the hump,'' Smith said. ``I'm a veteran 
who's been there, and who's hungry. I think sometimes when you have 
a veteran who's won a championship, you're just going out there and 
playing. I'm very hungry to win a championship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All of the Blazers talked about putting aside their egos for the  
good of the team last season, but at times the party line didn't 
hold. Point guard Damon Stoudamire grumbled on several occasions 
about not playing more in the fourth quarter, and he was ripped for 
speaking out on the subject during the Western Conference finals 
against San Antonio. And Jackson reportedly got into an argument 
with coach Mike Dunleavy over the same issue after Game 3 of the 
Spurs' four-game sweep. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Smith sees the team as having its priorities in place.  
</P>
<P>
	``When it's time to win, you've got to put your stats aside,''  
he said. ``Everybody who played here last year sacrificed his 
stats. It really impressed me that every guy wanted to win. That's 
what really made me happy to get a chance to come here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, ever diplomatic, said he didn't think the Hawks gave up  
on him because of his surgically repaired knees. He said the team 
``just went in another direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I pretty much can't tell you why it was that they never gave  
me a definitive reason, but I'm just happy to be here,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
