<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 07:56:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Asks FCC To Justify Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An appeals court ordered the Federal  
Communications Commission on Tuesday to justify continuing to make 
broadcasters give air time to opposing viewpoints, given the 
skyrocketing growth of other media outlets. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Broadcasters and the  
Radio-Television News Directors Association had asked the U.S. 
Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia to scrap the 
decades-old rules requiring people be given on-air opportunities to 
respond to personal attacks and political editorials. 
</P>
<P>
	The two groups argued that FCC regulations are unconstitutional  
and are no longer needed given the growth of cable, satellite TV 
and the Internet as sources of news and information. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-judge Court of Appeals panel returned the issue to the  
commission to give it ``an opportunity to provide an adequate 
justification for retaining the rules. The court asked the FCC to 
act quickly, but left open the possibility the commission could 
reconsider or modify the rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``The FCC must therefore explain its rationale for these rules  
in more detail, thereby permitting the court to test that rationale 
against petitioners' factual assertions and, if necessary, the 
demands of the First Amendment,'' the court wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's political editorial rule requires TV and radio  
stations that endorse a political candidate to notify and give free 
rebuttal time to the candidate's opponent. Stations that oppose a 
candidate must notify and give that candidate free time to respond. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's personal attack rule requires TV and radio stations  
that assault the honesty, character or integrity of a person or 
group as part of a controversial story to give that person or group 
free rebuttal time. 
</P>
<P>
	Public interest groups contend the rules ensure that the public  
has some access to the airwaves. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0365 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 14:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't Approves New Cancer Drug Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Patients with suspicious chest X-rays are  
getting a new test to help determine if they need a biopsy for lung 
cancer: The government approved a drug Wednesday that can literally 
light up cancerous cells. 
</P>
<P>
	Diatide Inc.'s NeoTect will not replace biopsies in which lung  
tissue is surgically removed to definitively diagnose cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	But because NeoTect works differently than other noninvasive  
cancer tests, ``it is a very valuable tool'' for deciding which 
patients need a biopsy, said Dr. Florence Houn of the Food and Drug 
Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	About 171,000 Americans will be diagnosed with lung cancer this  
year, and about 159,000 will die, the American Cancer Society 
estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	NeoTect is for patients whose chest X-rays or CT scans show a  
mass that doctors cannot determine is benign or cancerous. 
Sometimes mere scars, for instance, appear suspicious. 
</P>
<P>
	Many types of lung cancer produce a protein called somatostatin.  
NeoTect is injected into the arm and travels to the lungs, where it 
detects somatostatin by latching onto somatostatin ``receptors,'' 
or docking points, on cancer cells. NeoTect carries a radioactive 
label that lights up the cancer under a common nuclear-medicine 
camera. 
</P>
<P>
	There are other noninvasive tools to help doctors decide who  
needs a biopsy. NeoTect appears as accurate as one well-regarded 
test, the PET scan, said Dr. Neal Rinne of Cigna Healthcare of 
Arizona. But PET scanning equipment is so expensive that in many 
parts of the country, the scans simply aren't available, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The NeoTect can be done at a lower cost, and done in small  
towns,'' because it merely requires a common nuclear-medicine 
camera, Rinne said. 
</P>
<P>
	NeoTect can be wrong, Houn cautioned. It was about 70 percent  
accurate in detecting cancer, and 79 percent to 86 percent accurate 
in pinpointing patients who truly were cancer-free, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus, NeoTect is not a stand-alone cancer test, the FDA  
stressed. 
</P>
<P>
	Although studies showed NeoTect was safe, patients will get  
standard warnings to be careful about sanitation after receiving a 
radioactive medicine. Most of NeoTect's radioactive ingredient is 
flushed out of the body in urine within four hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Diatide said NeoTect would cost approximately $500, about $1,500  
cheaper than the PET scan. The company said shipments to doctors 
would begin soon. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0366 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 09:10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Verdict Thrown Out in 1971 Riot Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An appeals court has overturned more than $4  
million in jury awards to two former Attica inmates who claimed 
they were tortured by guards after the deadliest prison riot in 
U.S. history. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said Tuesday a lower court  
judge in Buffalo improperly instructed two juries before they 
returned verdicts in favor of former inmates Frank Smith and David 
Brosig in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel angry. I'm bitter. I'm disappointed, but I'm  
re-energized because I'm a fighter. I'm not a quitter,'' Smith 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith had been awarded $4 million by a jury while another  
awarded Brosig $75,000. The jury trials for damages were held after 
a previous jury found that Karl Pfeil, a former assistant deputy 
superintendent at Attica, was liable for the mistreatment of the 
inmates. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Pfeil's lawyers, Randy Rucinski, said the appeals court  
was correct. ``We're very happy with the result. We consider it a 
victory,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, who had been serving a term for armed robbery, was one of  
the inmates most brutally beaten after the Sept. 9, 1971, uprising 
in which more than 1,200 inmates at Attica seized parts of the 
prison for several days. The prison was taken back in a raid that 
killed 10 hostages and 29 prisoners. 
</P>
<P>
	Testimony showed prison supervisors were aware that after the  
uprising, guards had misconceptions about how inmates had treated 
their hostages but that the supervisors did nothing to correct the 
guards' erroneous impressions. The hostages, it turned out, had 
died from friendly fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, now 66, said he was beaten, threatened with death, forced  
to walk across broken glass and burned with cigarette butts and 
shell casings. He said that experience left him with posttraumatic 
stress disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, the appeals court found that the juries  
considering damages were improperly permitted to revisit many of 
the same issues already considered by the liability jury. The 
appeals court suggested that the case be reassigned to a judge 
``best able to expedite its resolution.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990804.0367 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 14:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Corn, Soybean Prices Rise Again  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans advanced to their highest levels in months  
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid concern upcoming rains 
will provide little relief to water-starved crops. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, orange juice futures also jumped, as did  
energy futures. 
</P>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures advanced strongly a third day as  
private forecasters joined the National Weather Service in calling 
for widespread Midwestern rains over the next 10 days. But those 
meteorologists said actual rainfall totals will be light in the 
states that need the moisture most, including Illinois, Iowa, 
Indiana and Nebraska. 
</P>
<P>
	Hot, dry weather has taken its toll particularly in Illinois,  
one of the largest growing states, and Indiana. The government 
reported earlier this week that crop conditions had deteriorated 
sharply as young corn and soybean plants baked under temperatures 
that topped 100 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	While corn and soybean harvests likely will remain quite large,  
the reductions could come at a fortuitous time. Demand to Asia, a 
key exporting region for U.S. producers, is on the rise as 
countries there shake off economic problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 5 cents to $3.06 1/4 a bushel;  
December corn rose 5 3/4 cents to $2.36 1/2 a bushel; December oats rose 
1 1/4 cents to $1.18 1/4 a bushel; November soybeans rose 15 3/4 cents to 
$4.94 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Orange juice futures rose sharply on the Board of Trade of the  
City of New York, the parent of the New York Cotton Exchange, amid 
concern that hot weather in Florida could reduce the crop there. 
</P>
<P>
	Extreme heat could take its toll on the crop for a second year.  
Last year's crop production fell by 24 percent from a record 244 
million boxes the year before. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants were bracing for the worst ahead of  
influential crop forecaster Elizabeth Steger's first production 
estimate, which is due next Thursday. That report comes two months 
before the USDA releases its first estimate for new production. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices also may have received a boost from word that a male  
Oriental fruit fly had been found north of Orlando, Fla. The pest 
damages crops, but sightings have been sporadic since it was first 
discovered in the region in May. 
</P>
<P>
	September frozen concentrated orange juice rose 1.65 cents to  
81.65 cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy futures advanced in a volatile trading session on the New  
York Mercantile Exchange as investors digested a report that Russia 
plans no gasoline exports during the month of August. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's Fuel and Energy Ministry said all gasoline produced by  
Russian companies would be supplied only to the domestic market in 
a move aimed at preventing illegal exports. Exports of fuel oil and 
diesel also were to be cut. 
</P>
<P>
	The move could further tighten world inventories and comes just  
as the U.S. Energy Department reported gasoline and crude 
inventories last week fell more sharply than expected. An American 
Petroleum Institute report a day earlier had indicated gasoline 
supplies rose. 
</P>
<P>
	September crude rose 14 cents to $20.44 a barrel; September  
unleaded gasoline rose .92 cent to 63.94 cents a gallon; September 
heating oil rose .73 cent to 53.02 cents a gallon; September 
natural gas rose 4.4 cents to $2.642 for each 1,000 cubic feet. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
