<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Court Asked To Enforce Prop 187 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Sponsors of a voter-approved ban on  
education and public services for illegal immigrants have asked a 
federal appeals court to allow enforcement of the initiative. 
</P>
<P>
	The move comes less than a week after Gov. Gray Davis said he  
had settled a lawsuit by dropping the state's appeal of a court 
ruling that declared most of Proposition 187 unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the governor abandoned the defense of Proposition 187,  
the will of the people was frustrated,'' the Pacific Legal 
Foundation, a pro-187 group, said Wednesday in papers filed with 
the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	Proposition 187, approved five years ago by 59 percent of the  
voters, would deny public education, social services and 
non-emergency health care to illegal immigrants, who were already 
ineligible for most health and welfare benefits under federal law. 
</P>
<P>
	In a final legal attempt to revive the ballot measure, the  
foundation argued that there is no longer any legal ``controversy'' 
between the state and opponents of Proposition 187. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the Constitution allows federal courts to hear only  
cases involving controversies between opposing parties, the judge's 
ruling should be withdrawn and the suit dismissed, the foundation 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The request, if granted, would require opponents to file a new  
suit and give supporters of the initiative a chance to defend it in 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	Pro-187 groups stayed out of the previous case, deferring to  
then-Gov. Pete Wilson and then-Attorney General Dan Lungren, and 
were turned down when they sought later to intervene. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
