<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oklahomans Reclaim Murrah Plaza </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- The outdoor plaza next to the Oklahoma City  
federal building -- used as a makeshift treatment center for victims 
in the deadly 1995 bombing -- was to reopen Thursday as a spot where 
workers once again can enjoy brown bag lunches. 
</P>
<P>
	Sounds of water cascading over a granite fountain can be heard  
by those who stop for a rest or observe progress in the 
construction of the Oklahoma National Memorial. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it'll be great when I can bring my lunch tomorrow and  
get used to enjoying it,'' bombing survivor Paul Heath, a 
psychologist at the Veteran's Administration, said of the Alfred P. 
Murrah Federal Building Plaza. 
</P>
<P>
	The Memorial construction can be viewed through a low glass wall  
on the north side of an observation platform on the plaza, which is 
adjacent to where the Murrah building once stood. Trees and plants 
have been planted, selected to closely match the original 
landscaping. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the most peaceful thing I've ever seen in an urban  
area,'' George Hozendorf, special assistant to the regional 
administrator of the General Services Administation, said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I loved it. I appreciated that they tried to put back the  
original,'' said Jim Denny, father of survivors Brandon and Rebecca 
who were in the day-care center at the time of the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Denny said so many times he would pick up the children from the  
center and spend time in the area. The playground area of the 
day-care center has been preserved behind a fence in the corner of 
the plaza. 
</P>
<P>
	Fences around the remainder of the plaza were scheduled to come  
down Thursday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The fence has been a focal point for visitors at the bombing  
site. Many have left mementos in memory of the 168 people who died. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the plaza is not a memorial, the planners were mindful  
of the meaning it would have to Oklahomans, and the proximity to 
the memorial. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not being able to bring someone back doesn't rob you from  
having the opportunity of experiencing the positive memory of those 
people when you walk around on the plaza,'' Heath said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
