<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shannon Sharpe Injured in Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Shannon Sharpe's disaster Down Under  
just got a whole lot worse. 
</P>
<P>
	The Denver Broncos tight end suffered an ankle strain Thursday  
and is in doubt for the exhibition game against San Diego on 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharpe has been the most vocal critic of the NFL's decision to  
take the American Bowl to Australia for the first time because of 
the distance the teams were required to travel. 
</P>
<P>
	While Broncos coach Mike Shanahan believes the injury is little  
more than a minor strain, Sharpe was fuming after being forced to 
miss half of the practice session. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never wanted to come here,'' Sharpe said. ``Now I've got to  
fly back 17 hours with this and even if I get to play I know I'm 
going to be sore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sharpe said he hopes to play Sunday against San Diego in the  
Olympic stadium, but said even that wouldn't cheer him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm having a bad week, not just a bad day,'' Sharpe said. ``I  
hate the place, the people are rude and I couldn't get a taxi for 
20 minutes. None of them would stop for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shannahan said he did not think Sharpe needed to be sent for an  
MRI on the ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's very serious, at least the doctors say they  
don't think it is very serious,'' Shanahan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone rolled on the back of his leg and initially we weren't  
sure if it was the knee or the ankle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shanahan said the Broncos would take no risks with Sharpe's  
injury but that they will play him if he recovers in time. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharpe, 31, is preparing for his 10th season with the Broncos,  
has produced three 1,000-yard receiving seasons, matching an NFL 
record. He played in his seventh straight Pro Bowl last year after 
leading the NFL in receiving yards as a tight end. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharpe lashed out at NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue after the  
team touched down in Australia on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one should be made to have to fly 17 hours and play a  
football game,'' Sharpe said. ``I'm sorry, Mr. Tagliabue. You need 
to address this in our upcoming meetings. This is utterly 
ridiculous.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
